<FIRST>r a AM-ChicagoMayoral     01-24 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evans Files Third-Party Candidacy For April Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alderman Timothy Evans, bypassing the Democratic
primary in favor of a third-party bid for mayor, submitted 100,000
petition signatures Monday for a spot on the April 4 election ballot.
   Evans, running under the Harold Washington Party, named for the
city's first black mayor, said he turned in four times the number of
names needed to qualify a third-party candidacy for mayor.
   ``What you see is a testament to the thousands of people who
participated, who passed the petitions, who signed the petitions,''
Evans told a crowd of 200 supporters at City Hall.
   He is skipping the Democratic primary to avoid splitting the
black vote with Mayor Eugene Sawyer. Evans and Sawyer are both black.
   Unless the petition signatures fail to withstand challenges,
Evans will meet the winners of the Democratic and Republican
primaries in an election that will determine who serves the
remaining two years in Washington's term.
   While filing his petitions, he pledged to reform what he called
the remnants of the political ``machine'' of late Mayor Richard J.
Daley, who died 12 years ago.
   Daley's son, Cook County State's Attorney Ricard M. Daley, is the
Democratic front-runner, attracting support from whites, Hispanics
and some blacks, but Sawyer appears to be chipping away at the lead,
according to polls.
   ``We don't know who our opponents will be, but we've got to
defeat the Daley machine,'' Evans said.
   Washington suffered a heart attack and died in November 1987.
Evans was his floor leader in the City Council.
</TEXT>
