<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--China-Crime     01-24 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--China-Crime,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharp Rise In Crime; Economic Development Blamed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crime rose sharply last year _ in part because of
economic development _ with serious crimes such as murder and
robbery increasing 65.7 percent, the vice minister of public
security was quoted today as saying.
   Vice Minister Yu Lei said 827,000 crimes were reported last year,
up 45.1 percent from 1987, the official China Daily newspaper
reported.
   He said 80 percent of all the crimes were theft.
   Yu blamed the crime increase on economic development which made
more goods and money available to some people, and on the country's
transient population _ peddlers, construction workers and drifters _
now estimated at 50 million.
   Yu said drug trafficking and smuggling by ``overseas gangs'' also
increased, but China still has one of the lowest crime rates in the
world.
</TEXT>
