<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     01-24 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Rain Man' and `Twins' Top Box Office Draw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Rain Man'' and ``Twins'' had the highest box
office receipts for the sixth straight weekend as many would-be
moviegoers stayed home to watch the Super Bowl.
   Three weeks into the new year, it was also evident that studios
were intent on wringing out the old. There were no new releases in
the weekly top 10, and movies on the list have been in circulation
an average six weeks.
   Holding on handily to No. 1 was the Dustin Hoffman-Tom Cruise
film ``Rain Man,'' which took in $7 million in its sixth week of
release for a gross of $79.5 million.
   ``Twins,'' with Arnold Schwarzenegger and Danny DeVito as
brothers separated at birth, finished second with $4.82 million and
a seven-week gross of $80.4 million.
   It was the fourth straight weekend that the films finished in
that order. The previous two weekends, ``Twins'' finished ahead of
``Rain Man.''
   A female duo in ``Beaches,'' starring Bette Midler and Barbara
Hershey, took third place with $4.79 million. ``The Accidental
Tourist'' was fourth with $3.3 million.
   Fifth place went to ``Working Girl'' at $3.1 million.
   ``The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!'' was sixth,
``Mississippi Burning'' was seventh and ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels''
was eighth.
   The newest entry in the top 10 was ``Deep Star Six,'' barely
hanging on with a $1.39 million gross at No. 9 in its second week of
release.
   Rounding out the list was Disney's animated film ``Oliver and
Co.,'' which has taken in $48.1 million after 10 weeks.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Rain Man,'' United Artists, $7 million, 1,509 screens,
$4,641 per screen, $79.5 million, six weeks.
   2. ``Twins,'' Universal, $4.82 million, 1,640 screens, $2,940 per
screen, $80.4 million, seven weeks.
   3. ``Beaches,'' Disney, $4.79 million, 809 screens, $5,921 per
screen, $13.2 million, five weeks.
   4. ``The Accidental Tourist,'' Warner Bros., $3.3 million, 954
screens, $3,474 per screen, $18.3 million, five weeks.
   5. ``Working Girl,'' 20th Century Fox, $3.1 million, 1,148
screens, $2,681 per screen, $34.2 million, five weeks.
   6. ``The Naked Gun,'' Paramount, $3 million, 1,687 screens,
$1,796 per screen, $64.5 million, eight weeks.
   7. ``Mississippi Burning,'' Orion, $2.7 million, 568 screens,
$4,674 per screen, $10.1 million, seven weeks.
   8. ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels,'' Orion, $2.1 million, 1,515
screens, $1,391 per screen, $34.1 million, six weeks.
   9. ``Deep Star Six,'' Tri-Star, $1.39 million, 1,118 screens,
$1,227 per screen, $5.6 million, two weeks.
   10. ``Oliver and Co.,'' Disney, $1.37 million, 1,454 screens,
$944 per screen, $48.1 million, 10 weeks.
</TEXT>
