<FIRST>u a AM-SeaRescue     01-24 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sea Rescue,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple In 80s Found After Missing At Sea Five Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple in their 80s who had been
missing at sea for almost five days _ four of them without food or
fresh water _ were plucked from an island on the South Carolina
coast by a Marine helicopter Monday.
   ``I'm telling you it was worth all the tea in China'' to see that
helicopter, Thomas Pettigrew, 81, said from a hospital bed at
Beaufort Memorial Hospital where he and his 80-year-old wife, Katie,
were listed in fair condition.
   The Pettigrews left Charleston early Thursday on a day-long
fishing trip in their 18-foot fiberglass boat.
   After being blown out to sea, running out of gas and being tossed
about in 12-foot waves, the craft washed up late Saturday on Bay
Point Island, about 50 miles southwest of Charleston.
   The couple were spotted Monday afternoon by a helicopter on a
training exercise from the Marine Corps Air Station in Beaufort,
authorities said.
   They were transported to the hospital by the helicopter, said
Petty Officer James Turner of the Charleston Coast Guard Base.
   The Coast Guard had started a search of the offshore waters
Friday after the couple were reported overdue at the Lockwood
Municipal Marina. But the search was suspended late Sunday.
   A storm system that moved through the area over the weekend
brought winds of 25 to 45 mph. Temperatures dropped to 35 degrees in
Charleston early Sunday.
   ``Considering the fact that they have had no food for four days
and significant exposure, I think they're doing great,'' said Dr.
Lester Haddad, the director of the emergency room at the hospital.
   ``When they got to the hospital, the first thing we gave them was
a good meal,'' he added.
   He said the couple would remain in the hospital at least
overnight for observation and treatment for exposure.
   Pettigrew said he never gave up hope through the ordeal with his
wife of 44 years.
   ``No, I always had hope. I didn't give up my hopes,'' he said.
   Pettigrew added he had no doubt the couple would be rescued when
they washed ashore on the island.
   ``I wasn't afraid of anything no more once I got on that
island,'' he said. ``I knew I was on dry land. I was hoping I would
get something to eat.''
   Lt. Quain Kahler of the Coast Guard said there was a caretaker's
cottage on the uninhabited island about 500 yards off the beach
where the couple could have gotten food. But he said the couple
didn't know it was there.
   Haddad said the couple is doing well and ``it's nice to have a
happy story to report for once.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
