<FIRST>r w PM-CocaineSeizures     01-24 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Seizures,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Turns Up In Fruit Pulp, Anchovies and Beeswax, Customs Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine mixed up in shipments of fruit pulp and
anchovies were among U.S. Customs Service discoveries that led to
record seizures in the past three months.
   ``A lot of it is coming in by ship, which have these tremendously
huge containers,'' Customs spokesman Dennis Shimkoski said Monday as
he announced seizures of almost 23 tons of cocaine in the first
quarter of fiscal 1989.
   ``Sometimes it's in hollowed-out lumber,'' he said. ``We've found
it in shipments of beeswax, fruit pulp, industrial gear boxes,
anchovies and false walls of containers.''
   Occasionally, bags of the drug were interspersed in huge
containers of items such as chocolates, bulk lumber and fruit pulp,
but sometimes the cocaine was just mixed in with such cargo,
requiring it to be cooked out later, he said.
   ``With the technology that they use, the sky's the limit on what
they'll try next,'' said Shimkoski.
   According to Customs figures announced Monday, the service seized
45,530 pounds of cocaine _ just short of 23 tons _ between Oct. 1
and Dec. 31, 1988, which is the first quarter of fiscal 1989. That
was 11,276 more pounds than in the same months in 1987, a one-third
increase, he said.
   Much of the cocaine found mixed with other cargo was discovered
through the Automated Commercial System, which uses computers to
compare cargo manifests to find ``who the high-risk importers might
be, or the high-risk imports,'' Shimkoski said.
   For the entire 1988 fiscal year, which ended Sept. 30, 1988,
customs officers took in a record high 138,808 pounds of cocaine,
nearly as much as they took in the two previous years combined.
   The Drug Enforcement Administration is estimating that cocaine
production overseas is decreasing in fiscal 1989 from a high in
fiscal 1988.
   This would mean that the dramatic increase in seizures by Customs
in the first quarter of fiscal 1989 reflected an actual cut in the
amount of cocaine coming in, not just a cut in a much larger supply,
said DEA spokesman Maurice Hill.
   ``Without a doubt,'' it's a cut in imports, Hill said. ``But you
realize with the numbers we're dealing with, it's not a dent.''
   In fiscal 1989, production of finished cocaine by the four major
producing countries _ Colombia, Peru, Bolivia and Ecuador _ will
range from 708,400 pounds to 919,600 pounds, according to DEA
estimates.
   Meanwhile, the Customs Service's 21 international mail branches
in fiscal 1988 seized record quantities of other drugs _ heroin,
opium and marijuana, Shimkoski said.
   Those branches seized 164 pounds of heroin, compared with just 23
pounds in fiscal 1987, he said. Meanwhile, opium seizures increased
from 1,019 pounds to 1,600 pounds, and marijuana seizures increased
from 1,141 to 1,310 pounds. There were no significant amounts of
cocaine mailed, he said.
   To increase such seizures in the future, the Customs Service is
cooperating with the Postal Service on a program in which mail from
29 high-risk drug sources countries would be cleared at the port of
arrival.
   ``This will prevent ground transfers to inland destinations,
eliminates potential monkey business'' that could occur if the bags
were not checked immediately, Shimkoski said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
