<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra     01-24 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Examines More Classified Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An interagency intelligence panel in the Bush
administration could determine whether additional criminal charges
are dropped against fired National Security aide Oliver L. North.
   The group began its review after U.S. District Judge Gerhard
Gesell issued a sealed order last Thursday detailing how much
classified information must be disclosed by the defense in order for
North to get a fair trial.
   No final decisions have been made, sources familiar with the
process said Monday, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   An earlier review by the interagency group led to dismissal of
conspiracy and theft charges against North in the closing weeks of
the Reagan administration. That review was of documents prosecutors
planned to use against North.
   The interagency group concluded in that earlier review that due
to national security concerns it would not declassify much of the
material which Gesell ordered must be disclosed at trial. Gesell
declined to reconsider his decision requiring extensive disclosure
and as a result, independent counsel Lawrence Walsh sought dismissal
of the conspiracy and theft charges.
   The detail Gesell said must be disclosed after that earlier
review included verbatim texts of various intelligence reports and
the names of five Central American countries and Israel. Foreign
leaders were to be identified by relative rank and field of
activity, though not be name.
   Gesell has limited the defense to presenting 300 classified
documents, the same number that would be presented by Walsh's office
to prosecute North in the Iran-Contra case.
   Twelve criminal charges remain against North.
   Nine of the 12 counts focus on North's efforts to conceal from
Congress and former Attorney General Edwin Meese III his efforts on
behalf of the Contras fighting the leftist government of Nicaragua.
Four of the nine counts deal with alleged concealment of the
diversion of money to the Contras from the administration's secret
arms sales to Iran.
   North also is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 security
system at his home from co-defendant Richard Secord, converting to
his own use at least $4,300 in travelers checks from Contra leader
Adolfo Calero and conspiring to defraud the Treasury of tax revenue
in connection with charitable contributions supporting the Contras.
   The conspiracy and theft counts that were dropped accused North
of illegally diverting to the Contras more than $14 million in
proceeds from the Reagan administration's arms sales to Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
