<FIRST>r w PM-CoastalPollution     01-24 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coastal Pollution,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Report Suggests Fees on Coastal Polluters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study by two congressional subcommittees
recommends imposing fees on companies that dump toxic wastes and
other pollutants into the nation's coastal waters.
   A fee system would ``create powerful economic incentives'' for
companies to reduce the amount of wastes dumped into oceans, bays
and estuaries while raising money to pay for new environmental
programs, according to the report released Monday.
   The fees would be imposed on companies that are meeting federal
regulatory standards, which allow some dumping. Companies found to
be illegally dumping toxic wastes and other pollutants already are
subject to criminal penalties, including fines.
   The 48-page report, released by Rep. Gerry E. Studds, D-Mass.,
stems from nine hearings held during the past two years by the House
Merchant Marine and Fisheries subcommittee on fisheries and the
environment, headed by Studds, and the oceanography subcommittee.
   The panels painted a bleak picture of the state of the nation's
coastal waters.
   ``The continuing damage to coastal resources from pollution,
development and natural forces raises serious doubts about the
ability of our estuaries, bays and near coastal waters to survive
these stresses,'' the subcommittees wrote.
   ``If we fail to act and if current trends continue unabated, what
is now a serious, widespread collection of problems may coalesce
into a national crisis by early in the next century.''
   The subcommittees warned against ``quick fixes'' and noted that
installing ``an effective and fair fee system'' would be difficult.
They did not offer specifics.
   ``Many variations and alternatives should be examined. But the
twin imperatives of increasing funds for pollution control and
decreasing wastes justify the effort,'' the report said.
   The study said spending for marine research and monitoring
decreased during the Reagan administration from a 1981 level of more
than $150 million to about $110 million last year.
   ``For the past eight years we have tried to defend past
accomplishments against the encroachments of a hostile
administration,'' Studds said. ``Today, we have ... a president who
campaigned from Boston Harbor to the Jersey Shore to Santa Barbara
as an environmentalist. And we have both the opportunity, and an
urgent national need, to reverse the tide of coastal degradation and
move forward once again.''
   The subcommittees recommended development of a national coastal
protection policy, increased funding levels, stricter pollution
enforcement efforts and new incentives for voluntary compliance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
