<DOCNO> AP890124-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Gotti     01-24 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gotti,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reputed Mob Leader Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Gotti, the reputed head of the Gambino
organized-crime family, and two of his associates were arrested
Monday night on charges they had ordered a union leader shot three
years ago.
   Gotti was arrested while walking with his bodyguard in
Manhattan's Little Italy section about 5:30 p.m. and charged with
first-degree assault and conspiracy, said District Attorney Robert
Morgenthau.
   Gotti was arraigned before Manhattan Criminal Court Judge
Patricia Williams, who ordered him held without bail.
   An indictment by a grand jury was expected to be unsealed Tuesday.
   The other defendants arrested on the same charges were Angelo
Ruggiero and Anthony Guerrieri.
   The FBI has identified Ruggiero, 48, as a captain in the Gambino
group and Guerrieri, 60, as a ``soldier.''
   The FBI and other New York state law enforcement officials have
said that Gotti, 48, heads the Gambino family syndicate, which is
believed to be the largest and most powerful organized crime group
in the country.
   Assistant District Attorney Michael Cherkasky declined to comment
on the charges. But sources said the sealed indictment involves the
shooting on May 7, 1986, of John O'Connor, vice president and
business manager of Carpenters Union Local 608.
   O'Connor was shot several times in the buttocks in what
investigators said was retaliation for his having ordered vandalism
in 1986 at a restaurant using non-union carpenters. O'Connor
apparently was unaware that the owners were friends of Gotti.
   Morgenthau's office said law enforcement officials overheard
Gotti, via a court-ordered listening device, talk about killing a
union leader shortly before O'Connor was wounded.
   The contract for killing O'Connor allegedly was given to James
Coonan, the reputed leader of the Westies, a gang that operated on
Manhattan's West Side. Some of the gang members are expected to be
named in the indictment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
