<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     01-24 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen Tuesday,
while share prices rose sharply on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, hitting
another new high.
   The dollar closed at 126.95 yen, down 1.25 yen from the previous
day's 128.20 yen finish. The currency opened at 127.37 yen and
ranged between 126.70 and 127.55 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
162.50 points Monday, added another 224.80 points, or 0.72 percent,
closing at 31,557.68, a new high.
   Declining U.S. oil prices helped to raise the ``confidence of
investors'' who have been more concerned about oil prices than
exchange rates recently, said Seichiro Kita of Daiwa Securities, a
major Japanese brokerage.
   U.S. spot crude oil prices finished sharply lower Monday in what
appeared to be a long-awaited technical correction from the gains of
the last six weeks, with February contracts for West Texas
Intermediate crude oil ending at $17.70 a barrel, down $1.15 a
barrel from Friday.
</TEXT>
