<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     01-24 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barnes Drops Out of Race for Democratic Chairman, Endorses Brown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Michael Barnes of Maryland endorsed
Ron Brown for the chairmanship of the Democratic Party after
abandoning his own bid for the post.
   Barnes' departure Monday left four candidates vying to succeed
Paul G. Kirk Jr. as party chairman: Brown, a former party official
who played a key role in Jesse Jackson's presidential campaign;
Michigan party chairman Richard Wiener; and former Reps. Jim Jones
of Oklahoma and James Stanton of Ohio.
   ``I believe that party unity will be best served if we can unite
behind Ron, a man of proven ability, who has served in numerous
important capacities in our party, including deputy chair,'' said
Barnes.
   As Jackson's convention manager last year, Brown received a share
of the credit for the show of unity between Jackson and presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis at the Democrats' national convention.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Kennedy: Regulators Ignoring Alleged Discrimination In Mortgage</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lending
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government regulators are routinely allowing
discrimination in home mortgage lending against blacks and Hispanics
seeking to buy homes, two congressmen charged.
   ``It is inexcusable for the responsible agencies to be ignorant
of the rates of rejections for black and Hispanic home buyers,''
Rep. Joseph Kennedy II, D-Mass., said Monday. ``Now that the
evidence is before them, it is their duty to act decisively.''
   Kennedy and House Banking Committee Chairman Henry Gonzalez,
D-Texas, pointed to data from the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
obtained by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution under the Freedom of
Information Act and published in Sunday's editions.
   Statistics from 10 million loan applications from 1983 to
mid-1988 showed the rate of rejection for white applicants at the
3,100 savings and loans nationwide was 11.1 percent, while the
rejection rate for blacks was 23.7 percent and 18.2 percent for
Hispanics.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eastern Weather Satellite Repositioned after Western One Fails</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eastern weather satellite that provides
cloud pictures seen in newspapers and on television is being shifted
westward to help cover ground that had been covered by a satellite
that died from old age.
   The loss of GOES-West on Saturday leaves the nation with just one
stationary weather satellite. Another one is not due to be launched
for at least 18 months.
   Thomas M. Pyke Jr., head of satellite services at the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, said the loss leaves
meteorologists will have ``only limited coverage of Atlantic and
Pacific ocean areas where these severe storms originate.''
   The nation operated with only a western satellite from 1984 until
March 1987 because of the failure of an old eastern satellite.
</TEXT>
