<DOCNO> AP890124-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-US-Catholics-Pope     01-24 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Catholics-Pope,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope John Paul, U.S. Bishops To Meet Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II and the U.S. Catholic hierarchy, who sparred
over the issue of church dissent during the pontiff's visit to Los
Angeles in 1987, will tackle the volatile issue of U.S.-Vatican
relations in a March meeting in Rome.
   More than 30 U.S. bishops and two Eastern Rite metropolitans have
been invited to the March 8-11 meeting, which follows a year of
private discussions with U.S. bishops, the United States Catholic
Conference announced Monday.
   ``It was a good start in Los Angeles, and now we hope to make it
a little more in-depth,'' said Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis,
president of the National Conference of Catholic bishops. ``He is
very strong for the meeting. He wants to have it.''
   When the two sides last met in September 1987, the pope
challenged American bishops to crack down on dissenters from church
teaching, while the U.S. bishops told the pontiff an authoritarian
approach alienates many of the country's 53 million Catholics.
   In his talk, the pope decried reports that many Catholics veer
from official teaching on issues such as sexual morality and divorce.
   ``It is sometimes claimed that dissent from the Magisterium is
totally compatible with being a `good Catholic' and poses no
obstacle to the reception of the sacraments. This is a grave error
that challenges the teaching office of the bishops of the United
States and elsewhere,'' the pope said.
   But Archbishop Rembert G. Weakland of Milwaukee told the pope
that in the United States, ``The faithful are more inclined to look
at the intrinsic worth of an argument proposed by the teachers in
the church than to accept it on the basis of the authority itself.''
In many cases, he said, ``an authoritarian style is
counterproductive, and such authority for the most part then becomes
ignored.''
   Archbishop John R. Quinn of San Francisco said he recognized the
pope's concerns, but ``we cannot fulfill our task simply by an
uncritical application of solutions designed in past ages for
problems which have qualitatively changed or which did not exist in
the past.''
   The state of U.S.-Vatican relations had fallen to the point in
November 1986 that Bishop James Malone, then-president of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, called for a meeting
between U.S. leaders and the Vatican to discuss the ``growing and
dangerous disaffection'' of American Catholics from the Holy See.
   In his letter this month to U.S. bishops, the pope said he was
aware of their ``keen interest'' in meeting with him as a group.
   The letter did not set a specific agenda, but said the theme of
the meeting would be ``evangelization in the context of the culture
and society of the United States, with particular emphasis on the
role of the bishop as the teacher of faith.''
   May said in a telephone interview that the topic will be similar
to the issues raised in Los Angeles in 1987, but ``that was just a
beginning.''
   He said the climate of U.S.-Vatican relations has changed since
Malone made his appeal at the bishops' meeting following the papal
visit.
   For example, he said, Seattle Archbishop Raymond Hunthausen, who
had been unilaterally stripped of some of his authority by the
Vatican for alleged abuses, has regained effective control of the
archdiocese and is the one delegates to the papal meeting in March.
   ``I personally think that things are much more even right now and
much more peaceful than at the time Bishop Malone made his
suggestion,'' Archbishop May said. ``I think things are on a nice,
even keel.''
   Archbishop May also noted that the pope has largely praised the
U.S. church during the bishops' private meetings with the pope
throughout last year. The meetings were part of the required ``ad
limina'' visits all episcopal leaders must make to Rome every five
years.
   He said the pontiff ``paid tribute'' to Mass attendance in the
United States, the schools and social service programs run by the
church and the bishops' pastoral letters on peace and the economy.
Among the problems cited by the pope during the ``ad limina'' visits
were a lack of appreciation of penance, inappropriate use of
eucharistic ministers to give communion and a need to recruit more
vocations, May said.
   The U.S. delegation also plans to make its own points in Rome,
May said.
   ``We do believe that it will be helpful for the holy father as
well to know more about the culture and society where we work,'' May
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
