<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AK-47Shootings     01-24 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AK-47 Shootings,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Wounds Two Fellow Workers, Kills Self At Car Dealership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with a history of mental problems
wounded two co-workers at a car dealership when he opened fire with
an AK-47 assault rifle on customers and employees before killing
himself, police said.
   The body of Willie Howard Womack Jr., 26, of Virginia Beach, was
found Monday in the office of a service garage at Kimnach Ford. Near
his body was the rifle and a derringer, said police Cpl. Robert P.
Haynes.
   Heavily armed police had surrounded the garage and tried to
contact Womack for more than six hours before they lobbed tear gas
canisters into the building and went inside.
   Womack's sister, Angela, had tried to contact her brother over an
intercom after police efforts to reach him by telephone and bullhorn
failed. But he apparently had been dead during what police thought
was a standoff, said Haynes.
   Womack, who cleaned cars and ran errands at the dealership, had
been at work for a while before the shooting broke out, Haynes said.
   ``One of his co-workers said he came into work as happy as
ever,'' he said. Police disclosed no motive for the shootings.
   ``He said everybody at work had been picking on him lately,''
said Womack's mother, Nancy Condrey. She said her son had some
previous mental problems, had sought professional help and been on
medication.
   Wounded in the assault were Barry Graham, 32, and William
Bidlack, 33. Graham was hospitalized in serious but stable condition
with a wound in the leg and Bidlack was in satisfactory condition
with a hand wound. Both worked in the body shop.
   The service garage and several cars in the parking lot were
riddled with bullets.
   Dealership owner Peggy Kimnach said Womack had worked there for
five years and was a ``good employee.''
   A mechanic, Wayne Gravitt, described Womack as quiet. ``Nobody
really knows him,'' he said.
   ``We was very flaky, but we never thought he was dangerous. In
fact, we felt kind of sorry for him,'' said Leo Shelor, another
mechanic.
   Donna Morris, 26, of Virginia Beach, had left her car for
servicing and was waiting outside for a taxi when the shooting began.
   ``It sounded like firecrackers,'' she said. ``All of a sudden the
service doors opened and everybody just came piling out.''
   A female employee told her to run because ``somebody had gone
berserk in there with a gun.''
   Monday's shooting was the nation's second in a week involving an
AK-47. On Jan. 17, 24-year-old Patrick Edward Purdy fired more than
100 rounds from an AK-47 semi-automatic assault rifle outside the
grade school he once attended in Stockton, Calif., killing five
children and wounding 29 others and a teacher before killing himself.
</TEXT>
