<DOCNO> AP890124-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     01-24 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Factions Clash In South Lebanon, 4 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias battled anew
in south Lebanon today while their leaders met with Syrian and
Iranian officials in Damascus to seek an end to the bloodshed.
   Police said four people were killed and 14 wounded in the
fighting between the Syrian-backed Amal militia and the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   That raised the casualty toll since the latest spasm of violence
erupted Dec. 31 to at least 172 killed and 332 wounded.
   The fighting began with artillery exchanges late Monday,
shattering a four-day cease-fire. It centered on Hezbollah's
stronghold on the western edge of Israel's self-designated
``security zone.''
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said both sides launched attacks against each others'
positions, but neither gained any territory.
   The fighting died down into intermittent mortar exchanges around
daybreak.
   Amal said in a statement that Hezbollah fighters started the
fighting by attacking its positions in the hamlets of Kfar Filla and
Jarjoua. The towns are west and southwest of the triangular-shaped
mountain enclave controlled by the Iranian-backed militia.
   ``The Hezbollah attacks were repulsed,'' the Amal statement said.
It gave no other details.
   Hezbollah accused Amal of attacking its fighters in the villages
of Jbaa and Ein Bouswar in an attempt to sabotage efforts by Iran
and Syria to end the nine-month confrontation between their unruly
Lebanese surrogates.
   By police count, more than 500 people have been killed and 1,500
wounded since April in battles between the two factions for control
of Lebanon's 1 million Shiites, the country's largest sect.
   A Hezbollah communique said the Amal assaults were ``crushed and
the attackers pushed back.''
   The statement warned Amal against ``maintaining a hostile
attitude and blocking efforts to achieve a comprehensive political
settlement.''
   In the Syrian capital, Syrian and Iranian envoys worked today on
achieving a peace formula acceptable to their proxies.
   Syria's Foreign Minister, Farouk Sharaa and his Iranian
counterpart, Ali Akbar Velayati, held a series of meetings Monday
with Amal leader Nabih Berri and Hezbollah representatives Sheik
Ibrahim Amin and Hussein Musavi.
   Berri told reporters Amal will not agree to a settlement until
Hezbollah hands over the assassins of three Amal commanders.
   Amal has accused Hezbollah of killing Daoud Daoud, its leader in
south Lebanon, and two senior lieutenants in a street ambush in
south Beirut on Sept. 22. Hezbollah denies involvement.
   The Iranian-backed fundamentalists advocate the creation of an
Iranian-style Islamic republic in Lebanon. The more secular and
nationalist Amal seeks a government in Lebanon in which Moslems
would have an equal share of power with the once dominant Christians.
   The Shiite battles have strained the relations between Iran and
Syria, Tehran's main Arab ally in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war
with Iraq that an Aug. 20 cease-fire brought to a halt.
</TEXT>
