<DOCNO> AP890124-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     01-24 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Spreads From Northern Rockies To Plains; East, South Unseasonably
Warm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow spread from the northern Rockies to the Plains today,
Southern California got rain and snow, but the East and much of the
South had unseasonably warm weather.
   Snow and blowing snow continued in much of Montana and Wyoming,
and an additional 2 to 4 inches of snow was expected with 15-30 mph
winds. Snow advisories were in effect in both states. In Montana,
the snow was a foot deep in Bozeman and 10 inches deep in Buttle and
Billings.
   The snow spread into South Dakota and western Nebraska. Freezing
drizzle iced roads in the northwest panhandle of Nebraska and the
north-central part of the state.
   The rain scattered over Southern California turned into snow in
the mountains. A snow advisory was issued for the mountains, and
local accumulations of 4 to 8 inches were possible.
   Showers were scattered in eastern Texas and western Louisiana.
   Unseasonably mild weather continued from the lower Great Lakes
region to the middle Mississippi Valley and the southern Plains.
Temperatures were above freezing across much of the region this
morning. Normally, low temperatures across the Great Lakes are in
the single digits and teens.
   Today's forecast called for scattered rain over the lower
Mississippi Valley and western Tennessee, rain from Southern
California to western Arizona and southern Utah, with snow in the
mountains of Southern California and Utah; snow in the central
Rockies and western sections of the northern Plains; and rain in
western Washington state.
   High temperatures were predicted in the teens and 20s in the
northern Rockies, northern Plains, much of Nebraska, the upper
Mississippi Valley and the northern Great Lakes; the 20s in northern
Maine; the 30s and 40s from the northern Pacific Coast to the
central Rockies, the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles, the middle
Mississippi Valley, the lower Great Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley and
the Atlantic Coast from New Jersey to New England; the 70s from the
Gulf Coast to the southern Atlantic Coast; and in the 50s and 60s in
the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees below zero at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 67 degrees at
Brownsville, Texas.
