<DOCNO> AP890124-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SovietQuake-Buildings     01-24 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Quake-Buildings,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Building Improvements May Have Limited Tadzhikistan Death Toll</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some residents of the earthquake-stricken
Soviet republic of Tadzhikistan may owe their lives to use of
relatively lightweight concrete roofing used in the region, a
scientist said.
   ``This is something Tadzhikistan engineers took pride in _
lighter weight roofs (of thin, corrugated concrete), and their
encouragement of the use of this kind of building practice,'' Brian
Tucker, California's acting state geologist, said Monday. Tucker has
made extensive studies in the region.
   Early reports from the Soviet news agency Tass indicated about
1,000 people died because of the quake in the Central Asian republic
Monday, at least 600 of them in the farming settlement of Sharora,
one of at least three villages buried by a 50-foot-high slide of
dirt and mud.
   Because the landslide appears to be the biggest killer in the
quake, ``it seems that the majority of people would have died
regardless of the type of roof they had over their head,'' Tucker
said.
   ``But of the people who weren't buried in mud, probably fewer
died due to the collapse of thick ceilings than would have without
the current practice of lightweight roofs,'' Tucker speculated by
phone from Washington, where he was attending a conference.
   Tucker said the improved building practices stemmed from a large
earthquake in 1949, which killed roughly 20,000 people and was
centered east of Dushanbe, Tadzhikistan's capital. Monday's tremor
was centered 20 to 30 miles southwest of Dushanbe.
   Like Monday's quake, which measured a moderate 5.4 on the Richter
scale, the 1949 jolt triggered a huge landslide, Tucker said, adding
that it buried the town of Khait, roughly 50 miles east of Dushanbe.
   The quake 40 years ago prompted the Soviet Academy of Sciences to
establish a permanent research expedition in the town of Garm. The
seismologists and engineers gained better understanding of seismic
risks, started quake prediction efforts and improved building
practices, Tucker said.
   ``One of the little things they could do for these rural
communities was to make these thin, corrugated cement roofs instead
of the thick mud and rock roofs'' traditionally used atop one-story
adobe homes, he said.
   Tucker said because such roofs are common now, the danger of
death from building collapse during Tadzhikistan quakes ``is much
less now than it used to be.''
   Tucker visited Garm more than a dozen times between 1975 and 1983
as part of a U.S.-Soviet exchange program. He studied how shaking
was much more intense on loose soils than on solid rock.
   ``This is important because most dwellings are on sediment-filled
valleys,'' he said. ``All buildings are built there on loose soil.''
   The villages are vulnerable to landslides because they ``are just
nestled in narrow valleys'' in the rugged Pamir and Tien Shan
mountain ranges, he added.
   Tucker said the mountains were uplifted by the collision of India
northward into China and Central Asia. The collision produced a zone
of seismic activity that stretches from Tadzhikistan on the west to
Burma on the east, he said.
   Tucker said Dushanbe, with some 460,000 residents, has
multi-story buildings, mostly made of concrete slabs loosely hooked
together. He speculated they apparently escaped serious damage
because of the city's distance from the quake's epicenter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
