<FIRST>r a PM-ReluctantMayor     01-24 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reluctant Mayor,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council Decides To Run Town Without Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HICO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This central Texas town has been without a
mayor since July, and City Council has decided it can stay that way
for a while.
   Council members were forced to decide Monday night after the man
who was elected mayor Saturday announced he wouldn't take the job.
   Glenn Marshall, who won on a write-in vote, didn't run for the
post and said afterward that he'd rather be on the City Council than
be mayor. The mayor does not vote on city matters except to break
ties.
   ``The council set out new policies in June of last year and the
mayor really doesn't have a lot of power now in the city except as
just a figurehead,'' said the city secrtary, Mary Scott.
   Marshall was elected mayor when 41 of the 66 voters in the
special election wrote his name on the ballot, which contained no
candidates for mayor. The rest of the votes were scattered among
nine other non-candidates.
   Marshall had been acting mayor since J.M. Blakley resigned after
serving for only two months.
   An election was called to fill the vacancy, but no one filed for
the position. Marshall said any potential candidates probably shied
away from running because of ``too much regulation _ state and
federal _ down the road.''
   The next mayoral election in Hico, which is about 65 miles
southwest of Fort Worth, will be in May.
</TEXT>
