<FIRST>u i PM-SovietQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0463 01-24 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Quake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0463,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Losing Hope They Will Find Survivors In Soviet Quake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with fears of new mudslides, rescuers losing
hope, other details. No pickup. CHANGES byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers probed with bulldozers and shovels today
for survivors in the soggy mass of dirt and rock an earthquake sent
crashing into three Central Asian mountain villages, but expected
only to find bodies.
   The official Tass news agency estimated 1,000 people were killed
in slides loosened by the tremor as it struck a rich agricultural
region of the Soviet republic of Tadzhikistan before dawn Monday.
   ``There is little hope (of finding survivors) because of the
flood of dirt and mud,'' Erkin Kasimov, a spokesman for the
republic's foreign ministry, said today. ``But while there is any
hope, the rescuers will keep working.''
   Official reports said more than 100 people were hospitalized in
the Tadzhik capital of Dushanbe, 20 miles from where the Soviet
Union's second devastating earthquake in two months had caused the
most destruction.
   Vitaly Zhukov, deputy head of the republic's official news
agency, said 11 people died during the night in Dushanbe hospitals.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda blamed the conditions for
mudslides on heavy snows followed by a thaw in hills overlooking the
stricken villages of Sharora, Okuli-Bolo and Okuli-Poyen.
   The thaw moistened the earthen walls of canals that stretched
down to the villages and when the quake hit, the rich earth loosened
and Pravda said it ``moved in a huge mass onto the villages'' _
about 1{ to 1\ miles.
   ``There is a danger of new mudslides in similar places in the
event of a new natural blow,'' the paper said.
   Pravda said previous experience had shown that the Soviet Union
is careless in construction of buildings, especially in rural areas.
However, it did not specifically blame poor construction for any of
the deaths in the area about 1,800 miles southeast of Moscow.
   Poorly constructed apartment buildings have been blamed for many
of the estimated 25,000 deaths in the earthquake that struck
northwestern Armenia Dec. 7. That quake registered 6.9 on the
Richter scale.
   The U.S. Geological Survey said Monday's quake measured 5.4 on
the scale.
   Rescue workers labored today under sunny skies in 50-degree
temperatures in the three adjacent villages, digging with shovels,
bulldozers, cranes and earthmovers, Kasimov said.
   He said the quake and mudslide also damaged farms, homes,
schools, stores and administrative buildings outside the three
villages.
   Zhukov said many of the surviving women and children had been
evacuated, but some remained behind in hopes of finding relatives.
   Rescue workers put up round reinforced tents and built small
wooden huts for survivors and worked to restore communications and
electricity to the area, he said. Food and fuel were also sent to
the scene, Tass said.
   Zainiddin Nasreddinov, editor in chief of the Tadzhik news
agency, estimated that about 600 people were killed in Sharora _
almost the entire population.
   The 40-second tremor was centered 20 to 30 miles southwest of
Dushanbe, a city of more than 460,000 people, Tass said. The area is
in the fertile Gissar district, a vineyard and livestock-raising
center.
   The earthquake unhinged a wall of loess at least five miles wide
that buried Okuli-Bolo and much of Sharora, said Kasimov. Officials
said most of the victims were asleep at the time.
   Residents of Okuli-Poyen, apparently roused in time, fled in
panic before the slide could reach their homes, Kasimov said from
Dushanbe.
   In Okuli-Bolo and Okuli-Poyen, ``everything is destroyed _ all
the homes, the schools, the hospitals and clinics, the stores,''
Nasreddinov said.
   Okuli-Bolo is a ``heap of rubble'' and the chairman of a local
economic cooperative, Hairrulo Yuldashev, said the households of 70
peasant families were ``completely demolished and buried by the
landslide,'' Tass said.
   The TV news program ``Vremya'' showed aerial footage of Sharora,
with white roofs of buried homes peeking through the dirt like
seashells scattered on a beach.
   The Kremlin leadership sent condolences and promised aid.
According to Nasreddinov, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev telephoned
Tadzhikistan officials to promise Moscow's help.
</TEXT>
