<FIRST>r a PM-SludgeSite     01-24 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sludge Site,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shipyard Recommended As Sludge Processing Site In Boston Harbor Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quincy residents won't smell a thing, but officials
in the suburb say they still will fight a proposal to build one of
the country's biggest sewage sludge processing plants.
   A recommendation to build the plant at the defunct Fore River
Shipyard was announced Monday by Massachusetts Water Resources
Authority head Paul Levy, who said the process _ which turns waste
into compost instead of burning it _ wouldn't give off an odor.
   ``I don't propose to build anything unless I would feel
comfortable living next door to it,'' Levy said.
   But Quincy officials on Monday conferred on ways to fight the
proposal. And the federal Environmental Protection Agency planned to
ask a federal judge to require the authority to build a backup
sludge incinerator, said Paul Keough, deputy EPA regional
administrator.
   According to Levy, the processing plant would be one of the
nation's largest, comparable in size to plants in Akron, Ohio, and
Los Angeles.
   The full water resources authority's board is expected to approve
Levy's recommendation Feb. 1.
   Cost and convenience were the chief reasons for choosing the
shipyard, Levy said. The authority already owns the property, unlike
the two other proposed sites: Spectacle Island in Boston Harbor and
a 90-acre site in Stoughton, another suburb south of Boston.
   The shipyard already has been scheduled for a temporary sludge
treatment plant beginning in 1991. The permanent plant is scheduled
for completion in 1995.
   The $193 million estimated cost of building and operating a
sludge plant over 25 years compares to $208 million for the
Stoughton site and $258 million for Spectacle Island.
   Quincy City Councilor Michael Cheney has already said he plans to
urge the city to sue to battle the proposal. The chief concerns
among officials in Quincy and neighboring Weymouth are excess
traffic and odor.
   State Rep. Robert Cerasoli, whose district includes the shipyard,
blamed Quincy Mayor Francis X. McCauley for agreeing to allow the
authority to use the shipyard as a temporary sludge treatment site.
   ``I didn't think that after five years they'd abandon the interim
plant,'' Cerasoli said.
</TEXT>
