<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Scandal     01-24 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Member Resigns Over Links to Company in Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's senior economic planner resigned today, the
third Cabinet member to step down in less than two months in
connection with a stock-trading scandal that has shaken public
confidence in the government.
   The resignation of Ken Harada was expected to put heavy pressure
on several other Cabinet members, including Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita, who have acknowledged links to the company at the center
of the storm.
   Harada had led a parliamentary committee investigating the
scandal until he became head of Japan's Economic Planning Agency in
a Dec. 27 Cabinet shuffle.
   In a televised news conference following his resignation, Harada
acknowledged reports he had received regular political donations
from Recruit Co., but denied any wrongdoing and said the company had
``absolutely not asked for any favors'' in return.
   The national newspaper Asahi Shimbun reported today that Harada
had received $80 a month from Recruit for 14 years. In addition, a
Recruit subsidiary donated about $8,000 at a Harada fund-raising
party in August, it said.
   In the stock scandal, Recruit, an information conglomerate, made
available hundreds of thousands of unlisted shares in a subsidiary,
Recruit-Cosmos, to dozens of prominent people who made large profits
after the stocks were listed for public trading and rose quickly in
value.
   Neither the donations nor the stock transactions were illegal of
themselves, but questions of bribery, ethics and undue business
influence on politicians were raised.
   Only three days after Takeshita formed his new Cabinet in
December, Justice Minister Takashi Hasegawa stepped down after it
was disclosed that he also had received regular donations from
Recruit.
   A member of the previous Cabinet, Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa, stepped down in early December in connection with the
scandal.
   Miyazawa resigned after having repeatedly changed his explanation
of a close aide's purchase of the unlisted stock shares.
   Takeshita has acknowledged that an aide and a relative profited
from the sale of Recruit-Cosmos shares. News reports have said
Recruit's former chairman, Hiromasa Ezoe, also gave Takeshita's
political support group $38,000 in 1987 and 1988.
   Kyodo News Service reported that Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo
Obuchi has received $160 a month from Recruit, and Agriculture
Minister Tsutomu Hata has acknowledged that Recruit bought tickets
for a fund-raising party in 1986 at an undisclosed price.
   Obuchi, who serves as chief government spokesman, told reporters
today that the Cabinet would launch a thorough investigation into
ties between Recruit and Cabinet members.
</TEXT>
