<FIRST>u a PM-BundyMother 1stLd-Writethru a0491 01-24 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy Mother, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0491,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bundy Wishes Mother Goodbye: `There Was a Part of Me That People
Didn't Know'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 1 graf to UPDATE with execution; pickup 2nd graf
pvs, ```He kept ...'''; LaserPhoto TAC1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five hours before his execution today, Ted
Bundy called to tell his mother goodbye and sounded ``wonderful ...
very much at peace with himself,'' she said.
   ``He kept saying how sorry he was, that `there was another part
of me that people didn't know,''' Louise Bundy said.
   For unexplained reasons, Bundy was allowed two 10-minute calls,
rather than the one expected by Mrs. Bundy, the Morning News Tribune
of Tacoma reported.
   At the conclusion of the second call, Mrs. Bundy told the
confessed serial killer, ``You'll always be my precious son.''
   When the first call came shortly before 11 p.m. PST, Bundy's
adoptive father, John Bundy, turned to his wife and said quietly,
``You do the talking.''
   After the initial hellos, she said, ``We just want you to know
how much we love you and always will.''
   Her voice shook with emotion. When he spoke, she rapidly wrote
down the messages he asked her to give friends and loved ones.
   ``He sounds wonderful,'' his mother said after the first call.
``He sounds very much at peace with himself.
   ``He said, `I'm so sorry I've given you all such grief ... but a
part of me was hidden all the time,' and then he said, `but the Ted
Bundy you knew also existed.' ''
   In the second call, she told him, ``We're all praying for you.''
   Later she told the friends in her living room, ``He said God's
spirit was with him.''
   The mood at the Bundy home was grieving but subdued. Mrs. Bundy
raised her voice only when asked about the death penalty.
   ``I think it's barbaric!'' she said. ``What good does it do? It's
legalized murder is all. It's not a deterrent. They've been killing
people for thousands of years (in executions) and what good has it
done?''
   Mrs. Bundy planned to be at a friend's home with family members
and her minister when the execution was carried out this morning.
   On Monday, she said she was upset her son hadn't told her about
the killings before confessing to law enforcement officials.
   ``It's a terrible thing,'' Mrs. Bundy said. ``He wasn't raised
that way. He was raised in a good, loving, caring family. We still
love and care for him, but we want to know what caused this.''
   When asked whether her son is mentally ill, Mrs. Bundy said, ``I
think he must be. He must be! How could anybody not be, and commit
those crimes?
   ``I would have liked to have known it from him ahead of time,
yes. It would have still hurt very badly, but getting it second hand
was pretty devastating.''
   Mrs. Bundy said she never had any indication that her son hated
women but believed he was jilted by a woman he loved in 1972 or
1973, perhaps triggering hatred that led to the killings.
</TEXT>
