<FIRST>u a PM-Bundy-LakeCity 1stLd-Writethru a0477 01-24 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy-Lake City, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0477,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Eager for Ordeal to End</HEAD>
<HEAD>LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Bundy executed; pickup 5th graf,
``It'll give ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many residents of this small North Florida
town expressed hope that Ted Bundy's execution today would restore
their community spirit and belief in the American judicial system.
   Bundy died in the electric chair for the 1978 rape and murder of
Lake City schoolgirl Kimberly Leach after his trials and subsequent
appeals dragged through the judicial system for years.
   ``There is no doubt there's been a tremendous erosion of public
confidence in the system because of Ted Bundy,'' said Jerry Blair,
the state attorney who prosecuted Bundy for the murder of the
12-year-old girl.
   ``It's sort of like the Super Bowl,'' Mayor Gerald Witt said
before the execution. ``We're just waiting for it to happen.
   ``It'll give everybody a feeling of relief, and make everybody
smile, to know he's finally been electrocuted. He's destroyed so
many lives ... it seems like he's just a living devil.''
   The execution will be celebrated tonight with a barbecue at the
Naked Lady tavern north of town. The owners advertised the
celebration with a sign that reads, ``We're Cooking Too.''
   A neighboring business, Weggy's Package Store on Highway 441,
displayed what has become a common slogan in Florida on its outdoor
sign, ``Buckle Up Bundy, It's the Law.''
   Although Bundy has confessed to the murders of other young women
in recent days, it's Kimberly's murder that turned this small,
crossroads community of fewer than 10,000 people into a town without
pity.
   State Trooper Ken Robinson, who found Kimberly's body in an
abandoned pig sty, planned to witness the execution, as did Blair.
   ``We'll all be better off when this is history,'' Robinson said.
   Retired school Superintendent Silas Pittman, like many residents
here, said he hoped Bundy's execution would help them again become a
town capable of forgiveness and compassion.
   ``There's no question about it, it'll be a therapeutic act,''
said Blair.
   ``A lot of people say the law of the land should be carried
out,'' said the Rev. Edwin F. Montgomery, pastor of the First
Presbyterian Church and an opponent of the death penalty. ``It's
almost like something is unfinished.''
   But Montgomery said he believes most people would have put the
tragedy behind them long ago had Bundy been sentenced to a life in
prison.
   ``Many people haven't been able to get past the anger in the
grief process,'' he said. ``We never got resolution because we're
still in the anger stage.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890124-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Bundy-StarkeScene 1stLd-Writethru a0476 01-24 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy-Starke Scene, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0476,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reluctant ``Execution Capital'' Filled With Journalists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 1 graf and SUBS last 2 grafs to UPDATE with Bundy
executed.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents expressed resentment about their
town being known as ``Execution City'' as journalists overran the
town to cover today's electrocution of confessed serial killer Ted
Bundy.
   More than 100 journalists, accompanied by satellite dishes, vans
and even mobile homes, began setting up early Monday at the former
cow pasture across from the state prison building where Bundy was
set to become the 20th convict to be executed since Florida resumed
executions nearly 10 years ago.
   ``This is the most I've seen,'' said Bob Macmaster, a state
Corrections Department spokesman. ``The media has really overflowed
the small media area we had set aside.''
   More journalists were arriving by the dozens, including some from
Western states where Bundy is linked to as many as three dozen
female victims.
   ``Bundy has been the boogeyman of the Northwest for 15 years,''
said Mary Mapes, a producer for KIRO-TV in Seattle. ``He really
inspires fear and fascination.''
   Jacksonville graphic artist George Johnson, parked just outside
the entrance to the Florida State Prison, said he had sold six dozen
T-shirts that depicted Bundy in the electric chair, with the slogan:
``Burn, Bundy, Burn.''
   Johnson said most of his sales, at $10 a shirt, were to
journalists and prison employees.
   ``They're ready to see him burn. I think he's an animal,'' said
Johnson. Johnson said he lived near Salt Lake City in the mid-1970s,
when the bodies of suspected Bundy victims there were found.
   A banner on Johnson's car advertised, ``Tuesday is Fryday.''
   People in this town of some 5,000 people have grown resentful of
their portrayal by out-of-town reporters. While the five state
prisons that lie within 20 miles are the major employers in the
area, residents point out they are 11 miles from the prison and
shouldn't be known as home of the electric chair.
   ``I feel the people of this community have the attitude of the
state,'' resident Lila Yawn said. ``I don't think they're
bloodthirsty. I think we're just like any other normal American
town.''
   Today's execution came as this city is recovering from a drug
scandal and is worried about state plans for a Jacksonville-to-Tampa
turnpike. Some businesspersons say the turnpike could either boost
the city or kill it, depending on how close it comes to the town.
   Meanwhile, at 7 a.m., as Bundy was being executed, the polls were
opening for the special election of a new police chief, replacing
one who was charged with grand theft last year. A year earlier saw
nearly three dozen federal drug-related cases involving police
officers, the former county attorney and school officials.
</TEXT>
