<DOCNO> AP890124-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0819EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BiegenwaldTrial     01-24 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Biegenwald Trial,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Sentences Man to Death for Second Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted multiple murderer faces a death
sentence for the second time in the slaying of a teen-ager, becoming
the first defendant to undergo a second capital punishment trial
under New Jersey law.
   A Monmouth County jury sentenced Richard Biegenwald, 48, to death
Monday for the slaying of Anna Olesiewicz, 19, more than five years
ago.
   The jury returned the death sentence after six hours of
deliberations. The state Supreme Court had let stand the murder
conviction, but overturned Biegenwald's first death sentence because
of trial errors and ordered him resentenced by a new jury.
   New Jersey law requires one trial to determine guilt or innocence
and a second to determine sentence. Biegenwald is the first to go
through a second death penalty trial under New Jersey's 7-year-old
capital punishment law.
   Superior Court Judge Patrick McGann ordered Biegenwald executed
by lethal injection on March 15. However, that date will be
postponed because the state Supreme Court automatically reviews all
death sentences.
   In addition to his two murder convictions, Biegenwald pleaded
guilty to the murders of two young women in the Monmouth-Ocean area
during the early 1980s. Prosecutors also suspect Biegenwald in a
fifth slaying.
   A defense attorney urged the jury to spare Biegenwald's life,
saying he would be valuable for studying sociopathic behavior.
   But Assistant Monmouth County Prosecutor James Fagen
characterized Biegenwald as evil and a ``cold-blooded murderer.''
   Biegenwald declined an opportunity to make his own plea to the
jury.
   Fagen said Biegenwald was sentenced to life for a murder
conviction in 1959, but murdered again when released on parole.
   ``Did that rehabilitate him? No,'' Fagen said. ``If it was
punishment, did he learn from it? No. For him, there is only one
punishment.''
   Defense attorney Louis Diamond argued that Biegenwald's beatings
as a child and the harsh treatment he received in psychiatric
hospitals, including electroshock therapy, taught him ``that life is
meaningless, death is meaningless.''
   He also said Biegenwald may have had a motive for killing Ms.
Olesiewicz, saying that the two had smoked marijuana together, an
act that would have jeopordized his parole status after his release
from prison for the 1959 murder.
   Under state law, a jury is permitted to return a death sentence
if it finds a murder was committed without a reason.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
