<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--BoatFire     01-24 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Boat Fire,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arrested After Shuttle Boat Catches Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shuttle boat that ferries people between Los
Angeles and Santa Catalina Island caught fire early today when its
engine overheated, and authorities rescued and then arrested three
people on board, officials said.
   The unidentified people were taken into custody because they
hadn't been authorized to run the 56-foot Channel Express, said Fire
Department Capt. Edward Carlson.
   ``All I know is they weren't authorized to move the boat,'' he
said. ``They may have been employees, I don't know.''
   The three were the only people on the ship at the time, Carlson
said. There were no injuries.
   The boat was reported burning at 3:12 a.m. just outside the
harbor, Carlson said. He said three fire boats doused the blaze
within 10 minutes and the Coast Guard then towed the boat back to
its berth.
   The blaze caused $500,000 damage, Carlson said.
   An investigation determined the fire in the engine room started
when the engine overheated because water valves had not been opened,
he said.
