<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Hamadi     01-24 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Hamadi,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Appeal of Lebanese Kidnapper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARLSRUHE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected
the appeal of Abbas Ali Hamadi, who was sentenced to 13 years in
prison last year for his role in the kidnappings of two West German
businessmen in Beirut.
   Hamadi was convicted by a Duesseldorf court in April of taking
part in the kidnappings in an effort to win freedom for his brother,
Mohammed, who had been arrested in Frankfurt in connection with the
1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner.
   The Supreme Court rejected the appeal without explanation.
   Abbas Hamadi was also convicted of attempting to blackmail the
West German government and of helping his brother smuggle liguid
explosives into the country.
   The West German hostages, Rudolf Cordes and Alfred Schmidt, have
since been released.
   Mohammed Hamadi has been on trial since July in Frankfurt. He is
charged with murder and air piracy in the TWA hijacking, which
claimed the life of a U.S. Navy diver. During the ordeal, 39
Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   The younger Hamadi has admitted his role in the hijacking but has
denied killing Navy diver Robert Stethem.
