<DOCNO> AP890124-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CoupleFound     01-24 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Couple Found,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Couple Found On Island After Missing At Sea Almost Five Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly couple whose daylong fishing
trip turned into a nightmare when a storm blew their boat out to sea
survived on ocean water and a day's worth of food before they were
rescued five days later.
   The couple's boat washed up onto an isolated island three days
after it went adrift, but the two didn't know they were just 500
yards from a caretakers cottage and went without food for two nights
until their rescue Monday.
   Thomas Pettigrew, 81, said the sight of a Marine helicopter
hovering over the island about 45 miles south of Charleston was
``worth all the tea in China.''
   The Charleston resident and his 80-year-old wife, Katie, were
listed in good condition today at Beaufort Memorial Hospital, where
they were being treated for dehydration and exposure.
   ``Considering the fact that they have had no food for four days
and significant exposure, I think they're doing great,'' said Dr.
Lester Haddad, director of the hospital's emergency room.
   The Pettigrews left Charleston on Thursday in their 18-foot
fiberglass boat. But they were blown out to sea and tossed around in
12-foot waves for three days before their craft washed up on St.
Phillips Island late Saturday.
   It wasn't until Monday that a helicopter from the Marine Corps
Air Station in Beaufort spotted them while on a training mission,
the Coast Guard said.
   A storm system that moved through the area over the weekend
brought winds of 25 to 45 mph and temperatures as low as 35 degrees
early Sunday, officials said.
   The Coast Guard searched offshore waters Friday after the couple
was reported overdue. But the effort, which included airplanes and a
110-foot cutter, was suspended late Sunday.
   Pettigrew said he never doubted that he and his wife of 44 years
would be rescued.
   ``I didn't give up my hopes,'' he said. ``I wasn't afraid of
anything no more once I got on that island. I knew I was on dry
land. I was hoping I would get something to eat.''
   But it wasn't until he and his wife were rescued that they were
fed. During the couple's two nights on the island, they never
realized they were about 500 yards from a caretakers cottage, said
Lt. Quain Kahler of the Charleston Coast Guard Base.
</TEXT>
