<DOCNO> AP890124-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Belgium-Missing     01-24 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Belgium-Missing,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Group Claims Vanden Boeynants Is Alive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Left-wing radicals claiming to hold
former Prime Minister Paul Vanden Boeynants said today the
politician is alive, 10 days after his disappearance.
   ``He is alive and will confess,'' the Revolutionary Socialist
Brigade said in a typewritten note sent to the Brussels daily Le
Soir. The note was accompanied by two handwritten pages, purportedly
by Vanden Boeynants, and an identity card that appeared to belong to
him.
   Police said they were investigating the authenticity of the
documents.
   The brigade claimed last week it kidnapped Vanden Boeynants, who
disappeared Jan. 14, and said it was holding him for ransom. Nothing
had been heard from the group since last Tuesday.
   Two other left-wing groups _ the notorious Direct Action and the
Fighting Communist Cells _ also have claimed they kidnapped the
69-year-old Belgian.
   ``There are elements that could allow us to think that they (the
brigade) are holding Mr. Vanden Boeynants,'' said Andre Vandoren,
the deputy Brussels prosecutor.
   In its last communication Jan. 17, the brigade said Vanden
Boeynants would appear before a ``People's Tribunal,'' and it
threatened to kill him.
   Today's letter said he ``will appear free before the people,'' if
$790,000 ransom is paid. Two-thirds of the money must go to the poor
and the rest to the group, says the brigade, which is unknown to
police.
   The letter purportedly from Vanden Boeynants was clear only in
parts. It said in part:
   ``Through the BSR (brigade), I will make a statement to the press
shortly after my release saying I had to take the initiative to give
within six weeks a large amount of aid to relief groups for the
poorest regardless of their politics, language or religious
beliefs.''
   The letter did not mention a release date.
   Vanden Boeynants was prime minister from 1966 to 1968 and from
late 1978 until early 1979.
   In 1986, he received a three-year suspended sentence for tax
evasion and fraud as head of his meatpacking business.
   Vanden Boeynants disappeared the day before parliament was to
open an inquiry into his affairs. On Sunday, a judicial dossier
linked to that investigation disappeared.
</TEXT>
