<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Vatican-Arson 3rdLd-Writethru a0533 01-24 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-Arson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0533,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Tries to Set Fire to Raphael Painting at Vatican</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs with man identified. Pickup 7th pvs, `Museum
officials...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man in a wheelchair tried to set fire to a
16th century painting by Raphael in the Vatican Museum today by
setting ablaze a flammable liquid he tossed at the painting, Vatican
officials said.
   Museum guards restrained the man, quickly extinguished the flames
and prevented the work from being damaged, said Vatican spokesman
Joaquin Navarro.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said police identified the man as
Thomas Lange, a 31-year-old West German from Berlin who had been
living in Italy about a year. Earlier, Navarro said the man spoke
only English.
   The incident occurred in the Vatican Picture Gallery, which
contains some of Raphael's most famous works. Navarro said the man's
target was the Madonna of Foligno, painted from 1512 to 1513.
   Navarro said the man, who had been noticed by guards in the
museum in previous days, struggled up from his wheelchair, took out
a thermos and tossed a liquid toward the painting.
   The liquid landed on the floor and wall beneath the painting, and
the man then tossed a lighted match to set it ablaze, Navarro said.
He said the flames did not reach the painting.
   Navarro described the man as ``showing signs of being
handicapped, also mentally.''
   Museum officials took down the work to check for possible smoke
damage. It was to be back on display Wednesday.
   Navarro said the man was also carrying two spray bombs of the
type used for personal defense and another bottle of an unidentified
liquid.
   The 10-by6{-foot canvas the man tried to damage depicts the
Madonna with child seated on clouds above a sphere surrounded by
cherubs. Beneath are Saints John the Baptist, Francis and Jerome. In
the distance are the Umbrian town of Foligno.
   The most serious vandalism against a Vatican work of art occurred
in 1972 when Hungarian-born Laszlo Toth battered Michelangelo's
famed Pieta with a hammer inside St. Peter's Basilica.
   Toth, who screamed ``I am Jesus Christ'' as he attacked the
statue, broke off the Madonna's left arm and veil and dented the
left side of the face.
   The masterpiece was fully restored and is now protected by
bulletproof glass in the basilica.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
