<FIRST>r a PM-Mitchelson-Victims     01-24 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mitchelson-Victims,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Awards $56,000 To Women Claiming Sexual Assault By Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women who claim famed divorce lawyer
Marvin Mitchelson sexually assaulted them were awarded $56,000 for
medical and psychiatric care despite the refusal of authorities to
prosecute the cases.
   The state Board of Control, a three-member crime victims
compensation panel, concluded Monday that Kristin Barrett-Whitney
and Patricia French were telling the truth about the alleged
assaults.
   Ms. Barrett-Whitney was awarded $46,000 and Ms. French, $10,000.
The money comes from fines paid by criminals.
   Mitchelson, who gained national attention for his handling of
divorce and ``palimony'' cases involving celebrities, has
steadfastly denied the allegations. He has called the women, both
former clients, ``professional extortionists.''
   Mitchelson could not be reached for comment on the award. A
message left with his answering service before business hours today
was not immediately returned.
   The alleged assaults, which were said to have occurred in 1981
and 1985, were the subject of a segment on CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes''
last year.
   The county district attorney's office, after a lengthy
investigation, decided early last year there was insufficient
evidence to prosecute the cases. The state attorney general's office
also reviewed the cases but declined to prosecute.
   Ms. Barrett-Whitney's psychiatrist, Dr. Gary Shepherd, called the
panel's decision fascinating.
   ``The district attorney won't prosecute, but the state will pay
money, because they say a crime occurred,'' he said.
   Austin Eaton, executive officer of the Board of Control, said the
board's standard of proof is less stringent than that required in a
criminal prosecution.
   A preponderance of evidence is all that is required by the board,
rather than the beyond-a-reasonable-doubt standard followed by
prosecutors, Eaton said.
   The board heard about 20 minutes of testimony from the women, a
psychiatrist and a police detective who investigated their claims in
1986.
   The Los Angeles police detective, Robert Kestler, testified that
he believed the women were telling the truth.
   Mitchelson was not invited by the board to testify before it.
   Both women praised the board's decision.
   ``I've fought long and hard for this,'' Ms. Barrett-Whitney said.
She also vowed to continue to push for Mitchelson's prosecution.
</TEXT>
