<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg 1stLd-Writethru a0473 01-24 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0473,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Gets Steinberg Case; Two Alternates Say They Would Convict</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with deliberations resuming.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the child-killing case against Joel
Steinberg weighed homicide charges against him, and two alternate
jurors who were dismissed said they would have voted for conviction.
   However, the alternates expressed mixed feelings about the
prosecution's star witness _ Steinberg's former live-in companion,
Hedda Nussbaum, whose testimony will likely determine the verdict.
   The jury received the case Monday and deliberated for about nine
hours without reaching a verdict. Deliberations resumed this morning.
   Of the five alternate jurors released by Judge Harold Rothwax,
some told reporters they believed Ms. Nussbaum testified truthfully,
others weren't sure and some thought she was covering up.
   Dr. Samuel Klagsbrun, Ms. Nussbaum's psychiatrist, said Monday
his patient ``will interpret any verdict except murder as, `They
didn't believe me.'
   ``If the jury shows any doubt she feels people will feel she is
responsible or somehow she participated in the crime, and that is a
hurt that she finds almost unbearable,'' he said.
   Steinberg is charged in the death of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg,
the girl he obtained at birth from an unwed Long Island teen-ager
and raised but never legally adopted.
   Lisa was removed comatose from Steinberg's Greenwich Village
apartment on Nov. 2, 1987, and taken to a hospital where she died of
a brain injury three days later.
   The case drew nationwide attention to the problem of child and
spousal abuse, especially to the responsibility of teachers,
neighbors and other adults who may suspect someone is a victim of
abuse.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, testified for the prosecution that Steinberg
told her in bed, after they free-based cocaine and while Lisa lay
comatose on their bathroom floor, that he had ``knocked Lisa down
and she didn't want to get up.''
   Steinberg's lawyers charge that Ms. Nussbaum beat the child to
death in a jealous rage, while prosecutors say Ms. Nussbaum was too
incapacitated from being abused by Steinberg to have been able to
inflict a fatal beating.
   If jurors decide Steinberg bears guilt in the child's death, they
must decide among four possible homicide counts: murder, first- or
second-degree manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide.
   One alternate juror who was dismissed Monday after she became ill
told reporters she would have voted to convict Steinberg of murder.
   The juror, Sharon Rupert, 50, was excused shortly before Rothwax
completed his final instructions to the jury. The other alternate
jurors were released shortly before the 12 regular jurors retired
for the night.
   ``I believed Hedda,'' said Ms. Rupert. ``I almost cried when she
left the witness stand.''
   Alternate Millie Sandoval, 31, when asked if she believed Ms.
Nussbaum's testimony, said: ``It's hard to say. I just feel that she
was just as much to blame. I don't think she should get away with
everything.''
   She refused to comment on whether she thought Steinberg should be
convicted. But when asked if she believed Steinberg ``did it,'' Ms.
Sandoval said ``I believe it could have been both of them.''
   Edna Massick, 34, said, ``I think Hedda was telling the partial
truth; I can't say I feel she was telling the complete truth. I
think she was covering for Joel. She is a very sick woman.''
   Asked if she thought Steinberg should be convicted, Ms. Massick
said: ``Definitely. I think he should have been convicted. I'm not
sure of what.''
</TEXT>
