<FIRST>r a PM-KlansmenSentenced     01-24 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Klansmen Sentenced,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences, Fines Six Ex-Klansmen In Decatur Clash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite pleas for leniency, six former Ku
Klux Klansmen were ordered to spend time in prison for helping to
disrupt a black protest march in Decatur almost 10 years ago.
   The lengthy case ended Monday when the six were sentenced and
fined by U.S. District Judge James H. Hancock after they told him
they had severed their Klan connections and were sorry for what they
had done.
   The 1979 clash came as blacks protested the arrest of a black
Decatur man, Tommy Lee Hines, who was charged with raping three
white women in 1978.
   Hines was convicted of one of the rapes and sent to prison. The
Alabama Court of Criminal Appeals later ruled that he was mentally
incompetent, and he was moved to a mental hospital in Tuscaloosa.
   The protest march ended in a gunfight and brawl with Klansmen,
with several marchers and policemen injured.
   Attorneys for the six had sought probation or community service
instead of prison terms.
   Three other ex-Klansmen also charged in the clash were sentenced
previously, one on his guilty plea and two on their convictions.
   Hancock gave the stiffest penalties to Ray W. Steele of Decatur
and William D. Riccio of Birmingham, who pleaded guilty to
misdemeanor charges of violating the marchers' civil rights by
conspiring to disrupt the march, and to two felony charges of
conspiring to obstruct an FBI investigation.
   Each was sentenced to terms of one and two years, to be served
concurrently, and each was fined $1,000.
   On guilty pleas to conspiring to disrupt the march, Roger D.
Handley of Warrior was sentenced to four months and fined $600;
William J. Mason and Lenwood L. White, both of Muscle Shoals, were
sentenced to three months and fined $500; and Terry J. Tucker of
Cullman was sentenced to two months and fined $400.
   ``I made a mistake,'' White said. ``I have to pay the price.
It'll never happen again.''
   Riccio told the judge that ``I guess I was hardheaded for a long
time. I butted my head against the wall and got wore down. I will
not let this court down if given the opportunity to prove I am a
changed person.''
</TEXT>
