<FIRST>r i PM-Flight103     01-24 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prince Charles Pays Belated Royal Visit To Lockerbie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles came to Lockerbie today
to comfort the bereaved and mend fences with townspeople aggrieved
by the royal family's behavior after the crash of Pan Am Flight 103.
   The visit by the heir to the British throne was seen as a tacit
admission by the royal family that it bungled its response to the
Dec. 21 tragedy, first through an inept remark by Charles' younger
brother Prince Andrew, and then by staying away from a memorial
service for the victims.
   Charles, who arrived by train for a 90-minute visit that
stretched to 2{ hours, got a friendly welcome and several residents
said they felt mollified by his trip.
   All 259 people aboard the New York-bound Boeing 747 were killed,
along with 11 residents of this rural town, when a bomb blew up the
jet.
   Andrew, who visited the day after the crash, got into trouble
when he appeared to voice more concern for the Americans on the
plane than the Britons on the ground.
   ``It's very sad for the town, but my deepest feelings go out to
the people, the families of those Americans who died in the crash,''
he told reporters.
   Media reaction was scathing when the royals stayed away from a
memorial service Jan. 4 in Lockerbie attended by relatives of the
families, Pan Am staff and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   The royals sent local representatives, and Buckingham Palace said
it was not customary for Queen Elizabeth II to attend such events.
But the palace then announced the queen's husband, Prince Philip,
would attend the funeral of Emperor Hirohito of Japan.
   Thousands of British war prisoners died at the hands of the
Japanese during World War II, and many Britons regarded Hirohito as
a war criminal.
   ``The fact that a member of the royal family is going to Japan to
the funeral of a man who caused so much suffering, when they could
not come to a memorial service in their own country, must have some
effect locally,'' said Robert Jardine, vice chairman of the
Lockerbie and District Community Council.
   Charles met with bereaved families, inspected the crater caused
by the falling wreckage, toured damaged homes and laid a wreath
outside the town hall.
   He also met with rescue officials, shook hands with townspeople
and stopped for a quick drink and friendly banter at a local pub.
   ``I think it's helped out,'' said Anne McPhail, a Lockerbie
resident. ``I wondered about it myself. I thought it was a bit late
in the day but now I feel better about it.''
   Said store manager Robert Devlin: ``It says a lot for him that he
had the courage to come. It is a great honor.''
   Trucker Niven Milligan said: ``I am pleased that the prince has
come to make amends for his brother.''
   The physical impact of the crash is still evident. Southbound
lanes remain closed on the main highway alongside the crater. Nearby
are the burned-out shells of houses.
   The government has announced a grant of about $12.6 million to
pay for the search and rescue operations, police investigation and
counseling for the bereaved.
</TEXT>
