<HEAD>West African President Orders Troops To Shoot Rioters On Sight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COTONOU, Benin (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mathieu Kerekou ordered troops to
open fire on crowds following anti-government riots in the capital,
official reports said today.
   State radio broadcast Kerekou's order for soldiers ``to shoot
without warning on any group that forms and this throughout the
national territory.''
   In telephone calls, reporters at Benin's state news agency
confirmed that rioting broke out Monday night, but they refused to
give details.
   Demonstrators sacked several public buildings and burned
portraits of Kerekou, the French agency Agence France Presse
reported.
   Protesters chanted the name of Lt. Col. Francois Kouyami, said to
be one of the leaders of an attempted coup last year, said AFP.
Kouyami escaped from prison in November.
   Authorities have dispatched 300 extra troops to reinforce the
garrison in the capital, which is 20 miles east of Cotonou.
   Porto Novo was the scene of several incidents earlier this month
when teachers, unpaid for several weeks, went on strike to demand
their salaries. Unrest lasted a week, but the discontent has
continued.
   Kerekou has ruled since 1972, when he seized power in the tiny
West African nation's fifth coup since its independence from France
in 1960. The country used to be called Dahomey.
