<FIRST>r i PM-Switzerland-Alert     01-24 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Switzerland-Alert,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss on Alert, Warning of Terror Attacks On U.S., British</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities tightened security at
Zurich's international airport after a warning that terrorists may
launch attacks on U.S. or British targets from Switzerland, police
said today.
   In a separate incident, a New York-bound Air India passenger jet
was diverted to Ireland after a bomb threat.
   The Swiss alert said a terrorist group carrying Lebanese
passports was traveling around Europe and planned attacks on
unidentified American or British targets that could take place in
Switzerland or be launched from there, Zurich police spokesman Jan
Karbe said.
   ``We must take the alert seriously and we are doing so,'' said
Zurich airport spokesman Peter Gutknecht.
   Airport officials ordered ``adjustments in tactics and
personnel'' for the entire airport Saturday morning, Karbe said
without elaboration.
   He said the warning, received by Zurich airport authorities
Friday, was part of routine international exchanges of information
between airports, law enforcement agencies and airlines.
   On Monday, an Air India jumbo jet carrying 279 passengers was
recalled one hour and 15 minutes after it took off from London's
Heathrow Airport.
   Flight 111, which was over the Atlantic Ocean off Ireland's west
coast, diverted to Shannon International Airport.
   A spokesman for Aer Lingus, the handlers for Air India at
Shannon, said baggage was left in the airplane's hold until the time
the jet originally was scheduled to land in New York, in case a bomb
attached to a timer was on board.
   A search produced no explosives, he said.
   ``The hoax was a sick and disgusting joke,'' said Evelyn
Cooperstock of New Haven, Conn. She was among passengers who
reboarded the plane today after it was cleared for the
trans-Atlantic flight.
   On Dec. 21, a bomb blew up a Pan Am jet bound for New York,
killing all 259 on board and 11 people on the ground in Lockerbie,
Scotland.
</TEXT>
