<FIRST>u p PM-ChicagoMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0509 01-24 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0509,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evans Files Third-Party Candidacy For April Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Jackson endorsing Sawyer.
Picks up 10th graf, ``We don't ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson today endorsed Mayor Eugene Sawyer's
bid for the city's Democratic mayoral nomination, saying Sawyer
``has earned our support.''
   The endorsement came just hours after Sawyer's leading black
challenger, Alderman Timothy Evans, submitted 100,000 petition
signatures in a third-party bid.
   Evans' move was an attempt to avoid a split in the black primary
vote that would give an edge to the leading white Democratic
candidate, Richard M. Daley, son of the city's longtime former mayor.
   Unless his petitions are challenged, Evans will bypass the city's
Feb. 28 Democratic mayoral primary and run under the banner of his
own party, which he dubbed the Harold Washington party, in the April
4 special election to fill the remaining two years of Washington's
term.
   Washington, the city's first black mayor, died from a heart
attack in November 1987. Evans was Washington's floor leader in the
City Council, but the aldermen selected Sawyer, who also is black,
to succeed Washington until the special election could be held.
   Jackson said today that a primary victory by Sawyer ``will show
our strong resolve to go forward in unity with a multiracial
coalition of workers ... determined to conquer the present odds.''
   As he filed his petitions, Evans pledged to reform the city's
political scene, especially what he called the remnants of the
``machine'' of late Mayor Richard J. Daley, who died 12 years ago.
   Evans also announced a drive to sign up an estimated 150,000
unregistered black voters. The drive, if successful, could benefit
Sawyer, but Evans' handlers believe the mayor won't survive the
primary.
   ``We don't particularly care who it helps in the primary. We want
to make sure people are registered to vote,'' Evans spokeswoman
Sharon Jenkins-Brown said. ``If ancillary effects fall to Sawyer,
more power to him.''
   Over the weekend, Sawyer got endorsements from several
influential black leaders, including a former political foe,
Alderman Danny Davis. Davis, however, said his endorsement is only
for the primary.
</TEXT>
