<SECOND>PM-UN-Namibia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0562,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibia Peacekeeping Force Cut; More Police Included</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after, ``In his ... he said,'' to include pvs
U.N. peacekeeping costs. PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, ``The Security ....''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
bowed to budget concerns today and recommended the Namibia
peacekeeping force be cut to 4,650 troops.
   It is expected to be the United Nations' costliest mission.
   Black African nations and non-aligned countries have argued for
weeks with the United States, Soviet Union, Britain, France and
China over the size and cost of the force.
   It will oversee Namibia's transition from South African rule to
independence, which is to begin April 1.
   The Organization of African Unity and non-aligned countries
insisted that at least 7,500 troops be dispatched, as provided for
in the original 1978 U.N. Security Council plan for the territory.
   But the United States and the other permanent members of the
Security Council, which together pay 58 percent of peacekeeping
costs, objected to the estimated $700 million cost of sending that
many troops.
   The United States proposed sending about 3,200 peacekeepers to
the territory, which has also been known as South-West Africa.
   In his recommendations to the Security Council, released today,
Perez de Cuellar kept the upper limit of the peacekeeping contingent
at 7,500, but said only 4,650 would be dispatched at a cost of about
$416 million. The remaining troops will be held in readiness in
their home countries in case they are needed, he said.
   All U.N. peacekeeping operations in 1988 cost about $375 million.
The most expensive was the 1960-64 Congo peacekeeping mission, which
cost more than $400 million, at much higher dollar rates, and
involved 19,828 soldiers.
   The Security Council must vote on Perez de Cuellar's
recommendations and is expected to approve them.
   Elections for a Namibian assembly are to be held in November. The
assembly will draft a constitution and organize a black-majority
ruled government, ending South Africa's 74-year rule over Namibia.
   A force of 500 police drawn from U.N. member nations will be sent
to supervise the Namibian police, who will still be responsible for
law and order during the transition to independence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890124-0085 </DOCNO>
