<HEAD>Malaysian Prime Minister Undergoes Heart Bypass Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
underwent successful coronary bypass surgery Tuesday at the Kuala
Lumpur Government Hospital, officials said.
   Doctors decided on surgery after conducting tests on the
63-year-old prime minister, who was admitted to Kuala Lumpur
Government Hospital on Jan. 18 after complaining of chest pains,
according to Dr. C. Fonseka, the hospital director.
   Mahathir's condition was stable, according to a statement
released through the national news agency Bernama.
   Officials at the Prime Minister's Department, speaking on
condition of anonymity, confirmed the Bernama report.
   Mahathir had suffered from minor blood presure problems, but this
was the first time he had complained of chest pains, friends and
relatives said.
   In 1981, Mahathir succeeded Hussein Onn to become Malaysia's
fourth prime minister since its independence from Britain in 1957.
   Mahathir is president of the United Malays National Organization,
which rules in a coalition with 12 other Chinese and Indian parties.
   Two years ago, his former deputy prime minister, Musa Hitam, and
finance minister, Tengku Razaleigh Hamzah, joined forces to try to
oust Mahathir. Maneuvering within the party is continuing, but
politicians and Western diplomats say Mahathir does not appear
likely to be ousted anytime soon.
   Mahathir, a physician trained in Western medicine, graduated from
the University of Singapore in 1957.
</TEXT>
