<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Rwanda     01-24 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Rwanda,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoners Get a Break on Start of President's Third Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rwandan government marked the start of
President Jevenal Habyarimana's third term by commuting death
sentences and reducing prison terms for inmates sentenced before
Jan. 8, Radio Kigali said Tuesday.
   The amnesty excludes those convicted of offenses against the
state, embezzlement or of being accomplices in those offenses, the
state-owned radio said in a broadcast monitored in Nairobi.
   The government also freed all prisoners serving five-year prison
terms, and all women and those under 18 sentenced to 20 years in
jail.
   The decree reduced life sentences to 20 years and death sentences
to life. The radio did not say how many prisoners were affected.
   Habyarimana was elected to a third five-year term in December.
</TEXT>
