<DOCNO> AP890124-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-VirginForest     01-24 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Virgin Forest,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Tract's Future May Be Decided In Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ROBRAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SKYLINE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future of one of the last tracts of
virgin forest in Appalachia is at stake in a lawsuit in which a
former owner argues the state should give the land back because it
isn't taking proper care of the historic relic.
   The oldest trees in the 550-acre Lilley Cornett Woods, 15 miles
west of Whitesburg in rugged eastern Kentucky, predate the Pilgrims'
landing in 1620.
   ``It's the last remnant of any size that's preserved in Kentucky
of the pre-settlement forest,'' said William H. Martin, an Eastern
Kentucky University official who oversees the site, including 252
acres of oak, walnut, chestnut and hickory that have never been
logged or used for grazing.
   ``That's it,'' Martin said. ``We're talking about 252 acres out
of 25 million originally in Kentucky.''
   Martin and the university are among the officials and state
agencies who are defendants in a lawsuit filed last year by a son of
Lilley Cornett, the man for whom the woods are named. The lawsuit
seeks to return ownership of the property to the son, Dock Cornett.
   The elder Cornett bought the land in 1918 and protected the woods
from outside encroachment for several decades. He willed the small
forest to his sons, who sold it to the state for $270,000 in 1968 on
the condition that it be preserved as a ``living museum.''
   Dock Cornett, 68, contends the state has failed to live up to
that obligation.
   He said the state and EKU have built a dam, cut timber, torn down
historic log structures dating from the 1800s and erected research
stations, all in violation of restrictions in the 1968 deed. The
university took over administration of the forest in 1977.
   A Letcher Circuit Court judge is expected to rule next month on
whether the lawsuit should be dismissed on grounds of governmental
immunity. If the case is allowed to proceed, Cornett's lawyer said a
trial could take place before the end of the year.
   Dock Cornett retained the right to live in a home at an edge of
the woods and to move about the property without restriction. He
keeps binoculars handy to observe the activities of the university
caretaker, Mike Brotzge.
   ``Getting the truth out is all I want,'' said Cornett, a retired
teacher, who was convicted on a misdemeanor charge of terroristic
threatening stemming from an altercation with Brotzge in 1987.
   Martin said suggestions that EKU was damaging the forest were
``absurd.'' He said the dam the university built along a stream
holds back a small amount of water for hydrology studies, and
experiments at the research buildings focus on acid rain and plant
species.
   Cornett and his lawyer, Coy Holstein of Whitesburg, said that in
addition to the serious accusations they have leveled against the
state and the university, they also are concerned that EKU officials
place too little emphasis on providing tours for visitors.
   Martin, who declined to discuss specific allegations in the
lawsuit, said only about 1,000 people visited the remote site in
1988. He said he thought no more than 3,000 visitors should be
allowed into the area annually and views the area primarily as a
research station.
   Visitors must make appointments to tour the woods. When visitors
arrived unannounced recently, Brotzge was working on a truck and
said he was too busy to provide a tour.
   If Cornett won the lawsuit, he would offer the land to other
state agencies or private conservation groups, Holstein said. If EKU
is allowed to keep the site, the lawyer said he believes the outlook
for the forest would be grim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890124-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   01-24 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Americans, Other Westerners to Leave Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos KAB1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy said Tuesday it had
warned Americans to get out of Afghanistan. Most of them, along with
other Western private citizens, announced plans to leave.
   Some diplomatic sources predicted President Najib will declare
martial law as the last Soviet military forces withdraw and leave
his army to fight alone against a Moslem insurgency that began after
a communist coup 11 years ago.
   Other than those in embassies, most Westerners are with the
International Aid Mission, a charitable organization that has
operated in Afghanistan for many years. Among other things, it runs
an eye hospital in Kabul.
   ``They've finally gotten through to us,'' said Richard Penner, a
Canadian who directs the mission.
   Penner said 10 people would stay, including himself, but the
other 42 would be gone by Feb. 11, four days before the Soviet
withdrawal deadline. The mission had 85 people in Afghanistan last
summer.
   The dozen Americans in Afghanistan, other than 11 at the embassy,
work for the mission.
   Nearly all dependents of foreigners already have left.
   Predictions of martial law accompanied growing evidence, despite
repeated Soviet denials, that the Red Army is pulling out of Kabul
ahead of the deadline set in a U.N.-mediated withdrawal agreement.
   A 70-vehicle military convoy left Kabul on Monday, heading north
on the Salang Highway that connects the capital with the Soviet
border 250 miles away. It included six tanks, armored personnel
carriers and trucks loaded with soldiers.
   It was the first northern movement of Soviet troops observed this
week. Western diplomats said convoys of up to 100 vehicles each were
seen moving up the highway four days last week.
   Afghan soldiers have replaced Soviet personnel at some guard
posts on Kabul's perimeter and hundreds of Red Army soldiers with
full gear have been seen boarding Ilyushin-76 transport planes at
the airport.
   Members of the Interior Ministry militia, a force of 30,000
considered to be among the government's best, were placed at
checkpoints in downtown Kabul a few days ago.
   Western diplomats in Islamabad, Pakistan, said Tuesday the heavy
convoy and air traffic indicated the final Soviet withdrawal was in
progress. The sources also reported intense fighting between
government forces in Kanduz, a northern province, and in Nangarhar
and Kandahar provinces to the east.
   They said the pace of departure indicated nearly all Soviet
forces would be out by the end of January. One diplomat, speaking
privately like the others, quoted Afghans and East European
diplomats as saying a paratroop battalion or other small force might
remain until the Feb. 15 deadline.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and an
estimated 115,000 were in the country wen the witdrawal agreement
was signed April 14 in Geneva. The pullout began May 15 and half
were gone by Aug. 15.
   Jon D. Glassman, charge d'affaires at the U.S. Embassy, said in a
warning letter to Americans that ``a critical point'' had come in
the Kabul area, increased instablity was likely, and they should
leave while commercial flights remained available.
   Only the Soviet airline Aeroflot and Ariana, the Afghan
government airline, still operate from Kabul. Aeroflot uses military
planes and Ariana flights are unpredictable, sometimes delayed or
canceled for lack of aviation fuel.
   Britain's embassy issued a similar warning last week to to its
nationals and citizens of other countries for which it has
diplomatic responsibility, including Canada, Australia and Ireland.
   Other than the missionaries, foreigners still in Afghanistan
include a few hundred diplomats, a dwindling number of Soviet
civilian advisers, employees of the International Red Cross and
officials of U.N. aid agencies and the U.N. body monitoring the
withdrawal agreement.
   On Saturday, the West German Embassy became the first to close.
Spokesmen for others say they confer regularly about when or whether
to do the same.
   Food shortages in Kabul have been severe because of guerrilla
attacks on supply convoys, and the Soviets began a flour airlift
last weekend that brings in 400-500 tons a day.
   Maj. Gen. Lev Serebrov, the Soviet deputy commander in
Afghanistan, insisted Sunday the final withdrawal had yet to begin.
   Western analysts believe the Kremlin wants to keep the pullout
under wraps for security and political reasons, including continued
political pressure on guerrilla leaders to resume negotitons for a
coalition government including communists.
   Leaders of the seven-party guerrilla alliance based in Pakistan
have refused such a deal and broke off talks with the Soviets about
a political solution.
</TEXT>
