<FIRST>r w AM-MIAMeeting     01-24 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Meeting,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials to Meet in Hunt for Missing Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials from the United States and
Laos will meet this week in Vientiane to schedule surveys and
excavations in the hunt for American servicemen missing from the
Vietnam war, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   The meeting will begin Thursday and extend through Saturday. The
U.S. delegation will be led by Harriet Isom, the charge d'affaires
at the American embassy in Vientiane.
   Earlier this month, U.S. and Laotian officials ``agreed to
establish a year-round POW-MIA work plan,'' the Pentagon said in a
statement.
   ``Excavations, surveys or investigations to be conducted later
this year may be planned at this (upcoming) meeting,'' it added.
   The American delegation will include technical experts from the
Joint Casualty Resolution Center and the U.S. Army Central
Identification Laboratory.
   There are 2,383 Americans still listed as missing from the
Vietnam war, including 547 who were lost in Laos.
