<FIRST>r a AM-OralAIDS     01-24 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oral AIDS,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Reportedly Got AIDS Virus from Woman During Oral Sex</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A Wednesday embargo on this story was broken. Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man reportedly contracted the AIDS virus by
having oral sex with a woman, the first report in medical literature
of woman-to-man transmission of the virus in that fashion, according
to a doctor.
   The case of the 60-year-old New England man was reported in this
week's New England Journal of Medicine by two physicians from the
Lahey Clinic Medical Center.
   ``I hope the message gets through, especially to younger people
in high school and college, who cling to the belief that they're all
right if they don't have intercourse,'' said Dr. Peter G. Spitzer,
one of the authors.
   The man who got the virus reportedly has been married for 30
years and has diabetes, which caused nerve damage that made him
impotent. He told his doctors he had not had sex with his wife for
years.
   The doctors said the man's only sexual contact in recent years
was with a prostitute with whom he engaged only in oral sex.
   He said the woman used intravenous drugs in his presence. This
suggested the possibility that she contracted the virus from sharing
hypodermic needles rather than from sexual activity, the report said.
   The two doctors from the Lahey Clinic in Burlington did not seek
out the prostitute because of state laws on the confidentiality of
AIDS patients, Spitzer said.
   ``Ironically, if she had syphilis, state health authorities could
trace her,'' he said.
   Spitzer said it is most likely that the virus was transmitted to
the man through her vaginal secretions. Researchers at Massachusetts
General Hospital have found the AIDS virus in vaginal fluids.
   But studies have shown that saliva can contain small amounts of
the virus, and it could have been transmitted through the
prostitute's saliva.
   Spitzer and his co-author, Dr. Neil J. Weiner, wrote that
``public health education about safer sexual practices must not only
advocate the use of barrier contraceptives such as condoms during
vaginal and rectal intercourse, but also caution against the
exchange of bodily fluids during other sexual practices, such as
oral sex.''
</TEXT>
