<SECOND>AM-People-Busey,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gary Busey, Still Confined to Private Rehab Facility, Doing Well</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gary Busey remained in a private
rehabilitation facility but was progressing well 52 days after being
thrown off his motorcycle and slamming head-first into a curb, his
publicist said.
   ``It's going to take a while for him, but they expect a full
recovery,'' spokeswoman Carla Schalman said Tuesday. ``He's doing
well, but it's a slow process and he won't be well overnight. They
are happy with his progress.''
   Busey, 44, underwent 90 minutes of brain surgery at Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center following the Dec. 4 accident in Culver City. He
entered the rehabilitation facility over the New Year's weekend.
   Ms. Schalman said the location of the facility was kept
confidential to guard the actor's privacy and dismissed speculation
that Busey's injuries may have been more serious than originally
thought.
   ``He's making progress in the rehabilitation, which involves
exercising and weight lifting,'' she said.
   Busey, an active opponent of mandatory helmet laws, wasn't
wearing a helmet when he lost control of his motorcycle.
   The actor was nominated for an Academy Award for his performance
in the title role of ``The Buddy Holly Story.'' His other credits
include ``Big Wednesday,'' ``Lethal Weapon'' and the HBO miniseries
``A Dangerous Life.''
