<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SenateDefense     01-24 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate Defense,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Focus on Military Strategy Seen as Senators Await Tower Testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders, awaiting testimony this
week by President Bush's nominee for secretary of defense, say the
legislative agenda involving defense policy is likely to center on
military strategy after eight years of the largest peacetime
build-up.
   Senate Armed Services Committee confirmation hearings start
Wednesday on former Sen. John G. Tower, R-Texas, Bush's choice to
head the Defense Department.
   The 63-year-old Tower, whose 24 years as a senator included a
stint a chairman of the committee, is expected to win approval from
his former colleagues despite concerns about his personal life and
work as a defense consultant.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the committee chairman, has said that Tower
is likely to win Senate confirmation.
   Among issues the committee is expected to raise with Tower are
the Pentagon budget, defense policy and Bush's appointments to
civilian posts within the department.
   Meantime, matching resources such as strategic weapons and
conventional forces to the type of military commitment the Bush
administration envisions will be the subject for a series of
congressional hearings during this legislative session.
   After two terms under Ronald Reagan in which the administration
allocated $2.13 trillion to the Defense Department, a figure that
does not include Department of Energy spending on nuclear warheads,
Congress is expected to take a careful look at strategy and the cost
of resources in light of the budget deficit situation.
   In his final budget, Reagan requested $315.2 billion in budget
authority _ a 2 percent increase after inflation _ for defense in
fiscal 1990, the 12 months opening Oct. 1.
   ``I think they're whistling Dixie if they think they'll get a 2
to 3 percent increase in spending,'' said Rep. Sonny Montgomery,
D-Miss., a member of the House Armed Services Committee. ``They'll
be fortunate if they get the inflation factor.''
   Bush, according to testimony last week from Office of Management
and Budget nominee Richard Darman, is expected to reduce Reagan's
request by an unspecified amount. Congress will likely wait for
Bush's changes before acting on the budget.
   During last year's presidential campaign, Nunn and Sen. John
Warner of Virginia, the ranking Republican on the Armed Services
Committee, sent a letter to Bush and Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
nominee, stressing the importance of qualified people.
   ``Strong defense leadership will be needed during the next four
years to resolve serious strategy, budget, force structure,
manpower, alliance and arms control problems and issues,'' Nunn and
Warner said in the letter dated Oct. 28, 1988.
   ``Central to meeting those challenges is the appointment of the
highest quality and experienced defense management team,'' they
wrote.
   Also during this congressional session, hearings will be held on
the plan to close 86 military bases and partly close five more _ a
recommendation by a special federal commission that has since been
accepted by Reagan's Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci.
   Despite some opposition, the chances of Congress passing a
resolution of disapproval against the plan or overriding a
presidential veto remain slim, say congressional aides, who believe
the battle over the bases will be fought in appropriating the funds
to close the facilities.
   Debate will also resume over spending for Star Wars research and
development, moving the new B-2 stealth bomber into production and
funding for the truck-mobile, single-warhead Midgetman missile and
the rail-mobile version of the MX intercontinental ballistic missile.
</TEXT>
