<FIRST>r a AM-FerryTheft-Fire     01-24 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ferry Theft-Fire,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arrested After Theft Of Ferry, Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men and a teen-ager were rescued from a
burning ferry Tuesday and then arrested for allegedly stealing it
for a joy ride, authorities said.
   The Catalina Island ferry caught fire after the engine overheated
in Los Angeles Harbor, firefighters said. Damage was estimated at
$500,000, said Fire Department spokesman Jim Wells.
   ``They didn't know how to run the boat, they almost got hit by a
tanker when they were running without lights, and when the Coast
Guard took them off the burning boat they appeared panic-stricken,''
said Officer Donald Dille of the police Harbor Division.
   The 56-foot ferry was taken from a berth during the night on an
apparent joy ride, Dille said. It was spotted on fire about 3 a.m.
   ``They apparently failed to open the sea chest, which allows
water to circulate around the engine to keep it cool,'' said Long
Beach Coast Guard spokesman Brad Smith. He said authorities
extinguished the fire in about 20 minutes.
   The boat normally is used for daily trips between the harbor and
Catalina Island, a tourist destination 21 miles offshore.
   Roy Bennett and Danny Andrews, both 28, of Bell Gardens were held
for investigation of grand theft of a vessel, a felony. Their
15-year-old companion was turned over to juvenile authorities and
later released to his parents.

</TEXT>
