<FIRST>r a AM-MethadoneVan     01-24 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Methadone Van,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Van Brings Methadone to Addicts in Boston Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first of 250 heroin addicts expected to
participate in Boston's mobile drug treatment program stepped aboard
a 32-foot van Tuesday to receive their first doses of methadone.
   Three city employees boarded the unmarked recreational vehicle at
dawn and set out for a state hospital in the city's Jamaica Plain
section, the first of two stops.
   ``What the van will do is allow necessary treatment to be
delivered so addicts will have a greater access to the programs,''
said Sarah Gant, a city health policy analyst. She said the new
service would make it easier for heroin addicts to get treatment on
their way to work or school.
   Candidates are screened and tested before being admitted to the
state-funded treatment, one of only two such programs nationwide,
said Tom Scott, the Addiction Services' acting administrative
director.
   The nation's first mobile methadone program got under way in
Brockton last month after gaining federal approval. It also has been
serving Taunton and Plymouth.
   Methadone, a synthetic opiate that satisfies the body's craving
but does not produce a heroin high, is dispensed to addicts in
medically controlled liquid doses.
   City health officials decided to use a van after Gov. Michael
Dukakis said he wouldn't approve a bill allowing them to distribute
sterile hypodermic needles to drug addicts as a way to stop the
spread of AIDS. Intravenous drug use, specifically the sharing of
dirty needles, is one way the deadly virus is transmitted.
   The city is leasing the van for $700 a month, paid for out of
$400,000 the state allocated to Boston to expand its methadone
programs.
   Medical monitoring and psychological and vocational counseling
are also part of the program, Scott said.
   Ms. Gant said all participants would be stabilized by officials
at Boston City Hospital before being admitted to the program, and
that those patronizing the van will be subjected to random urine
tests to ensure they are not using illegal drugs.
   About 250 people currently receive methadone from a city program
set up in a trailer outside Boston City Hospital. Eventually, the
van is expected to assist an additional 110 people, Scott said.
</TEXT>
