<FIRST>r a AM-ChainSaw-House     01-24 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chain Saw-House,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Guilty to Attacking House with Chain Saw</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOYLESTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man jailed since September for attacking
a former neighbor's 200-year-old home with a chain saw was ordered
to live with his parents in Florida as a condition of his release.
   Kevin Michael Magill, 28, pleaded guilty Monday to simple
assault, criminal mischief, defiant trespass and recklessly
endangering another person in the Sept. 6 incident, in which he
damaged a door and cut down a tree that fell on the roof of the
Haycock Township home, causing more than $100,000 damage.
   A state trooper testified that Magill told police the attack was
provoked by a sewage odor emanating from the house. He had been
jailed since his arrest the day after the attack.
   Bucks County President Judge Isaac S. Garb sentenced Magill to
time served in the Bucks County Prison after Magill's parents agreed
to take custody of their son and put him to work in a motel they own
in Key West, Fla. They also promised to seek counseling for their
son.
   ``That's what I need at this time,'' Magill told the judge. He
said a psychiatrist had diagnosed him as manic depressive.
   Robert O'Kon, owner of the home built in 1774, had told the judge
he would not feel safe as long as Magill has an opportunity to
return to the area.
   Magill, a self-employed drywall installer, lived in a mobile home
across the street from O'Kon.
