<FIRST>r w AM-US-Chile     01-24 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Chile,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Invokes Treaty to Resolve Dispute over Letelier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is invoking a 1914 treaty in
an effort to resolve a dispute with Chile over the 1976 car-bomb
death of a former top aide to President Salvador Allende, the State
Department said Tuesday.
   U.S. officials have long maintained that three Chilean secret
police agents were responsible for the Washington incident, which
claimed the lives of former Chilean Foreign Minister Orlando
Letelier and an American associate, Ronni Moffitt.
   The Chilean government, however, has refused U.S. requests for
the extradition of the three, and the issue has been a point of
contention between the two governments for years.
   Letelier, an outspoken critic of the government of President
Augusto Pinochet, also served as Chile's ambassador to Washington
under Allende and as defense minister.
   He and Ms. Moffitt were killed when a bomb placed under the car
in which they were riding exploded in the Embassy Row section of
Washington on Sept. 21, 1976.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said U.S. officials
presented Chile with a diplomatic note on Jan. 12 invoking the World
War I era treaty, which is designed to help end disputes that cannot
be resolved by diplomatic methods.
   He said the United States is asking that an international
commission established under the treaty investigate and report on
the facts surrounding the incident, ``including the involvement of
Chilean government officials and to investigate and report upon
subsequent investigations by the government of Chile into the
matter.''
   ``We believe that this treaty process provides an excellent and
neutral means for pursuing justice in the case and resolving the
differences between the U.S. and Chile that relate to the case, ''
Redman said.
   ``The U.S. government will therefore render all possible
assistance to the commission in carrying out its responsibilities
and we expect and trust that the government of Chile will do the
same.''
   Asked whether he expected that Chile will go along with the U.S.
approach, Redman said Chile is obliged to do so under the treaty.
   The president of the five-member panel is Madame Suzanne Bastid
of France. Two other members, picked by the United States, are
William Mulligan of New York and Sir John Freeland of Great Britain.
The other members, selected by Chile, are Edmundo Vargas of Chile
and Judge Manfred Lochs of Poland.
   In 1978, the United States requested the extradition from Chile
of Michael Townley, a U.S. citizen and an employee of the Chilean
intelligence service. He had been implicated in the murders.
   Chile complied and Townley was convicted and sentenced in a U.S.
court.
</TEXT>
