<FIRST>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     01-24 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Criticizes Soviet Bombing Raids Inside Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Tuesday criticized Soviet
bombing raids inside Afghanistan, accusing the Soviets of ``a clear
violation'' of understandings reached on its troop pullout.
   ``This pattern of daily bombardment is unacceptable,'' said State
Department spokesman Charles Redman. ``This is a clear violation of
Soviet assurances to us not to engage in offensive operations during
the withdrawal.''
   Speaking only three weeks prior to the mid-February deadline for
the Soviet troop pullout, Redman said the U.S. government still
expects the Soviet Union ``to be out by February 15th.''
   Redman noted that while the Afghan rebels, known as the
Mujahedeen, ``have been exercising restraint'' in permitting an
unhampered Soviet withdrawal, the Soviets have not.
   ``We believe that similar restraint would be appropriate on the
part of the Soviet Union,'' Redman said.
   While the guerrillas have halted attacks against the departing
Soviets, they have directed their pressure against the Soviet-backed
Marxist government of President Najib.
   The spokesman described the Soviet raids as ``a practice of heavy
bombardment of Afghanistan on a daily basis.'' In addition to
bombing runs conducted from bases in Afghanistan, ``numerous
sorties'' are being conducted each day from bases inside the Soviet
Union, Redman said.
   The targeted areas appear to include cities where no Soviet
forces are present, the spokesman said.
   Redman, who has voiced similar criticism over the past several
months, called the attacks ``very heavy bombardment ... aimed at the
Afghan people, in the form of the Mujahedeen. ... It just is counter
to what the Soviets have assured us that they would do.''
   The United States is a guarantor of the U.N.-mediated agreement
signed last April under which the Soviet Union is to remove all of
its military forces by Feb. 15.
   The Moslem guerrillas, now backed by Pakistan and the United
States, began fighting after a pro-Communist coup in April 1978.
   The Soviets entered the neighboring nation in December 1979 to
help the government battle the anti-Communist rebels. Its troops
were estimated to number 115,000 when the withdrawal began May 15.
   On Sunday, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze ended a
three-day visit to Afghanistan after pledging arms supplies to
Najib's government when the remaining Soviet soldiers depart.
   Shevardnadze said the withdrawal would go ahead as scheduled and
that he believed Najib's government will cope with the insurgents on
its own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
