<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Candidate     01-24 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Candidate,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian Church Leader Nominated for Legislature</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patriarch Vazgen I, leader of Armenia's Catholics,
has been nominated to run for a seat in the Soviet parliament, Tass
reported Tuesday.
   The Soviet news agency said the Armenian church leader won the
unanimous backing of a meeting of voters in the district of
Echmiadzin, the see of the Armenian Apostolic Church. Tass said he
is the first religious worker in the history of Soviet Armenia ever
to run for a parliamentary seat.
   Vazgen is at least the second cleric nominated for a seat in the
new Congress of People's Deputies, a parliamentary body to be
elected March 26. A Russian Orthodox leader whose diocese includes
Leningrad and Estonia was nominated earlier.
   The congress will elect the national president, a post now held
by Mikhail S. Gorbachev, and members of a full-time legislature.
</TEXT>
