<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     01-24 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Namibia Peacekeeping Force Cut; More Police Included</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet complaints about costs
forced U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on Tuesday to
recommend that the United Nations slash its peacekeeping force for
Namibia to 4,650 troops.
   It will be the first U.N. attempt to guide a colony to
independence, and the world body's biggest and most expensive
peacekeeping mission since the 1960-64 Belgian Congo crisis.
   Perez de Cuellar estimated it will cost $416 million to deploy
the peacekeepers with about 800 election supervisors, an
undetermined number of civilian administrators and an augmented
force of 500 police supervisors.
   Black African and non-aligned nations for weeks have argued for
at least 7,500 troops, as indicated in a 1978 Security Council plan
for the independence of South-West Africa, better known as Namibia.
   That would have cost $700 million, U.N. officials said.
   But the Soviet Union and China abandoned their usual Third World
allies and agreed with the other permanent Security Council members
_ the United States, Britain and France _ that costs should be cut.
   Each of the five permanent members has the power to veto any
Security Council resolution, so Perez de Cuellar's report reflected
their wishes. His recommendations must go to the Security Council,
which is expected to approve.
   He suggested the Security Council keep the upper limit of the
peacekeeping contingent at 7,500, but dispatch only 4,650. Remaining
troops would be on standby in their home countries, he said.
   He authorized 500 police supervisors from U.N. member nations to
oversee the South African-trained Namibian police, who will remain
in charge of law and order during the transition to independence.
More police supervisors were needed because the police force has
nearly trebled in the past decade to a strength of 8,300, the
secretary-general said.
   At $416 million for one year, the Namibian mission will be more
expensive than the $375 million total cost of all other assessed
peacekeeping operations in 1988.
   The Congo peacekeeping mission cost $400 million from 1960-64, at
much higher dollar rates, and involved 19,828 soldiers at peak
strength.
   South Africa has administered Namibia since it captured the
mineral-rich colony from Germany in World War. Namibia's
independence comes through U.S.-brokered peace accords signed Dec.
22 by Angola, Cuba and South Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
