<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1556EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Kidney     01-24 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidney,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Suspect in Kidney Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>by VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Tuesday charged a man with
brokering the sale of kidneys for use in transplants at an exclusive
London hospital, a public prosecutor said.
   Retired military officer Tunc Ay Kunter has ``confessed to acting
as a middleman for four such operations,'' but insists he acted for
humanitarian reasons, according to the prosecutor, Sait Erel.
   The arrest follows one man's charges that one of his kidneys was
removed without his knowledge or consent at London's private
Wellington Humana hospital, Erel said.
   Turks have been angered by reports that Turkish peasants were
selling their kidneys to wealthy recipients at the London hospital.
   Turkish law allows donations of human organs, but forbids their
sale. Sellers and organizers convicted in a kidney transaction could
be jailed for up to four years, Erel said.
   National television broadcast the charges Sunday that featured a
couple who said they each sold a kidney through a middleman to
recipients at a hospital.
   One kidney was sold for the equivalent of $5,600 and the other
for $3,200, the unidentified man and woman said on the program. They
did not identify the hospital or middleman.
   Erel said Kunter, 55, was picked up at his house Monday night and
was charged Tuesday after investiagors found evidence indicating
Kunter made money out of kidney transactions. Kunter said he
arranged them for humanitarian reasons and no money was involved.
   `It is not easy to believe that he has done them just for
humanitarian reasons,'' Erel said of Kunter's defense. ``He has been
involved in a long process of taking them (organ donors) to clinics,
having their passports issued and taking them to London for
nothing.''
   Legal proceedings started after one man, Ahmet Koc from
Dogubeyazit township in eastern Turkey, claimed in a Jan. 10 letter
that Kunter tricked him to go to the Wellington Humana hospital,
where one of his kidneys was removed without his consent.
   According to Erel, Koc claimed Kunter took him to the hospital
for what was described as a checkup linked to a job offer. After the
kidney was removed, Koc said, he was paid $4,637 by Kunter's brother
in London, Ata Nur.
   Erel said he could not start legal proceedings in other kidney
sales allegedly involving Kunter unless the donors applied to his
office.
   Wellington Humana hospital has said it has no evidence that Turks
were paid money to donate kidneys.
   However, it said it was reviewing its organ transplant procedures
following the British government's announcement of an investigation
into the case.
</TEXT>
