<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-ChemicalWeapons     01-24 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Chemical Weapons,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislation Promised Against Spread of Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to penalize nations that use
chemical weapons and private companies that help produce them will
be introduced this week, Republican and Democratic senators said
Tuesday.
   The proposed action was announced at a hearing in which senators
cited reports that the West German government had looked the other
way while German industries helped Middle East nations obtain
chemical warfare capability. A U.S. official said West Germany is
now addressing the situation.
   Senators also were told that the Soviet Union is stockpiling
biological weapons in violation of a 1972 agreement banning them
worldwide.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said he will soon introduce a bill to require
U.S. diplomatic and economic sanctions against any nation using
chemical or biological weapons. He said the legislation will ask
other nations to do likewise.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said he will sponsor companion
legislation to invoke sanctions against companies of any nationality
which supply chemical warfare equipment and technology to Third
World nations.
   ``I have every reason to believe that, in the end, the Congress
and the administration will see the wisdom of both approaches,''
Helms said.
   Helms and other members of the Foreign Relations Committee
complained about reports that West German officials ignored the
situation while German chemical firms helped Libya build a chemical
plant that has been alleged to be capable of producing poison gas.
   William F. Burns, the retired Army major general who heads the
Arms Control and Disarmament Agency, testified that about 20 nations
have the capacity to produce chemical weapons, He said about five or
six are known to have used or stockpiled them.
   Responding to questions, Burns listed Iran, Iraq, Libya, Syria
and North Korea as poison gas stockpilers. He said Iraq, Iran and
Libya are reported to have used chemical weapons.
   Burns also said the United States believes the Soviet Union is
maintaining stocks of biological weapons in violation of the 1972
international agreement outlawing the manufacture and possession of
lethal biological agents.
   ``We believe the Soviet Union does have a stock of biological
weapons and obviously they must have some capacity to produce
them,'' Burns said.
   Helms asked how, in that case, the Soviets can be trusted to
adhere to a new international agreement, soon to be negotiated,
banning the manufacture, stockpiling and use of poison gas and other
chemical weapons.
   Burns replied that the 1972 agreement had no provisions for
monitoring and verifying compliance while any new pact will have
verification provisions.
   He acknowleged, however, that verification will be difficult and
that perfect monitoring probably cannot be achieved.
   Helms complained that West German companies were helping Third
World countries, especially in the Middle East, obtain chemical
weapons capability.
   He also said a West German firm is helping Libya obtain the
ability to refuel warplanes in midflight, extending their range and
giving them the ability to strike Israel.
   ``The problem is extremely grim,'' Helms said. ``With the
critical assistance of Western industrial firms, the four most
radical regimes in the world are acquiring weapons of mass
destruction.''
   Burns, who said he had discussed the situation with officials of
the West German Embassy, said the attitude of the Bonn government
has changed significantly.
   ``I believe the West German government is addressing the
problem,'' Burns said. He predicted the West German government would
erect a much stronger system of export controls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
