<FIRST>r a AM-Bundy-Scene     01-24 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy-Scene,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Macabre Carnival Atmosphere At Bundy Execution</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bundy Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GVL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A carnival atmosphere prevailed outside the
prison where Ted Bundy was executed Tuesday, as capital punishment
supporters hawked electric chair pins, sang macabre songs and
lighted sparklers.
   Nearly 100 death penalty supporters milled about a pasture at the
Florida State Prison, some even dancing over the demise of one of
the nation's most notorious killers.
   Corrections Department spokesman Bob Macmaster said the pre-dawn
crowd, including some 30 opponents of the death penalty and more
than 100 journalists, was larger than he had ever seen at an
execution.
   The frivolity offended foes of capital punishment and even some
who thought Bundy should die.
   ``I think it's fair to execute him. I just don't think it's fair
everyone is dancing around, having fun,'' said Bridgette Braswell of
Gainesville.
   ``I am shocked,'' said Anne-Marie Diller, also of Gainesvill, who
held a votive candle to protest the execution. ``I think people came
here like they were going to the fair. I'm shocked that people could
rejoice over someone's death, even if he is guilty.''
   The ``Old Sparky'' lapel pins first sold for $3 but later were
upped to $5 as the 7 a.m. execution approached.
   ``I'm here to support the death penalty. The pins are only a
sidelight,'' said the vendor, who wore a staw hat adorned with an
American flag. He said his name was Richard and that he worked in
law enforcement and did not want to give his last name for fear of
reprisals at work.
   Nearby, a man wearing a Ronald Reagan mask and a T-shirt that
read ``Toast Ted'' carried an effigy of Bundy in a noose.
   Asked to explain the joyous mood, death penalty supporter Jerry
Jackson said: ``A lot of people want to have a good time to get it
past them. It's been real heavy on a lot of people, especially on
communities in Florida.''
   About 15 people from Tallahassee, where Bundy killed two sorority
sisters at Florida State University 11 years ago, sang a song titled
``On Top of Old Sparky.'' At 7 a.m. they ignited sparklers and
hollered.
   ``If it doesn't do anything else, it's going to once and for all
get Ted Bundy out of the lives of the families he victimized,'' said
Wendy Nelson, who wore a shirt that read, ``Someone I love was
murdered.''
   Ms. Nelson's 10-year-old daughter, Elisa, was slain in 1980.
Larry Mann, convicted in the girl's death, has an appeal pending.
   ``It's not for me to critique them if they are enjoying it,'' she
said of the upbeat protesters.
</TEXT>
