<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--MilitaryStrength     01-24 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Military Strength,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strength of Armed Forces Drops to 2,121,142 in December</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pentagon-Airlift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The active-duty strength of the nation's armed
forces continued to drop slowly last month, the Pentagon said
Tuesday.
   In all, the Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force reported
2,121,142 men and women on active duty as of Dec. 31, down from
2,130,438 as of Nov. 30.
   On Dec. 31, 1987, there were 2,166,611 men and women in uniform.
   Most reductions in 1988 were made through changes in recruiting
goals, tighter re-enlistment standards and ``early out'' incentives.
   As of Dec. 31, the Navy said it had 582,692 people on active
duty, down 3,264 from Nov. 30. The Marine Corps said it had 195,027,
down 910 compared with the count on Nov. 30.
   The Army reported a decline of 6,074 to a total 765,037. The Air
Force said its active-duty strength climbed by 952 to 578,386 at the
end of December.
</TEXT>
