<DOCNO> AP890124-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-ADV--Holly Advisory   01-24 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-ADV--Holly, Advisory,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>ARTS AND ENTERTAINMENT EDITORS:</HEAD>
<HEAD>SUNDAY EDITORS:</HEAD>
<HEAD>WIRE EDITORS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>The Day the Music Died:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   When a plane crashed Feb. 3, 1959, killing Buddy Holly, Ritchie
Valens and J.P. ``Big Bopper'' Richardson, there was little written
about the careers of the legendary rockers. Today, however, the
music world has realized the important contributions each made to
rock 'n' roll, especially Holly, whose death proved to be epochal.
   Upcoming shortly is a package of stories for Sunday, Jan. 29, by
David Bauder, Wendy E. Lane and Suzanne Gamboa, looking at the
anniversary of ``the day the music died,'' and the legacy of Buddy
Holly.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Musicians and Fans Remember ``The Day the Music Died''</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   Thirty years too late, the Crickets are looking to complete the
trip their leader Buddy Holly couldn't. On Feb. 3, 1989, the band is
booked to perform in Fargo, N.D., the city Holly, Ritchie Valens and
the Big Bopper were scheduled to play 30 years ago. Instead, their
plane crashed in a snowstorm, killing all aboard. Memorialized as
``the day the music died'' in Don McLean's 1972 epic ``American
Pie,'' the plane crash was the first great rock tragedy.
   BC-AP Arts: Music Died, will move as b0719.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Holly's Widow Pursues Rocker's Dreams</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   IRVING, Texas _ Maria Elena Holly spends much of her time hunched
over a paper-piled desk in her home _ trying to make Buddy Holly's
dreams come true. The late singer, songwriter and musician, who with
his own blend of rock 'n' roll and country influenced the Beatles,
the Rolling Stones and many others, dreamed that he would inspire
young musicians and pave their way in the industry.
   BC-AP Arts: Holly's Dream, will move as b0721.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Holly Recognized in Hometown? That'll Be the Day</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ Legendary rock 'n' roller Buddy Holly influenced
generations of musicians. So does his hometown give him fitting
recognition? That'll be the day, say fans and friends. They complain
that 30 years after his death, this city takes scant notice of its
most famous native son.
   BC-AP Arts: Buddy Who? will move as b0722.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   The following will be upcoming later:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Holly Fan Club Bigger Than Ever</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ The first and only time Bill Griggs saw Buddy
Holly perform, he didn't know the bespectacled youth with a Texas
twang was the lead singer for his favorite band, the Crickets
because Holly released songs under his own name as well. Griggs
started a Holly fan club 14 years ago. The organization had more
than 400 members after its first year and now has almost 5,400
members from 31 countries who gather yearly to share memories and
swap memorabilia.
   BC-AP Arts: Fan Club, will move as b0720.
</TEXT>
