<DOCNO> AP890124-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Democrats     01-24 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prospect of Brown Victory Draws Secession Talk from Alabama Party
Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospect that a Washington attorney who
played a prominent role in Jesse Jackson's campaign will be the next
Democratic Party chairman drew talk of secession Tuesday from an
Alabama party leader.
   John Baker said the election of Ronald Brown as national party
chairman would not be ``a sign the Democratic Party is getting
better.''
   A supporter of former Rep. Jim Jones of Oklahoma for the party
chairmanship, Baker said Brown's election would be a victory for the
liberal wing of the party.
   ``You can't secede from the national party, though, frankly, I
would,'' he said. ``We'd maintain our official formal affiliation in
name only.''
   ``I'm not sure that's what we need right now,'' said James
Ruvolo, the Ohio Democratic Party chairman and a supporter of
Michigan chairman Richard Wiener for the national post.
   ``Ron Brown will bring the party together,'' said his campaign
manager Carl Wagner. ``His bottom line is to enlarge the party to
build national and regional majorities to elect and re-elect
Democrats at every level.''
   ``Mr. Baker's remarks not only surprise me, but they make me very
sad,'' said Pat Eddington, a Democratic National Committee member
from Alabama.
   Mrs. Eddington said she is neutral in the contest for the
chairmanship and added, ``I have known Ron Brown for most of the 11
years I have served on the national committee and I have found him
always to be a team player who has paid his dues to the party. He is
also a very articulate and honorable person.''
   Seeking the chairmanship along with Brown, Jones and Wiener was
former Rep. James Stanton of Ohio. Former Rep. Michael Barnes of
Maryland dropped out of the race Monday and endorsed Brown.
   Wagner said: ``Ron has made it clear again and again that he will
win with solid support across the country.''
   He said that Brown already was receiving more support from
southerners than Paul G. Kirk Jr. got four years ago when he ran for
party chairman.
   Kirk won the post despite nearly total opposition from Southern
party leaders who objected to his ties to Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass.
   But Kirk succeeded in winning over the southerners who were in
the forefront of an unsuccessful effort to convince him to serve a
second four-year term.
   The other three candidates conceded that Brown is the
front-runner in the contest that will be decided by a vote of the
national committee at a meeting in Washington on Feb. 10.
   If elected, Brown would become the first black named chairman of
either major national party.
   Brown was staff director of the Senate Judiciary Committee under
Kennedy's chairmanship. He served as Jackson's convention manager
and was widely credited with playing a key role in helping close the
convention with a show of unity between Jackson, who lost a bid for
the presidential nomination, and Michael Dukakis, the nominee.
</TEXT>
