<FIRST>u i AM-SovietQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0623 01-24 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Quake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0623,0863</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tadzhik Mountain Villagers Bury Dead; New Quake Rocks Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 17th graf, ``Zhukov said ...'' to ADD
relief efforts.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mountain villagers in ``endless'' funeral
processions Tuesday buried their dead from the Tadzhikistan
earthquake that killed up to 1,000, and rescuers slogged through
muddy rubble in a desperate search for survivors.
   New warnings were issued for more possible landslides caused by
thawing snow in the Central Asian republic 1,800 miles south of
Moscow that was hit by Monday's predawn earthquake.
   In northwestern Armenia, which was devastated by a Dec. 7 quake
that killed 25,000 people, a powerful aftershock was reported
Tuesday. An Armenian official said the population had been warned
and no casualties were reported.
   Rescuers reportedly found one survivor from the Tadzhikistan
quake, although an official spokesman denied it.
   A 40-second tremor, which U.S. seismologists registered as 5.4 on
the Richter scale, hit before dawn Monday. It loosened layers of mud
that cascaded onto mountain villages in a rural area about 20 miles
southwest of the republic's capital of Dushanbe.
   Workers using shovels and bulldozers continued digging for
survivors, Tass said, but a local official said the efforts might be
in vain.
   ``There is little hope because of the flood of dirt and mud,''
Erkin Kasymov, a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry of Tadzhikistan,
said by telephone. ``But while there is any hope, the rescuers will
keep digging.''
   In one village, Sharora, more than 100 bodies have been hauled
from the mud and wreckage, Tass said. It said rescuers found only
one survivor, Sergei Muratov, 27.
   Muratov, reported to be in grave condition, was rushed to a
hospital, where ``surgeons are fighting for his life,'' Tass said.
   However, Vitaly Zhukov of the republic's official news agency and
chief of a press information center set up in the wake of the
tragedy, told The Associated Press no survivors were found during
excavations Tuesday.
   Zainiddin Nasreddinov, editor-in-chief of the news agency,
estimated that about 600 people, or about Sharora's entire
population, had been killed in the village.
   Tass on Monday estimated that 1,000 people had been killed, and
official reports said more than 100 people were hospitalized in
Dushanbe.
   The predominantly Moslem villagers buried their dead, and ``the
funeral processions seem endless,'' the Tass news agency said.
   Zhukov said 11 people died overnight in hospitals. Late Tuesday,
amid reports that casualties might not be as high as initially
reported, he said the preliminary estimate remained at 1,000 dead.
   He added, however, that it was still too early to determine how
many people had been buried in the slide.
   Sharora and three other villages located at the quake's epicenter
_ Okuli-Bolo, Okuli-Poyen and Khisor _ are now wreathed in the smoke
of bonfires and field kitchens, Tass said.
   Zhukov said the republic will need about 400 prefabricated houses
for survivors in the stricken villages. He told The AP, however,
that although several neighboring republics and rescue teams from
Armenia had offered assistance, local authorities had not yet
determined just what help would be needed.
   Tass said the Soviet Red Cross sent a planeload of relief
supplies to the region and that the Armenian Red Cross announced it
would send a rescue team to Tadzhikistan. The plane carried four
tons of tents, clothing, blankets, household goods and medical
supplies, the news agency said.
   The television news program ``Vremya'' said a special bank
account had been set up in Moscow to accept voluntary contributions
to aid quake victims.
   The Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda blamed heavy snows
followed by a thaw for saturating the Babatag hills overlooking the
villages of Sharora, Okuli-Bolo and Okuli-Poyen, and said much of
the mud was carried to the villages by an earthen canal.
   Pravda said the soil in the canal's walls was saturated with
moisture, and that when the quake hit, it ``moved in a huge mass
onto the villages.''
   ``There is a danger of new mudslides in similar places in the
event of a new natural blow,'' the Communist Party paper said.
   Ruben Karagyosyan, a spokesman for the official Politburo
commission created to direct the relief effort for the Armenian
earthquake, said 10 aftershocks had been registered Monday night and
Tuesday morning, including one the same magnitude as Tadzhikistan's
quake.
   Tass said the epicenter of the aftershock, which occurred at 5:30
a.m. Moscow time (9:30 p.m. EST Monday), was northwest of Kirovakan,
one of the Armenian cities heavily damaged by the Dec. 7 quake.
   ``Our scientists had already warned the government and the
population over television and through the press that aftershocks in
the zone of the quake were predicted,'' Karagyosyan said in a
telephone interview from Yerevan, Armenia's capital.
   Residents of the quake zone had been warned not to congregate in
kindergartens, schools and other buildings, he said. ``So there were
no serious consequences.'' He said no deaths or injuries had been
reported.
   Powerful aftershocks were registered in Armenia on Dec. 31 and
Jan. 4, Karagyosyan said.
</TEXT>
