<FIRST>r i AM-Kollek     01-24 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kollek,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Teddy Kollek Running For Sixth Term in Jerusalem</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Teddy Kollek announced Tuesday he will run
for a sixth term in increasingly tense Jerusalem, the Arab and
Jewish city where he has championed unity for 23 years.
   ``One day I hope Arabs will also participate in elections,''
Kollek says. ``This is a united city and will remain a united city,
with equal rights to Arabs.''
   As part of his campaign platform for the Feb. 28 election, Kollek
promises to continue providing equal services to Jewish and Arab
parts of the city.
   The 77-year-old mayor has faced increasing urban tension in the
past year as Palestinian riots erupted in Arab east Jerusalem.
   Palestinians in East Jerusalem generally have not run for the
council and most do not exercise their right to vote. The number
voting this year is expected to drop even further because of the
uprising against Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, now in its 13th month.
   Jerusalem police have clamped curfews on Arab neighborhoods on at
least three separate occasions during the past year, and there have
been numerous rock and firebomb attacks on Israelis.
   Police, however, have refrained from using live ammunition during
protests, and there has been only one Arab death in East Jerusalem
compared with 367 in the West Bank and Gaza.
   Kollek on Tuesday denied he initiated a recent proposal to move
Arab polling booths to West Jerusalem in an attempt to attract
moderate Palestinians who wish to vote away from the eyes of
militant neighbors who oppose participation. The proposal has been
scrapped.
   The popular mayor is virtually guaranteed to win another
five-year term in office, but he faces an uphill battle to hold on
to his narrow majority in the 31-member City Council, where
ultra-Orthodox and right-wing elements control almost half the seats.
</TEXT>
