<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildCare     01-24 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Care,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats, Hatch Unveil Revised $2.5 Billion Child-Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic senators joined a conservative
Republican Tuesday in introducing a revised $2.5 billion child-care
package aimed at satisfying President Bush and the GOP lawmakers who
blocked an earlier version.
   ``On behalf of America's children, we senators have extended a
political olive branch,'' said Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn.,
chief sponsor of the measure. He predicted the bill would serve as
the basis for an eventual compromise that could win congressional
passage and be signed by the new president.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said, ``We still have some differing
views, but we agree that it is time to address the growing concern
of millions of American families over the lack of affordable,
quality child care.''
   ``I am not co-sponsoring this bill because I think it is a
perfect solution,'' Hatch said. ``Rather, it signals the
continuation of the discussions we began last fall.''
   He said differences remain over financing and establishing
child-care standards.
   The legislation is based on last year's Act for Better Child Care
Services, which was designed to help low-income Americans pay for
child care, to expand the supply of child care and to assure minimum
standards of health, safety and staff training at child-care centers.
   Following months of negotiations between Hatch and Democratic
senators led by Dodd, the lawmakers added new provisions that would
give states more of the money to improve the quality and
availability of child care. The amount of aid going directly to
families decreases from 75 percent to 70 percent.
   The revised bill also would make grandparents, aunts and uncles
eligible for reimbursement; provide grants and loans to family
day-care and non-profit providers to establish and expand programs;
create a state-based revolving loan fund for new family providers,
and increase participation by state and local officials, employers
and religious groups on an advisory committee that will recommend
minimum standards.
   ``We're willing to compromise because it's in America's best
interests,'' said Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., who described
likened the lengthy negotiations to ``being in a bunker.''
   Dodd, who was bitterly disappointed last October when Republicans
held up the child-care legislation, said negotiations since last
year's defeat had produced ``a remarkable degree of onsensus.''
   He also expressed optimism over the change at the White House,
calling the Bush administration's attitudes on child care ``180
degrees different'' from the Reagan administration's.
   Dodd said, ``We have a new president who wants a kinder and
gentler nation and is willing to invest the money to make it happen.
We have a new leadership in the Senate which is committed to
enacting a child-care bill this year. And right here in the Labor
Committee we have an opportunity for the kind of bipartisan
cooperation which comes along rarely in a politician's career.''
   During the presidential campaign, Democrat Michael Dukakis backed
the Democratic bill while Bush proposed tax credits for families,
which could be used either to pay for outside child care or to
enable a mother to stay home instead of working.
   Dodd, speaking at a news conference with Hatch, said he will back
the Utah Republican's legislation for a tax credit but the Democrat
said such a plan was only part of the solution.
   ``It would not help this nation with our real challenge in the
child care arena _ to build a diverse system of child-care providers
with predictable standards of health and safety,'' Dodd said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
