<DOCNO> AP890124-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1901EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     01-24 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Wins Ratings Again With Big Super Bowl Boost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's coverage of the Super Bowl game far
outdistanced all other shows in the Nielsen television ratings for
the week ended Jan. 22., keeping the network in the No. 1. spot for
the 31st consecutive week.
   The football game, in which the San Francisco 49ers defeated the
Cincinnati Bengals, 20-16, pulled a rating of 44.6 and a 66 percent
share of the audience watching television. That means more than 40
million homes tuned in.
   The postgame show was second in the weekly A.C. Nielsen Co.
ratings, with 32.5 and a 49 share.
   The ratings figures were provided by CBS. Although all networks
receive the same raw ratings data from Nielsen, each network may
interpret the results differently. NBC's interpretation gave its
Super Bowl game coverage a 43.5 rating and a 68 share.
   The nearest regular show was NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' which was
third, with a rating of 25.3 and a 39 share. In all, NBC had eight
of the Top 10 shows and handily won the week.
   ABC's ``Roseanne,'' the biggest new hit of the season, was fifth
behind NBC's fourth-place ``Cheers.'' ABC's ``Who's the Boss?'' was
sixth, as ABC came in second.
   CBS, which placed third, had only one show in the Top 20. Its
coverage of the inaugural gala in Washington was 20th. Its usually
high-rated Sunday show, ``Murder, She Wrote,'' was knocked to 46th
place by the Super Bowl coverage.
   Other shows in the Top 10, all NBC: ``A Different World,''
seventh place; ``Golden Girls,'' eighth; ``Brotherhood of the
Rose,'' Part I, ninth; and ``L.A. Law,'' tenth. ``Cosby,'' ``Who's
the Boss?,'' ``A Different World'' and ``Golden Girls'' were all
reruns.
   NBC won the week with an average of 20.0. ABC was second with
12.1 and CBS was third with 12.0.
   In the season to date, NBC is first with 15.6, ABC is second with
13.0, and CBS is third with 12.4.
   Each ratings point equals 904,000 homes with television. The
share is a percentage of the sets in use.
   The premiere of NBC's ``Father Dowling Mysteries'' was in 33rd
place, while the premiere of CBS' ``Dolphin Cove'' was 49th. A
preview of NBC's ``Nightingales'' placed 24th and a preview of ABC's
``A Fine Romance'' was 56th.
   The ABC movie ``The Ryan White Story'' was 21st in the ratings,
and Bob Hope's Super Bowl special was 29th.
   NBC also won seven places in the second 10 shows. The rank: NBC's
``Unsolved Mysteries,'' ABC's ``Growing Pains,'' NBC's ``In the Heat
of the Night,'' NBC's ``Dear John,'' ABC's ``Head of the Class,''
NBC's ``Matlock,'' NBC's ``ALF,'' NBC's movie ``The Cover Girl and
the Cop,'' NBC's ``Night Court'' and CBS' ``Inaugural Gala.''
   The three network nightly news shows were in a close race: ABC
first with a rating of 11.7, CBS second with 11.6, and NBC third
with 11.5.
   The lowest-rated show of the week was CBS's ``TV 101.'' The
bottom five shows in descending order were: ABC's ``All-Star Salute
to the Reagans,'' ABC's ``Knightwatch,'' CBS' ``Viva Miami: Super
Sounds,'' ABC's movie ``Herbie Goes Bananas'' and ``TV 101.''
</TEXT>
