<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Jogging     01-24 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Jogging,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Jogs at Army Base; Motorcade Stops at Red Lights</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush interrupted his second full working
day at the White House Tuesday to take his first presidential jog,
running for 23 minutes on the grounds of a nearby Army base.
   It took a motorcade of 15 cars to get the president from the
White House to Fort McNair, a distance of about two miles. At Bush's
request, the motorcade did something presidential motorcades almost
never do: It stopped at red traffic lights along the way.
   Bruce Zanca, an aide to Bush, said the president was merely
following a practice he established as vice president. ``Mr. Bush's
preference as vice president was to stop at lights, keep things as
normal as possible,'' Zanca said.
   As vice president, Bush jogged for 20 minutes every second or
third day. But he usually did so on the sprawling grounds of the
vice presidential residence at the U.S. Naval Observatory.
   There is not nearly as much room at the White House compound.
   The president ran in bright orange jogging pants and a gray
long-sleeved top. With the temperature in the high 50s _ unusually
balmy for January in Washington _ Bush was perspiring lightly as he
finished his run.
   When a reporter suggested he was taking it fairly slowly, the
president responded, ``Wouldn't know it from watching the speed of
this thing.'' It was an apparent reference to his limousine, which
was being driven slightly ahead of him as he neared the end of his
jog.
</TEXT>
