<DOCNO> AP890124-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Ethics     01-24 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Ethics,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>All Senior Administration Officials to be Briefed on Ethics Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Tuesday asked the head of the
Office of Government Ethics to brief all senior administration
officials on ethical and conflict-of-interest standards required of
them, the White House said.
   Bush, who has pledged to make government ethics a high priority
in his administration, accepted OGE Director Frank Nebeker's offer
of Nov. 9 that Nebeker arrange for personal briefings of senior
officials and White House staff members to let them know the
guidelines on such matters as outside income, White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said.
   The idea of such briefings was one that Bush proposed during his
campaign.
   Bush, who has charged his legal counsel, Boyden Gray, with
coordinating the ethics policy, has scheduled an activity on the
ethics issue each day this week. Fitzwater acknowledged that
Tuesday's meeting wtih Nebeker, which lasted just 10 minutes, was
symbolic and intended to keep the spotlight on the ethics issue.
   On Wednesday, Bush was to officially name members of an advisory
commission on ethics, Fitzwater said. The advisory commission was to
be created by executive order and chaired by Griffin Bell, the
former attorney general in the Carter administration, and Malcolm
Wilkey, a senior judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington,
White House officials have said.
   On Thursday the president will meet with senior executive
employees to ``emphasize the ethics provisions of the law and their
responsibilities and what he expects of them.''
   He made a similar speech on Monday to White House appointees and
to his Cabinet, saying he wanted to avoid even the appearance of
impropriety.
   On Friday, Fitzwater said Bush will talk to the inspectors
general of the government departments to emphasize their role in the
ethics area and stress how much importance he is placing on the
matter.
   The Reagan administration was tarnished with allegations of a
``sleaze factor'' because of the many officials who were accused of
wrongdoing and unethical conduct. Bush repeatedly has attempted to
stress that he wants an administraiton that will avoid that kind of
reproach.
   However, Bush, as vice president, supported President Reagan's
veto of ethics legislation passed by Congress last year. He has said
he wants to introduce his own package.
   The task of Bush's commission will be to recommend what should be
in that legislation. Bush has said he wants the same standards that
are set for the executive branch to apply to Congress where
applicable.
   He made many recommendations during his campaign last year for
ethics revisions, including the naming of a senior presidential
counselor on the issue, and establishing an ethics office and staff
in each cabinet department and agency.
   Among the other members of the seven-member commission will be
former White House counsels Fred Fielding and Lloyd Cutler, and
Washington attorney Jan Baran, said White House spokeswoman Alixe
Glen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
