<FIRST>r a AM-CoupleFound     01-24 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Couple Found,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Couple To Remain In Hospital After Ordeal At Sea</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly couple whose day fishing trip
turned into three days at sea and nearly two on an uninhabited
island before they were rescued will stay in a hospital for several
days, officials said Tuesday.
   A spokesman for Beaufort Memorial Hospital said Thomas Pettigrew,
81, was in stable condition and was being kept for observation.
Hospital officials said he may have suffered a heart attack on the
boat or the island.
   Pettigrew's 80-year-old wife, Katie, was released from the
hospital Tuesday but will remain with her husband in his room.
   The couple left Charleston on their 18-foot fiberglass boat
Thursday for the fishing trip.
   The boat was blown out to sea and, after being tossed about in
12-foot waves, washed up late Saturday on Bay Point Island about 50
miles southwest of Charleston.
   The couple, who left with only enough food for one day, was
rescued by a Marine helicopter on a training mission late Monday
afternoon.
   The Coast Guard searched for the couple through high seas and
from the air from Friday through late Sunday, when the effort was
called off.
   The helicopter took them to the hospital. They originally
suffered from dehydration and exposure. They said they had drank sea
water to moisten their mouths.
   Pettigrew, a retired security officer, said Tuesday, ``I wasn't
afraid of anything. I had my .38 (caliber pistol) with me _ my
ex-service revolver.''
   He said seeing the Marine helicopter late Monday ``was worth all
the tea in China.''
   A helicopter passed over the couple late Saturday after they
washed ashore but didn't see them. They were able to flag down the
chopper Monday by using a white flag they had fashioned out of rags.
   ``The helicopter circled around and I kept waving,'' Mrs.
Pettigrew said. ``It seemed like heaven had opened up.
   ``We prayed a lot. There was nothing out there but the sky and
water,'' she said.
   Pettigrew said he built a bonfire when their boat washed up on
the island and while planes went over ``we couldn't get a hold of
anybody. The area we were in _ nobody goes by out there.''
   The only animals the couple saw on the island were goats. Lt.
Quain Kahler of the Charleston Coast Guard Base said a caretaker's
cottage with food was about 500 yards off the beach, but the couple
didn't find it.
</TEXT>
