<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     01-24 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A depiction of children who watch too much
television as ``couch potatoes'' has drawn a tongue-in-cheek yelp of
protest _ that potatoes deserve better.
   In October, the American Academy of Pediatrics began broadcasting
nationwide an animated public service announcement depicting two
children sitting on a couch watching television.
   ``Couch potato, too much TV couch potato, avoid this dreaded
disease,'' is sung in the background.
   Peter Kress, public relations director of the Maine Department of
Agriculture, fired off a letter to the academy and the networks,
saying he wanted them to know that potatoes are good food.
   ``We simply had to let you know that potatoes and potato people
are not lacking in nutritional or personal energy,'' he wrote. ``We
appeal to you to reconsider using the couch potato reference.''
   After all, potatoes are Maine's largest cash crop. More than 2.3
billion pounds of spuds are harvested each year, reaping $98.8
million for the state's farmers, who don't spend a lot of time on
the couch.
   Michele Weber, a spokeswoman for the Illinois-based academy,
noted her group did not coin the phrase ``couch potato'' and said
the commercial was not intended to offend anyone.
</TEXT>
