<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle     01-24 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle to Visit Venezuela, El Salvador Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle will be the first
Bush administration representative to make an official foreign
visit, going next week to Venezuela and El Salvador, the White House
announced Tuesday.
   The Feb. 1-3 trip was timed so that Quayle can attend the
presidential inaguration of Venezuela's Carlos Andres Perez on Feb.
2.
   Others scheduled to attend the inauguration are Cuban President
Fidel Castro and Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega.
   Other details were sketchy, and Quayle's chief of staff Robert
Guttman said it was still being determined what individuals Quayle
would meet during his brief El Salvador stop.
   He is to arrive in and leave the Central American nation on Feb.
3.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the El Salvador
stop was added so that Quayle could discuss the elections there in
March, and ``extend the best wishes of President Bush who has known
President (Jose Napoleon) Duarte for a number of years and meet with
other officials as appropriate.''
   Fitzwater said Quayle would express the concern for ``the
democratic process there and seeing it continue as it has under
President Duarte. We have concern about the guerrilla activity in El
Salvador and any threats that that may have in the election process
and I'm sure the vice president will discuss that with him.''
   The Salvadorean elections are March 19. Duarte is
constitutionally barred from seeking office again, but is backing
fellow Christian Democrat Fidel Chavez Mena, a former foreign
minister.
   Chavez faces Alfredo Cristiani of the rightist Republican
National Alliance Party, known by its Spanish acronym ARENA and
headed by controversial Roberto D'Abuisson.
   Polls have said the ARENA candidate is leading. That has caused
U.S. officials concern that an ARENA victory could further polarize
the war-torn country and make it more difficult to get further aid
to El Salvador through Congress.
   On Tuesday, Quayle visited Capitol Hill, where he told his old
congressional colleagues that his golf game is suffering as he
develops skills he needs in his new job.
   ``I used to give you strokes, but no more,'' Quayle told Rep. Bob
Michel, R-Ill., the House minority leader and another avid golfer.
   Michel introduced Quayle to the GOP leadership, and members
tossed around some jokes about what House Republicans want from the
new vice president: appearances at fund-raisers, friends appointed
to Bush administration jobs, and tickets to events.
   ``How are you at funerals?'' asked one, poking fun at the
assignment of vice presidents to attend funerals of foreign leaders.
   ``I think I'm going to be very good,'' Quayle replied.
   Quayle spent most of his day Tuesday with congressional leaders,
first at a bipartisan meeting with President Bush at the White House
and then posing for pictures with House and Senate Republicans and
Democrats in a series of courtesy calls.
</TEXT>
