<HEAD>Episcopal Church Appoints First Female Bishop</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Episcopal officials Tuesday approved the election
of the first woman bishop in the 2,000-year tradition of apostolic
succession, a line of bishops dating to Christ and his apostles.
   The approval of the election of Episcopal Bishop-elect Barbara
Harris brought a woman into that long line maintained by
Anglicanism, including the U.S. Episcopal Church, and Roman
Catholicism and Eastern Orthodoxy. Both the Catholic Church and
Eastern Orthodox churches bar women from the clergy.
   Her elevation as a suffragen, or assistant, bishop in the
denomination's Boston diocese sharply upset many conservatives
throughout the Episcopal Church but was hailed as progress by many
others.
   Her ``consecration will be both a momentous and solemn occasion
and a time of great joy and celebration,'' said the denomination's
top officer, Presiding Bishop Edmond L. Browning.
   His statement came after a majority of 60 of the church's 118
U.S. bishops gave their consent for her elevation, following
previous approval by a majority of the diocesan standing committees.
   The 60th vote was received by mail Tuesday afternoon, said the
Rev. James Solheim, spokesman for the Boston diocese. The approval
process, which began about three weeks ago after confirmation from a
majority of standing committees around the country, moved slower
than expected, Solheim said.
   Harris has declined to discuss her election until after it is
formally approved. She has an unlisted telephone number of because
of several threatening calls she received after the election.
   Harris had been elected Sept. 24 by a Massachusetts diocesan
convention.
   The election of Harris, 58, a divorced former public relations
executive, reverberated throughout world Anglicanism.
   Browning, in a statement from his office in New York, said most
of the churchwide consideration of Harris had been in a ``spirit of
prayerful discussion and sensitivity.'' But, he said, there also
were some ``angry words, some mean-spirited words and some
threatening words.''
   ``I have found this both inappropriate to the process and
diminishing to the sense of how we should conduct ourselves,'' he
said.
   The denomination approved women priests and bishops in 1976.
Since then, about 1,200 women have been ordained as priests in the
Episcopal Church.
   Critics said Harris was too liberal in her political views.
Others criticized her lack of college degree or seminary training,
while church conservatives said that under no circumstances would
they support any woman for bishop.
   Supporters said Harris was qualified for the job and her election
would broaden the scope of the church's outreach.
   Harris, who is black, was ordained a priest in Philadelphia in
1980 after studying theology through correspondence courses and with
tutors. In addition to her parish work, she recently headed the
Episcopal Church Publishing Co.
   Her election was termed as contributing to a ``final crisis for
the church'' in a pastoral letter from seven bishops of the
Evangelical and Catholic Mission, an Episcopal group that opposes
female priests and bishops.
   A compromise on the issue of female bishops was worked out in
July when the Episcopal Church's governing convention in Detroit
approved a measure allowing any congregation rejecting a woman
bishop to petition for a male ``Episcopal visitor'' bishop to
administer confirmations.
   But the woman bishop still would make periodic visits to such a
congregation, as required by church law.
   Harris' consecration ceremony is planned for Feb. 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
