<DOCNO> AP890124-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AutoInsurance     01-24 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Insurance,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Group Renews Fight for No-Fault Car Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No-fault auto insurance would save motorists
$3.7 billion nationwide, perhaps hundreds of dollars per family in
some states, a new consumer group estimated Tuesday in announcing a
campaign to convert all states to no-fault.
   ``Something must be done to break the 20-year cycle of madness
that has produced constant auto insurance crises,'' said Virginia
Knauer, leader of the organization, New Start.
   Ms. Knauer served presidents Nixon, Ford and Reagan as special
assistant for consumer affairs.
   The group said it was still working on estimates for separate
states and could not say how much individual drivers would save. It
said its estimate of nationwide savings was based on 1987 data from
the states.
   Something close to true no-fault auto insurance, first proposed
in a 1965 book by Robert Keaton and Jeffrey O'Connell, has been
adopted only in Michigan, New York and Florida, the group said.
Eleven other states have variants which Ms. Knauer called ``phony
no-fault,'' and 12 more use elements of no-fault plans in
traditional insurance law.
   Skyrocketing premiums have become politically controversial in
several states. California voters last fall passed a referendum
requiring companies to reduce premiums 20 percent.
   Nationwide, auto insurance premiums increased 60 percent from
1982 to 1987 while the Consumer Price Index was increasing 17
percent, the group said.
   Under traditional insurance, people involved in accidents often
file lawsuits to determine who was at fault and whose insurance
company must pay.
   Critics say this overcompensates the slightly injured,
undercompensates the gravely hurt, clogs the courts with lawsuits
that take years to reach verdicts and, according to a 1985
Transportation Department study, returns to victims only half of
premium payments. The rest goes to lawyers and to people who
administer the system.
   New Start said studies showed Michigan victims get 73 cents of
every premium dollar and New York victims get 60 cents.
   Bill Wagner of Tampa, Fla., president of the Association of
American Trial Lawyers, said of the new group and its contentions,
``If this entity could come up with a way to ensure fair treatment
to injured people by depriving them of their right to court, I'd be
for it.''
   Under no-fault, victims rapidly see ``the economic power of the
insurance companies used to deprive them of all their rights,'' he
said.
   In a no-fault system, victims file claims against their own
companies and are compensated by them regardless of who is at fault.
All 14 no-fault states restrict the right to sue.
   Michigan, New York and Florida limit lawsuits to people who have
suffered ``serious and permanent'' injury. This restriction greatly
reduces the number of suits, the group said.
   The other 11 states set a dollar threshold, ranging up to $6,000.
People who suffer losses greater than that may sue.
   The states: Colorado $500, Connecticut $400, Georgia $500, Hawaii
$6,000, Kansas $2,000, Kentucky $1,000, Massachusetts $500,
Minnesota $4,000, New Jersey $1,700, North Dakota $2,500 and Utah
$3,000.
   ``Monetary thresholds have proven ineffective because they
encourage abuses _ excessive medical treatment, inflated bills and,
in some cases, outright fraud _ to reach the required dollar
amount,'' New Start said.
   Ms. Knauer said she would invite heads of insurance companies to
meet with her next month before she begins a cross-country tour to
drum up support.
   ``I think the experience of the past 20 years suggests that
little can be accomplished which benefits the consumer by drawing a
line, and standing there shouting across the divide at insurance
companies,'' she said. ``They clearly are part of the problem, but
if we are to get anywhere, they equally clearly must be part of the
solution.''
   James L. Brown, director of the Center for Consumer Affairs at
the University of Wisconsin and one of the two founders of New Start
with the Rev. Robert J. McEwen, professor of economics at Boston
College, said no insurance industry funds had gone into organizing
the new group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
