<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Africans 1stLd-Writethru a0634 01-24 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Africans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Release Last Jailed African Student</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf `Dosso said...' to fix typo in name Dosoo. Pick
up 5th, `He said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Tuesday released the last of three
African students arrested after a Dec. 24 campus brawl that
triggered anti-African protests in several cities.
   The action comes one day before Mali President Moussa Traore, who
also is executive president of the Organization of African Unity,
arrives in China for a state visit. The OAU had criticized China's
handling of the racially tinged fight and later protests.
   Alex Dosoo of Ghana said in a telephone interview from the
eastern city of Nanking that he was released Tuesday from a guest
house where he was held in a guarded room for the last 11 days of
his 25-day captivity. The first two weeks he spent in jail.
   Dosoo said authorities still maintain he seriously injured a
Chinese man in the Dec. 24 fight at Nanking's Hehai University. He
denies the charge.
   He said police told him he was being freed ``because I have been
of good conduct ... and mostly in the interests of relations between
African countries and China.''
   Dosoo, a second-year engineering student, said he was told he can
continue his studies, but that he wants to return home.
   Ghana had protested Dosoo's arrest and said it might pull out its
26 students in China. Officials at its embassy in Beijing could not
immediately be reached Tuesday night for comment on Dosoo's release.
   Alpha Robinson of Gambia and Dossoumou Boni Lodovic of Benin were
held in disciplinary detention for two weeks on charges of ``trying
to stir up trouble'' during the fight. China initially ordered them
to leave China but later reversed itself. Robinson left and
officials have been trying to persuade Lodovic to stay.
   The reversal of the expulsions and Dosoo's release appeared
intended to soothe any ill will with African countries, whom China
long has courted in pursuit of Third World solidarity.
   Many African embassies also have seemed unwilling to criticize
China openly over the events, even while privately complaining about
China's handling of them.
   Traore's visit, his third to China since 1973, was planned before
the Nanking clash.
   According to Chinese officials, the Dec. 24 fight began when
African students at the Hehai campus gate refused to register
Chinese girlfriends they were bringing to a school dance. China says
the Africans attacked school guards and Chinese students, and that
11 Chinese and two Africans were hurt.
   However, African students say Chinese students attacked the
Africans first.
   Dosoo said Chinese hit him with umbrellas and he kicked one in
self-defense. He said after fleeing the area that he and a friend
were attacked by more than two dozen Chinese, and that one hit him
in the head, causing a wound that required stitches.
   Hundreds of Chinese students stoned the Africans' dormitories.
Throughout the week, thousands of Chinese marched through Nanking
shouting ``Kill the black devils!''
   Smaller confrontations involving alleged racism against African
students occurred in Beijing and two other cities, and nearly 500
Africans at one Beijing school have been boycotting classes since
Jan. 4 in protest.
   Eric Akumiah of Ghana, president of the Nanking branch of the
General Union of African Students in China, said about half of the
approximately 140 Africans studying in the city have returned to
classes in the past two weeks at their embassies' orders.
   He said only about 40 remain determined to leave China, including
himself.
   ``The Chinese are trying to ... just cover it up, be cool. That
is not the ultimate solution,'' he said. ``Today it's Nanking. Maybe
it will calm down. But it will come up again soon.
   ``The problem is the Chinese are unwilling to accept that there
is any trace of racism in China, and if you don't identify your
problem you can't solve it.''
   About 1,500 Africans are studying in China, many on scholarships
from Chinese government. Many report taunting from Chinese about
their dark skin. Several smaller clashes have occurred between
African and Chinese students in recent years, but Chinese officials
deny any racial element.
   Akumiah said the union had planned to send a student delegation
to meet Traore but authorities were not allowing African students to
board trains without passes from their schools.
</TEXT>
