<FIRST>r w AM-US-WarsawPact     01-24 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Warsaw Pact,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Hails East Germany's Proposed Military Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government on Tuesday hailed East
Germany's proposed cuts in military spending and troop strength,
saying such moves could provide good momentum for upcoming
negotiations on reducing conventional military forces in Europe.
   ``We welcome the announcement of the proposed cuts ... especially
if they are implemented in such a way that both GDR (German
Democratic Republic) and Warsaw Pact forces begin to become
defensive in their structure and doctrine,'' State Department
spokesman Charles Redman told reporters.
   Erich Honnecker, leader of the Warsaw Pact nation, announced on
Monday that his country would reduce its armed forces by 10,000 and
cut military spending by 10 percent.
   This follows Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's announcement
last month before the United Nations General Assembly that he
planned to slash Soviet forces in Eastern Europe by 50,000 men and
5,000 tanks.
   ``The Soviet and East German unilateral reductions, if
implemented, could give good momentum to the new conventional
talks,'' Redman said.
   Redman argued that Honnecker's announcement amounted to ``the
acknowledgement of the existence of Warsaw Pact conventional
superiority in Europe.''
   Saying the United States has often pressed for asymmetrical
reductions to eliminate the East-bloc superiority in troops and
tanks, Redman added that ``we thus doubly welcome the GDR's
announcement as confirmation that our approach to conventional arms
control in Europe is the proper one.''
   The spokesman said the administration looks forward to beginning
the conventional arms talks, set to start in March in Vienna.
</TEXT>
