<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     01-24 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy U.S. Wheat, Nearly Exhausting Purchase Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
635,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, virtually
wiping out its current purchase authority, the Agriculture
Department said Tuesday.
   Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was part
of 2 million tons authorized Dec. 23 under the Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP.
   The wheat was bought under a long-term supply agreement.
   Goldthwait said the wheat is for shipment in February and March.
Counting some wheat left over from previous arrangements, the
Soviets have only 35,200 tons still available under the program.
   With the latest sales, the Soviets have bought about 1.65 million
tons of U.S. wheat for delivery in the sixth year of the pact. The
agreement expired last Sept. 30 but was later extended through Dec.
31, 1990.
   The arrangement allows exporters to sell wheat and other
designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in
order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free
government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or
subsidies.
   Last year, U.S. corn sales to the Soviet Union totaled slightly
less than 5.2 million tons. Wheat sales in 1987-88, all subsidized,
totaled slightly more than 9 million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 635,000 tons of
wheat would be about 23.3 million bushels.
   Wheat prices at the farm have been averaging more than $4 per
bushel, according to recent USDA market figures, making the new sale
worth an estimated $93 million.
   Besides the wheat for 1988-89 delivery under the pact, the
Soviets have ordered 10.2 million tons of corn, 450,000 tons of
soybeans, and 1,132,500 tons of soybean meal, plus 500,000 tons of
grain sorghum. Only the wheat is subsidized.
   Goldthwait said the wheat sales will carry an average subsidy
rate of $23.05 per ton, or about 63 cents per bushel. He said the
bonuses on the 635,000 tons of wheat will be paid to seven
companies: Cargill Inc., 75,000 tons; Continental Grain Co.,
100,000; Garnac Grain Co., 25,000; Ferruzzi U.S.A. Inc., 300,000;
Toepfer International, 50,000; Union Equity Cooperative Exchange,
50,000, and Louis Dreyfus Corp., 35,000.
</TEXT>
