<HEAD>Kabul Radio Claims 711 Guerrillas Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's official radio claimed
Tuesday that government forces killed 711 Moslem guerrillas in the
previous 24 hours, 377 of them along the Salang Highway between the
capital and the Soviet border.
   No confirmation was available. Western observers usually describe
the radio's casualty claims as exaggerated.
   Kabul radio also said guerrilla commander Ahmad Shah Masoud,
called ``Lion of the Panjshir'' by his men, had looted 517 trucks
and burned 89 in the past nine months. It accused him of banditry.
   The Salang Highway runs through the Panjshir Valley. Severe food
and fuel shortages have resulted from insurgent attacks on convoys
along the highway, which carries departing Soviet soldiers home and
supplies to Kabul, the capital.
   Under a U.N.-mediated agreement, the Soviet military withdrawal
from Afghanistan is to be completed by Feb. 15.
