<FIRST>r a AM-Bundy-SororityHouse     01-24 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy-Sorority House,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mood At Sorority House One Of Relief, Sadness</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Kirk B. Cocke, Mrs. Cocke, cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security remains tight at the sorority
house where Ted Bundy killed two women 11 years ago, but current
residents were little troubled by his execution, an adviser said
Tuesday.
   ``They hope that they will be allowed to put this behind them,''
Kirk B. Cocke said.
   Security measures were evident as Mrs. Cocke, a former president
of Chi Omega National as well as a former adviser to the Florida
State University chapter, dealt with reporters Tuesday after Bundy's
morning execution.
   Once she stepped out of the house to talk with journalists, she
couldn't get back in without ringing the bell. And she couldn't
leave the door open without setting off a burglar alarm.
   The current sorority sisters were in grammar school when Margaret
Bowman, 21, and Lisa Levy, 20, were bludgeoned to death by Bundy on
Jan. 15, 1978. Two other students also were attacked but survived.
   ``So they really don't know anything about it except, of course,
they're conscious of all the attention,'' Mrs. Cocke said.
   Bundy was executed for the February 1978 death of 12-year-old
Kimberly Leach of Lake City, his last victim. But he also was
sentenced to death in the sorority house killings.
   ``I simply had breakfast with them this morning and talked to
them and answered their questions,'' Mrs. Cocke said.
   ``They're taking this with a great deal of calmness and poise and
dignity, I think.''
   Of Bundy's execution, she said: ``There was no feeling of
jubilation on part of the girls. It was more sadness and relief than
anything.''
   She said she didn't believe the current sorority sisters think
too much about Bundy's ramage.
   ``There are memorials in the house for the two girls that were
killed, and every year there's an award given in memory of the two
girls who were killed to the most outstanding Chi Omega,'' she said.
``But other than that they really don't think about it one way or
the other.''
   However, the last week, since Gov. Bob Martinez signed Bundy's
fourth death warrant Jan. 17, has been tense, according to Mrs.
Cocke.
   ``I think the attention it has created has made it worse on the
girls,'' she said, adding that it's difficult for them to answer the
many questions about how they feel and what they think of the case.
   Mrs. Cocke, who taught business management at Florida State
University at the time of the murders, knew both of the victims and
was one of the many adults who helped the sorority sisters after the
attack.
   ``It was a terribly traumatic time, terribly traumatic. Of
course, it was about six weeks or two months before he was caught so
that was a time of great tension. But even then the girls took it
with a great deal of dignity and grace. And they faced death for the
first time in their young lives.''
</TEXT>
