<HEAD>Powerful Quake Aftershock Recorded in Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful aftershock was reported Tuesday in
northwestern Armenia, where an earthquake killed 25,000 people last
month, but an official said people had been warned and no casualties
were reported.
   Ruben Karagyosyan of the official earthquake relief commission
for Armenia said 10 aftershocks were recorded Monday night and
Tuesday morning, including one at 5:30 a.m. that registered 5.4 on
the Richter scale.
   The official news agency Tass said the epicenter was northwest of
Kirovakan, a city heavily damaged by the Dec. 7 quake.
   In a telephone interview from Yerevan, capital of Armenia,
Karagyosyan said: ``Our scientists had already warned the government
and the population over television and through the press that
aftershocks in the zone of the quake were predicted.''
   People had been told not to congregate in kindergartens, schools
and other buildings, he said, ``so there were no serious
consequences.''
   He said strong aftershocks also occurred Dec. 31 and Jan. 4.
