<FIRST>r w AM-FordFires     01-24 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford Fires,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petition Asks Broadening of Ford Pickup Fires Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The private Center for Auto Safety asked the
government Tuesday to order the recall of 1.9 million Ford Motor Co.
pickup trucks, alleging that the vehicles' fuel system tends to
catch fire.
   The petition, by an advocacy group often at odds with the
automakers and their regulators, asked the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration to broaden its probe of alleged fires in
Ford's F-series pickup trucks with dual gas tanks.
   The agency in December opened a low-level investigation of Ford
F-series pickups made from 1986 through 1988. The center asked that
the investigation include pickups made as far back as 1983 and be
raised to an engineering analysis, a higher level than the present
preliminary evaluation.
   ``Opening the lowest-level investigation is woefully
inadequate,'' the petition said.
   The center said it had received eight reports of fires involving
F-series pickups.
   A Ford spokeswoman, Joyce Stinson, said at the company's
Dearborn, Mich., headquarters that Ford was cooperating with the
investigation and if it were broadened, ``we would continue to do
so.''
   The government agency, as a matter of policy, refuses to comment
on investigations in progress. It responds to petitions within 120
days of their filing.
   The petition was the second filed by the center this week after
months of little public activity.
   The center's director, Clarence Ditlow, said the organization had
deliberately held off from filing petitions until the new Bush
administration took office.
   ``Our experience here in Washington is any time there is an
election, from just before the election to when the new
administration comes in, nothing gets done,'' Ditlow said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
