<HEAD>Mediator Recalled to Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal mediator in the 15-month dispute
between Eastern Airlines and its machinists union has been recalled
to Washington because talks last week failed to achieve a settlement
on major issues, the chairman of the National Mediation Board said
Tuesday.
   Chairman Walter C. Wallace said talks between Miami-based Eastern
and the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers union resulted in some progress on minor issues but no
agreements on major issues. Wallace, in a statement issued by his
Washington office, was not more specific.
   As a result, mediator Harry Bickford was recalled to Washington
and the talks recessed until the mediation board conducts a status
review, Wallace said.
   He said the board had requested that both the airline and the
union refrain from making public statements about the talks pending
further announcements from the board.
   Eastern, which estimates it is losing $1 million a day, is
seeking $150 million in wage concessions from the 8,500-member union.
