<FIRST>r w AM-Barry-Probe     01-24 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Probe,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barry Goes Before Grand Jury Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr. appeared Tuesday for the
second time before a federal grand jury investigating his ties to a
drug suspect, but his attorney stressed again that Barry isn't a
target of the probe.
   ``During the time that the mayor was at the grand jury, we were
completely unafraid of anything concerning the Ramada Inn
investigation or the Virgin Islands investigation,'' said R. Kenneth
Mundy, Barry's attorney.
   ``I'm stronger than ever before,'' Barry said after his
two-and-one-half hour appearance. When asked if he was a target of
the investigation, he responded, ``absolutely not.''
   Federal officials refused comment on Barry's appearances, but
have said before they are trying to determine if the mayor thwarted
a police drug probe in late December. The grand jury is also
examining the mayor's role in a joint personnel project involving
the city and Virgin Islands government.
   Police were called back from a Dec. 22 attempt to buy drugs from
the suspect, Charles Lewis, after Barry turned up in Lewis' room at
a dowtown Ramada Inn. Barry has since acknowledged making several
calls to police investigating the incident, but said he was only
trying to speed up their inquiry.
   Lewis also headed the $260,000 joint personnel project for the
Virgin Islands government, but was fired from his post last April
after Virgin Islands officials became concerned about cost overruns.
Barry and other top city aids ran up hotel bills in the Virgin
islands of more than $37,000 while working on the plan.
   Mundy said Barry is unlikely to be called before the panel again,
but the mayor was served with a subpoeana that requested all of his
telephone records, schedules, and daily diaries for December, which
covers the time period when Lewis was in the Washington area. The
grand jury is also seeking all phone messages dating back to Sept.
15.
   All the requested material will be turned over to the grand jury
as soon as possible, Mundy said.
</TEXT>
