<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru   01-24 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0704,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Proposal To Postpone Vote Is Rejected</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS final grafs 16-19, `A diplomat...Western Hemisphere' with
8 grafs to ADD background on proposal and quotes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president's party on Tuesday
rejected a new offer by leftist guerrillas to participate in
elections if voting is postponed for six months.
   Fidel Chavez Mena, the Christian Democratic presidential
candidate and a close adviser to President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
said ``great efforts must be made on behalf of peace'' but that
putting off elections beyond March 31 would be unconstitutional.
   The constitution says elections must be held at least two months
before a new government is due to take office. Duarte's term ends
June 1.
   Roberto Viera, minister of communications, said the government
will analyze the document point by point and present a detailed,
formal response.
   The Marxist-led guerrillas, in a document made public Tuesday,
said they would take part if a presidential vote scheduled for March
19 is postponed to Sept. 15. They set other conditions, including
confinement of the army to barracks on election day.
   ``Many have said that the only obstacle to peace in El Salvador
is that we demanded a share of power before elections,'' said
Salvador Samoyoa, a member of the political commission of the
Farabundo Marti Liberation Front guerrillas, known as FMLN.
   ``Now we have removed that obstacle,'' Samoyoa said Tuesday at a
Mexico City news conference. ``We have agreed to play the game on
their field.''
   The guerrillas presented the proposal as a test of the other
political parties' desire for peace and of President Bush's desire
for political solutions in Central America.
   Ana Guadalupe Martinez, a member of the guerrillas' general
command, said the proposal was made because of increasing violence
and deteriorating economic, social and political conditions.
   ``The nation is headed for a social explosion,'' she said. When
asked what the guerrilla reaction would be if the proposal failed,
Ms. Martinez said, ``The tendency towards violence is increasing,
and the FMLN is not on the margins of that reality.''
   The guerrillas said Tuesday they would throw their support behind
Guillermo Ungo, the candidate of the leftist Democratic Convergence
alliance, if te vote were switched to Sept. 15. ``We believe we can
win if a fair election is held,'' said Ms. Martinez.
   The group's 7,000 guerrillas have been fighting the U.S.-backed
government and its 56,000-strong army for nine years, but neither
side has been able to gain a decisive advantage.
   The right-wing Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, which
has been leading in polls for the presidential election, noted that
the guerrillas did not say they would stop fighting.
   ``We are willing to talk. What we cannot do is subordinate
ourselves to a group of terrorist delinquents,'' said Sigifredo
Ochoa, a top Arena leader in the National Assembly.
   The Christian Democrats control the executive branch, but Arena
trounced the centrist party in legislative and mayoral elections
last year.
   The Arena presidential candidate, Alfredo Cristiani, led Mena by
more than 10 percentage points in a December poll, with Ungo running
a distant third.
   A diplomat in close contact with the army high command said the
response from Defense Minister Gen. Eugenio Vides Casanova to the
guerrilla proposal was ``a flat-out `no.'''
   A Western diplomat the only way the armed forces could be
persuaded to accept the proposal would be through strong pressure
from the United States.
   ``This is a proposal for the U.S. Congress as much as it is for
the Salvadorans,'' the diplomat said on condition of anonymity.
   Washington has provided El Salvador more than $3 billion in aid
since 1980, more than it has given any other country in the Western
Hemisphere.
   Another diplomat said the insurgents might be counting on
rejection. They could then portray themselves as a party truly
interested in peace but obliged to continue fighting.
   Ruben Zamora, a leader of the Democratic Convergence, called the
proposal ``a test to see if Salvadoran politicians really want peace
or if they only want jobs on the public payroll.''
   The guerrilla's conditions include a halt to ``repression'' of
labor and peasant leaders, revising the electoral code, awarding a
seat on the Central Elections Council to the Democratic Convergence,
and non-interference by the United States.
   In return, the guerrillas said they would respect political
activity, halt assassinations of mayors, observe a five-day truce at
election time, and call for participation by their ``entire social
base.'' The guerrillas have boycotted previous elections as a
``farce.''
</TEXT>
