<DOCNO> AP890124-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Canada     01-24 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Canada,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Heading North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will travel to Ottawa Feb. 10 to
meet with Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, the White House
announced Tuesday.
   It will be Bush's first trip outside the United States as
president. The White House said that Bush will make a ``working
visit'' to Canada, meaning that he and Mulroney will discuss
relations between the two countries.
   ``The prime minister and the president will discuss bilateral and
international issues of common concern during this agenda-setting
meeting,'' the press office said in a statement. ``It is expected
the two leaders will pursue their discussions at further meetings
during the year,'' it said.
   The one-day Bush trip will come the day after the president
delivers an address to the Congress laying out his basic themes and
discussing the federal budget deficit.
</TEXT>
