<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Over Much Of West, On Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and snow fell over much of the West on Tuesday, with locally
heavy snow in the mountains, and snow was scattered onto the
northern Plains.
   Rain along the northern Pacific Coast changed to snow at higher
elevations of Washington at noon, and snow extended across the Idaho
Panhandle, Montana, Wyoming, Colorado, northern Arizona, northern
New Mexico, Utah and eastern Nevada.
   A heavy snow warning was posted over the mountains of
southwestern Colorado.
   Snow spread into North Dakota, western South Dakota and
north-central Nebraska, and freezing rain was scattered over much of
central Nebraska.
   From Monday afternoon into Tuesday afternoon, 9 inches of snow
fell at Bowman, N.D., and 7 inches fell Lemmon, S.D., and Hettinger,
N.D.
   Snowfall over Arizona ranged from about 2 inches at the south rim
of the Grand Canyon to 4 inches at the Sunrise Ski Area. Utah
snowfall ranged from 5 inches in the mountains around Monticello and
Richfield to about an inch at Richfield.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 1 degree
below zero at Burns, Ore., to 78 at Fort Lauderdale, Fla. Tuesday
morning's low was 21 below zero at Butte, Mont.
   For Wednesday, rain and thundershowers were forecast over
Arkansas and Oklahoma, with showers extending across northern Texas,
the Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles, Kansas, Missouri, Illinois,
southern Indiana, western Kentucky and western Tennessee. Rain and
freezing rain were forecast over southern Iowa and eastern Nebraska,
changing to snow from western Minnesota across the eastern Dakotas,
the remainder of Iowa and Nebraska, eastern Colorado, northern New
Mexico and northern Arizona.
   Highs in the teens and 20s were predicted from northern and
central New England across northeastern New York state, Upper
Michigan, northern Wisconsin, the upper Mississippi Valley, the
northern half of the Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies
and the eastern half of the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah;
in the 30s and 40s from southern New England across the Virginias,
the remainder of the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley, the central
Mississippi Valley, Kansas, Oklahoma, and the northern half of the
Pacific Coast; near 70 and in the 70s from South Carolina and
Florida across the central Gulf of Mexico coast and the Texas Gulf
Coast; and generally in the 50s and 60s over the remainder of the
nation.
</TEXT>
