<HEAD>Former Veep Breaks Hip in Tumble from Bike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last graf to CORRECT that Agnew was not only vice president
to resign; John C. Calhoun resigned in 1832.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Spiro T. Agnew
tumbled off a bicycle and broke a hip during the weekend, but was
reported recovering in good condition.
   Agnew, 70, who lives near Eisenhower Medical Center, was taken
there Sunday afternoon by ambulance and admitted, hospital spokesman
Mike McFadden said Monday. He was in good condition, McFadden said.
   Agnew resigned the vice presidency in 1973 just before pleading
no contest to federal charges of tax evasion on $29,500 he received
in 1967 while governor of Maryland. Agnew, who was vice president
for nearly five years under Richard Nixon, had been elected governor
in 1966.
