<FIRST>r a AM-SerialKillers     01-24 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Serial Killers,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bundy on Notorious List</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bundy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   One of America's most notorious multiple murderers, Ted Bundy,
was executed Tuesday in Florida. Here is a brief look at other
recent serial killers, their crimes and punishment:
   
   JOHN WAYNE GACY, on death row in Illinois since 1980, was
convicted in 1979 of the murders of 33 young men and boys from 1972
to 1978. Authorities discovered 27 bodies buried in shallow graves
in the crawl space underneath Gacy's suburban Chicago home. Two more
bodies were found on his property and four were recovered from
nearby rivers.
   PATRICK WAYNE KEARNEY confessed in 1977 to killing 32 men along
southern California highways. He was convicted of 21 of the ``Trash
Bag'' murders _ so-called because many of the dismembered remains of
victims were dumped in trash bags _ and sentenced to life in prison.
   GERALD STANO, who claims to have killed 41 women in three states,
is on death row in Florida appealing his 1983 death sentence for the
murders of two Florida women. Although Stano has been sentenced on
only 10 murders, receiving seven life sentences and three death
penalties, investigators say they have documented 25 of the murders
claimed by Stano in Florida. Less is known about murders Stano
admitted to in the New Jersey-Pennsylvania area.
   DONALD HARVEY, a former Ohio nurse's aide known as the ``Angel of
Death,'' confessed to murdering 58 people over a 17-year period.
Many of Harvey's victims were suffocated. He claimed most were
killed out of mercy, but some in malice. Harvey was caught after a
medical examiner smelled cyanide while performing an autopsy on a
victim. Harvey is serving several life sentences in Ohio.
   WILLIAM BONIN, an unemployed truck driver, became known as
California's ``Freeway Killer.'' He was convicted of murdering 10
boys and young men and abandoning their bodies near freeways in 1979
and 1980.
   HENRY LEE LUCAS, a one-eyed drifter, has been convicted in 13
murders in the West and Southwest. He once claimed involvement in
more than 360 murders nationwide, but later repudiated his
confession.
   ALBERT DeSALVO, ``The Boston Strangler,'' killed 13 women in the
Boston area from 1962 to 1964. Confessed to being the strangler, but
police lacked the evidence to bring him to trial for the killings.
Instead, he was tried on a series of unrelated assaults, convicted
and sentenced to life imprisonment. He was stabbed to death in his
cell in 1973.
   JUAN CORONA was found guilty of the slayings of 25 farm workers
whose bodies were found in Yuba City, Calif. in 1971, and is serving
a life sentence.
   ``THE NIGHT STALKER,'' a random killer who struck in a
seven-month rampage during 1984-85 that panicked Californians. He
typically entered homes through unlocked doors and windows, raped
women, killed both men and women, and stole jewelry and other
valuables. Richard Ramirez, a drifter whom authorities have tied to
the killings, is standing trial for 14 murders and 31 other felony
counts.
   ``THE GREEN RIVER KILLER,'' officially blamed for the deaths of
as many as 48 young women in Washington state and Oregon in 1982-84.
Many victims were prostitutes and were known to frequent the Sea-Tac
Strip, near the Seattle-Tacoma airport. Some investigators in the
San Diego area believe the killings there of about 40 women since
1985, many of them connected with drugs and prostitution, may be the
work of Seattle's murderer.
   ``THE SOUTHSIDE SLAYER,'' believed responsible for 17 murders in
south-central Los Angeles and nearby suburbs. All the victims are
women, all but three were black, and most were prostitutes. The
slayings date back to September 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890124-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HahnMinister     01-24 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hahn Minister,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hahn Calls Long Island Minister `A Wimp' After He Pleads Guilty Before
Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY46</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister facing damaging testimony from
Jessica Hahn, the woman who brought down PTL evangelist Jim Bakker,
pleaded guilty Tuesday to reduced charges before the start of his
tax evasion trial.
   The surprise decision by Eugene Profeta to plead guilty to two of
18 state charges against him came just before Hahn, his former
secretary, was to testify during an evidence suppression hearing.
   Profeta, of Long Island, admitted in court that he tried to get
Hahn to lie to grand jurors investigating his financial dealings and
to filing a false 1986 income tax return.
   He declined comment after he and his wife, Glenda, left the
courtroom. State prosecutors agreed to drop charges against Profeta
that he skimmed funds from his Massapequa church for personal use
and to drop income tax evasion charges against his wife.
   ``He's a wimp,'' Hahn said of Profeta at a news conference
outside the courtroom. ``He couldn't say that `I made a mistake' and
because of that I lost my family. You know, I've paid a price. And
by the grace of God I've been able to turn it around.''
   The former church secretary, whose 1980 sexual encounter with
Bakker led to the downfall of his PTL ministry, became a celebrity
and posed nude for Playboy magazine in the wake of revelations about
their liaison.
   Hahn, who worked as a secretary for Profeta both before and after
the encounter with Bakker, also said she had an affair with the Long
Island minister. She had earlier said she turned to him for solace
after the Bakker incident.
   At the evidence suppression hearing Monday, a New York state
investigator testified that Hahn told him she received $12,000 from
PTL in what ``sounded like extortion'' and that she spent $7,000 on
cocaine.
   A tearful Hahn admitted to reporters Tuesday that she
``experimented with cocaine'' and tried to hurt Bakker by taking
$12,000 from the PTL ministry in exchange for a promise not to talk
about their sexual encounter.
   She said she tried to give the money back, but that PTL officials
refused to relinquish a signed document saying she wouldn't talk
about the sexual encounter.
   Hahn refused to say how much money she spent on cocaine.
   ``It was a hard time in my life,'' said Hahn, now seeking
employment as a disc jockey. `` ... I'm not using anything now. This
was just a three-month period in my life.''
   Under the plea bargain agreement, Profeta is to be sentenced to
six months in jail and five months' probation, pay a $5,000 fine and
$13,000 in back taxes. He also was ordered by state Supreme Court
Justice Joseph Harris to stay away from Hahn.
   Hahn testified before a grand jury investigating Profeta and
taped telephone coversations with him in exchange for the state's
agreement not to prosecute her.
   New York Attorney General Robert Abrams called Profeta's plea
bargain agreement appropriate.
</TEXT>
