<DOCNO> AP890124-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Budget     01-24 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Budget,0784</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Budget Makes Japan World Leader In Foreign Aid ^By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet adopted a budget Tuesday that makes
Japan the top provider of foreign aid, increases its defense
spending and boosts its share of the cost of keeping U.S. troops in
Japan.
   The total budget raises government spending by 6.6 percent _ the
largest increase in eight years _ to $471.95 billion. The government
budget for fiscal 1988, which ends on March 31, was $441 billion.
   In negotiations after the Finance Ministry's budget proposal was
presented last week, the Foreign Ministry and the Defense Agency won
increases in Japan's foreign aid and defense spending.
   A Foreign Ministry official said economic assistance to
developing countries is likely to exceed $11 billion in fiscal 1989,
up from an estimated $10 billion in fiscal 1988. That would put
Japan ahead of the United States as the world's largest donor of
foreign aid based on estimates by the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development.
   Due to differing fiscal years and accounting techniques, it is
difficult to draw direct comparisons between foreign aid budgets.
The $14.5 billion U.S. foreign aid proposal for the fiscal year
starting Oct. 1 includes military aid. Japan's aid budget includes
no military expenditures.
   Measured against the size of its economy, Japan's aid is not
outstandingly generous. This year it will be about 0.3 percent of
the gross national product, higher than the U.S. rate of 0.23
percent but below the average of 0.36 percent among major Western
donor nations.
   Japan's Defense Agency, limited by law to defensive capabilities,
will have a budget of $30.6 billion in fiscal 1989, up 5.9 percent
from this year's $28.78 billion, said Toshinori Shigeie, director of
the Foreign Ministry's national security affairs division.
   The increase will enable Japan to meet fourth-year plans in a
five-year program to beef up Japan's defense capabilities,
particularly its ability to defend its sea lanes, Shigeie said.
   Washington has urged Tokyo to do more for its own defense, but
military spending is controversial in Japan. Its constitution
renounces war and the use of force to settle international disputes.
   Japan has agreed to shoulder a larger share of the costs of
maintaining 64,000 U.S. troops here. In fiscal 1989, it will spend
$1.11 billion, or about 75 percent of the total cost, moving closer
to its goal of 100 percent.
   Of that amount, $695.3 million will be used to improve U.S.
military facilities in Japan, up 12.5 percent from this fiscal year,
and $415.6 million will go to support the 20,000 Japanese employees
of U.S. bases.
   Until fiscal 1987, Japan limited defense spending to 1 percent of
its gross national product _ the total value of its goods and
services. In fiscal 1987, defense spending amounted to 1.013 percent
of GNP, and in fiscal 1988 and 1989 the military budget will be just
above 1 percent of GNP, based on Finance Ministry estimates.
   Japan's GNP is forecast to reach $3.04 trillion in fiscal 1989,
up 4 percent from $2.89 trillion in fiscal 1988.
   Measured against the size of its economy, Japan's aid is not
outstandingly generous. This year it will be about 0.3 percent of
the gross national product, higher than the U.S. rate of 0.23
percent but below the average of 0.36 percent among major Western
donor nations.
   The government has announced it will double its official
development assistance to more than $50 billion for the five-year
period ending in calendar 1992 in a bid to promote Japan's
international contribution as a major economic power.
   In fiscal 1989, Japan's foreign aid allocations will include $228
million for measures equivalent to cancellation of the debts of some
least developed nations, said Shigeo Iwatani, senior assistant for
economic cooperation.
   They also will include, for the first time, $1.56 million for
small non-governmental organizations that provide emergency relief
and long-term grassroots assistance in developing nations.
   Iwatani said the ratio of outright grants to loans in Japan was
not available, but said the proportion of grants would be higher
than the 47.3 percent recorded in calendar 1987.
   He said Japan is adding personnel and strengthening research and
evaluation of aid projects in response to criticism that the
projects are poorly supervised and that loans usually provide
contracts for Japanese companies.
   ``We are trying to improve the quality of Japan's aid,'' Iwatani
said. ``Development assistance is a new field for Japan.''
   The government's budget proposal, which followed five days of
negotiations between the Finance Ministry and other government
bodies, is expected to go to Parliament for approval on Jan. 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
