<FIRST>u a AM-BundyInterview     01-24 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy Interview,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bundy: `I Deserve Punishment'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bundy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Condemned killer Ted Bundy told an
interviewer on the eve of his execution that ``I deserve the most
extreme punishment society has.'' But he said he didn't want to die.
   Bundy, the 42-year-old confessed killer of more than 20 young
women in four states, was executed in Florida's electric chair early
Tuesday for the kidnap, rape and murder of 12-year-old Kimberly
Leach of Lake City.
   Although he said he felt remorse for all of his sex-related
murders, Bundy said, ``There is no way in the world that killing me
is going to restore those beautiful children to their parents.''
   Toward the beginning of a videotaped interview with California
psychologist James Dobson at Florida State Prison, Bundy said he
took full responsibility ``for all the things I've done.''
   But he said they were te result of ``a fantasy life fueled by
hard-core pornography'' and alcohol.
   He said he had essentially a normal upbringing in a Christian
family, and ``I am essentially a normal person. ... except for this
destructive segment.''
   Bundy, handcuffed and sitting at a table across from Dobson,
alternately sobbed and smiled during the 29-minute interview. He was
dressed in the peach-colored, short-sleeved shirt worn by Death Row
inmates. And he seemed to ponder each question and answer carefully,
sometimes pausing at length before answering.
   Dobson, who has a daily radio program heard in 35 countries over
1,200 radio stations, inquired about the killer's youngest victim,
Kimberly Leach. ``What did you feel after that?'' he asked Bundy.
   Bundy held his hands to his face, closed his eyes and thought for
a long time before responding: ``I can't talk about that right now
... It's too painful. I can't do it ... I can't begin to understand
... the pain of these parents.''
   At one point, he told his interviewer that he ``felt the full
range of guilt and remorse'' but that he had it
``compartmentalized'' in his brain.
   He said it was ``important to me that I'm not blaming
pornography. . . I take full responsibility.'' But he said hard-core
pornography ``guided and shaped'' what he did.
   After he committed his first murder, ``What were the emotional
effects on you? What happened in the days after that?'' Dobson asked.
   ``It was like coming out of some horrible trance. ... It was like
being possessed by something so awful, so alien.
   ``I was absolutely horrified that I was capable of doing
something like that.''
</TEXT>
