<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Libya     01-24 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Employee Says Company Helped Build Chemical Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany-History, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A draftsman for a chemical company told
investigators his firm shipped chemicals to Libya and that employees
helped build a chemical weapons plant, West German television
reported Tuesday night.
   Also Tuesday, the newsmagazine Stern reported that a West German
government-owned company knew blueprints that were supposed to be
shipped to Hong Kong to build a pharmaceuticals plant had ended up
in Libya.
   The ARD television network said in an evening news broadcast that
Klaus Hess, a technical draftsman with Imhausen-Chemie, told West
German investigators the company had a key role in the Libyan
complex in Rabta, 60 miles south of Tripoli.
   It was the first report of an employee of Imhausen-Chemie
confirming allegations the company was involved in building the
plant.
   The U.S. government says the plant can make poison gas, an
allegation Bonn officials now support. Libya says the plant will
manufacture medicine.
   ``Klaus Hess is said to have given evidence that Imhausen shipped
parts and chemicals to Libya, and further that Imhausen employees
helped build the facility in Rabta,'' ARD reported.
   Imhausen-Chemie has denied accusations, first raised by U.S.
officials, that it was involved in the Rabta plant.
   ARD did not disclose where it initially got its information but
said it was confirmed by the Federal Prosecutor's Office in
Karlsruhe. The television also did not say if the employees traveled
to Libya to work on the plant.
   Earlier Tuesday, Stern magazine said an official at
Imhausen-Chemie told investigators that officials at Imhausen and
the government-owned Salzgitter Industriebau GmbH knew that
shipments of Salzgitter blueprints ended up in Libya instead of Hong
Kong.
   The Hamburg-based weekly did not name the official and it was not
known whether it was the same person identified in the ARD report.
   Salzgitter officials acknowledged last week that it had done
business with Imhausen-Chemie but said that was for construction of
a pharmaceuticals plant in Hong Kong. Salzgitter officials late
Tuesday denied any involvement in the project in Libya.
   Stern said ``it was also clear to experts'' with Salzgitter that
the Libyan plant was not designed as a ``small factory for
pharmaceuticals,'' but a ``large chemical plant for the production
of highly poisonous substances.''
   Stern reported last week that Salzgitter, which manufactures
steel products and industrial equipment, delivered blueprints for
the Libyan plant.
   Salzgitter Industriebau GmbH is a subsidiary of Salzgitter AG,
and both are wholly owned by the West German federal government.
   Karlheinz von den Driesch, spokesman for the Finance Ministry,
said he could not comment on the Stern report. But he also told
reporters the allegations will be investigated.
   A spokesman for the prosecutor's office in Offenburg confirmed
that an Imhausen-Chemie employee was questioned, but he declined to
reveal what that person told investigators. The spokesman, Hubertus
Voegele, spoke in an interview with Sueddeutscher Runkfunk radio.
   Prosecutors are investigating Imhausen-Chemie, based in the Black
Forest town of Lahr, and other West German companies for their
alleged roles in the Libyan complex.
   Last week, Stern said that the Hong Kong project, called ``Pharma
150,'' was devised to disguise involvement by Imhausen-Chemie in
helping build the plant in Libya, which has the same name.
   The magazine on Tuesday said the giant West German electrical
firm Siemens sold switching and measuring equipment for ``Pharma
150.''
   Siemens spokesman Horst Siebert said the company had delivered
equipment to Hong Kong but denied it had done anything wrong.
   Stern telexed its report Tuesday to other news organizations in
advance of Thursday's publication.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater denied on
Tuesday that President Bush apologized to Chancellor Helmut Kohl
about news stories alleging West German involvement in the Libyan
plant.
   Friedhelm Ost, Kohl's chief spokesman, said in Bonn on Monday
that Bush ``regretted'' commentaries in American newspapers that
harshly criticized West Germany over the Libyan scandal because they
failed to ``take into account'' the West German government's efforts
to prevent the production of chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
