<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1922EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Election     01-24 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Election,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editor Nominated For New Parliament in Stormy Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In more than four hours of passionate debate
Tuesday, nearly 1,200 Muscovites nominated the editor of a
freewheeling weekly magazine for a new national legislature charged
with carrying out reforms.
   Vitaly Korotich of Ogonyok magazine, criticized in press and
hounded by Russian nationalists, lost two previous tries for
nomination. Backers at the Dzerzhinsky district meeting, however,
overwhelmingly moved him to the next stage of the complex process
leading to elections March 26.
   While supporters and opponents debated his reformist philosophy,
the editor was in the United States on one of several recent trips
abroad.
   Vladimir Tsvetov, a television reporter who spoke for the
candidacy, said Korotich and others like him make President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's reform effort credible to foreigners.
   ``We are on the edge,'' and the Soviet Union can become a
``great, free socialist country'' or bog down in bureaucracy again,
Tsvetov said.
   A small middle-aged woman wearing glasses and a gray sweater
grabbed a microphone, but when the crowd heard the words
``Korotich'' and ``slander'' a chant of ``Down with Pamyat!''
drowned her out.
   Several young members of Pamyat, a Russian nationalist group
accused of anti-Semitism, raised banners in the back of the hall
criticizing Korotich. There was a crush of people straining to see,
then a roar of disapproval.
   Ogonyok reported earlier this month that Pamyat members broke up
an electoral meeting called to nominate Korotich for the
2,250-member Congress of People's Deputies.
   On Jan. 18, the government newspaper Izvestia implied Korotich
supporters also were involved in the disorder. The Communist Party
paper Pravda printed a letter denouncing his magazine as ``scum''
that defames the Soviet Union.
   When the 995 green cards that counted as ballots Tuesday were
collected and counted, Korotich had 787. Yuri Skokov, an electronics
institute director who stressed economic reform, got 145.
   Pyotr Makarin, a city official running the meeting, spent the
evening trying to shout over people who used any pause to comment or
ask questions from the floor.
   He stopped the meeting at one point and called out: ``We will sit
and wait until we restore elementary order!'' The crowd gradually
quieted.
   After the earlier meeting was broken up, Korotich also lost in a
try at the writers' union slate. Such other backers of reform as
Andrei D. Sakharov, the Nobel Peace Prize winner, have been passed
over by their professional groups and had to seek endorsement
elsewhere.
   Sakharov said last week the system for choosing candidates, which
became law in December, should be more democratic.
   Under Korotich's leadership, Ogonyok has printed many sensational
stories about social problems and corruption of former leaders.
Recent issues revealed long-hidden statistics on the number of
suicides in the Soviet Union and carried stories about the
son-in-law of the late President Leonid I. Brezhnev, who was
convicted of corruption in late December.
   Such articles have created ardent supporters and passionate
critics.
   Nearly an hour before Tuesday's meeting, scores of people jammed
near the entrance of trade union hall in cold, clear weather.
   They broke a pane of glass next to the entrance and shouted:
``The door! The door!'' at officials who had locked the entrance
because a quorum of 500 people had been assured and there was no
more room.
   A man at the edge of the crowd muttered: ``They don't need
Korotich; they need a Stalinist camp,'' referring to the vast labor
colonies set up during Josef Stalin's purges.
   Officials finally relented and let in the crowd, which jammed the
aisles throughout the meeting.
   One third of the legislature's members will come from
geographical districts like Dzerzhinsky and another third from
districts representing ethnic groups. The rest are being chosen by
the Communist Party and its affiliates, trade unions and
professional and social organizations.
   Korotich's nomination now goes to a district electoral commission
that will decide which candidates are put on the ballot.
</TEXT>
