<FIRST>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     01-24 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Endorses Sawyer's Primary Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer picked up the endorsement of
Jesse Jackson on Tuesday in his bid to solidify black support and
block Richard M. Daley from attaining the mayoral post long held by
his late father.
   Jackson appeared with Sawyer, 54, on a packed stage at a South
Side community center to formally endorse the mayor in the city's
Feb. 28 Democratic mayoral primary. Sawyer, who is black, is being
challenged by Daley, 44, who is white and considered the
front-runner.
   Jackson called Sawyer ``a healer'' who has continued city
programs started by the late Mayor Harold Washington, the city's
first black mayor.
   Sawyer, who was elected mayor by the City Council a week after
Washington's death, said Jackson's endorsement would energize his
campaign.
   Jackson said he waited until just five weeks before the primary
to announce his endorsement because of deep divisions in the largely
black coalition that boosted Washington into the mayor's office in
1983.
   His endorsement came a day after Sawyer's leading black
challenger, Alderman Timothy Evans, filed for election in a
third-party bid designed to avoid a split in the black primary vote
that would give an edge to Daley.
   Many Washington backers have called Evans, 45, the heir-apparent
to Washington, who died of a heart attack in November 1987.
   Jackson, who has been considered an Evans ally, said his
endorsement of Sawyer applied only to the primary _ not the April 4
general mayoral election in which Evans would run.
   Jackson charged that Daley, the Cook County state's attorney and
son of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, had sent ``a signal'' by
singling out three blacks _ Health Commissioner Dr. Lonnie Edwards,
Chicago schools Superintendent Manford Byrd, and Police Chief Leroy
Martin _ as people he would replace.
   Avis LaVelle, Daley's press secretary, said Jackson was wrong in
his assertions. She said Daley has suggested that Edwards resign,
that Byrd be given a six-month contract extension, and has said
nothing definite about Martin.
   Evans is seeking to bypass the primary and run under the Harold
Washington party banner in the April special election to fill the
remaining two years of Washington's term.
   Other Democratic primary contenders are Alderman Lawrence Bloom,
a white Washington ally; James Taylor, a former state legislator,
and Sheila Jones, a Lyndon LaRouche backer. Four others are seeking
the Republican nomination.
</TEXT>
