<FIRST>r a AM-NoahRobinson     01-24 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noah Robinson,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests Case in Murder Trial of Jesse Jackson Half-Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution rested its case Tuesday
against Noah Robinson after more than four days of testimony in
which Chicago gang members said the Chicago millionaire hired them
to kill a childhood friend.
   Robinson, half-brother of the Rev. Jesse Jackson and a Greenville
native, is charged with murder and conspiracy in the death of Leroy
``Hambone'' Barber. He also is charged with conspiring to kill
Janice Denise Rosemond, who witnessed Barber's 1986 murder.
   Before the government wrapped up its case, Judge James E. Moore
granted a motion by defense lawyers to supress evidence seized
during a June 4 search of Robinson's Chicago home.
   Sgt. Dan Brannigan, an expert in gang-related acts for the
Chicago Police Department, testified that during the search officers
broke down a locked door to Robinson's bedroom and found a money
order receipt from a Robinson associate to Edward Cooksey, one of
four El Rukn gang members charged with murder in the Barber slaying.
   Officers also noticed phone numbers of gang members taped to a
mirror, he said.
   Robinson's lawyer, Robert Simone, argued that the officers'
actions were an unreasonable search and seizure, and Moore agreed.
   Earlier Tuesday, Simone questioned the credibility of Jackie
Clay, a former bodyguard for Robinson and a former El Rukn gang
member, who said Robinson paid him $500 to participate in the
alleged contract killing. Clay is also charged with murder in
Barber's slaying.
   Clay, who said Tuesday that he had left El Rukn in 1986,
testified a day earlier that the defendant hired El Rukn members to
come to Greenville to kill Barber, a former employee and childhood
friend of Robinson's.
   Previous trial testimony showed that Barber and Robinson had
quarreled in Greenville before Barber's death, and that Robinson
believed Barber was responsible for break-ins of buildings he owned
in Chicago.
   Robinson, a businessman, owned properties in both Chicago and
Greenville as well as a fast food franchise and a dairy company.
   Clay testified that he became a fugitive when Greenville police
issued a warrant for his arrest in the Barber murder and that
Robinson sent him money and promised legal assistance. He turned
himself in to police just before Christmas.
   During cross-examination, Simone tried to portray Clay as a
hardened criminal who made a deal with the prosecution in exchange
for testifying.
   On Monday, Clay testified that an El Rukn member told him the
gang was preparing to ``take care of Hambone for Local.'' Local was
a code name the gang used for Robinson.
   He then described how he and three other gang members traveled to
Greenville, but then quarreled over how to kill Barber. That mission
failed, but a second trip several days later ended in the fatal
shooting of Barber in front of a building owned by Robinson.
   The trial began Jan. 16.
</TEXT>
