<FIRST>r a AM-Bundy-Plea     01-24 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy-Plea,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manipulative Killer Once Rejected Plea Bargain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theodore Bundy, who was executed Tuesday for
the murder of a 12-year-old schoolgirl, once rejected a plea bargain
that would have imprisoned him for life.
   State Attorney Jerry Blair said at the time that Bundy ruined any
chance of avoiding the electric chair by trying to outwit the
prosecution.
   In May 1979, Bundy decided to admit his guilt in three Florida
killings on the condition that the prosecution would not recommend
the death penalty.
   Blair projected the guilty pleas would have produced a life
sentence with no chance of parole for at least 75 years.
   But plea bargaining broke down when Bundy tried unsuccessfully to
remove public defender Michael Minerva from the case, claiming he
was trying to coerce Bundy into admitting guilt, Blair said.
   He believed Bundy's bid to drop Minerva was part of a scheme to
have his guilty plea reversed on appeal.
   On Tuesday, state officials were poised to fend off one other
legal ploy that might have postponed the 7:06 a.m. execution.
   Gov. Bob Martinez appointed three psychiatrists to be at the
prison prior to the execution in case Bundy's attorney raised the
claim that he was mentally incompetent to be executed.
   Defense psychiatrist Dorothy Lewis of Yale University examined
him and found him competent to be executed.
</TEXT>
