<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     01-24 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Three Israeli-Allied Lebanese Militiamen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Israeli-allied Lebanese militiamen
were killed Tuesday when a bomb went off under their vehicle as they
patrolled Israel's self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon,
police said.
   Four militiamen in the American-made armored personal carrier of
the South Lebanon Army were wounded in the midday attack near the
village of Kantara, 16 miles east of the southern port of Tyre.
   Police said the SLA retaliated by shelling nearby Kabrikha
village with mortars and artillery for two hours.
   The site is just north of the area of operations of the Irish
battalion of the U.N peacekeeping force in south Lebanon.
   ``Irish troops were seen evacuating nearly 50 pupils trapped in
the shelled village school,'' a police spokesman said on condition
of anonymity.
   U.N. spokesman Timur Goksel said an Irish private was wounded in
the left arm by shrapnel from an SLA mortar blast while in his
sandbagged position 17 miles east of Tyre. He was not identified.
   Israel created the security zone, a six-to-10 mile-wide buffer
strip along the border, when it withdrew most of its troops from
Lebanon in 1985, ending a three-year occupation.
   The strip, a target of frequent attacks by extremist Moslem and
leftist militiamen and Palestinian guerrillas, is patrolled by about
1,000 Israeli soldiers and more than 2,000 SLA militiamen, who are
trained and financed by Israel.
