<FIRST>r a AM-Rough-SexDefense     01-24 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rough-Sex Defense,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wrestler Who Used Rough Sex as Defense Pleads Guilty to Reduced Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 375-pound former professional wrestler
who said he strangled a 105-pound woman after she savagely bit him
during rough sex pleaded guilty to a reduced charge of manslaughter
Tuesday.
   Larry Finnegan Jr., 28, of Greenwich, whose ring name was
``Crusher,'' was originally charged with murder in the death last
June of Hazel Koppel, 20, a homeless woman whom Finnegan said he
paid to have sex with him.
   Under the plea agreement, Finnegan will be sentenced to 18 years
in prison, to be suspended after he serves 12. He is scheduled to be
sentenced March 15.
   The prosecution conceded in Superior Court that Finnegan's
version of how Koppel died was plausible, given the substantial bite
wound he suffered.
   ``We had the visible effects of a bite mark on his left breast
that was placed there by the victim for whatever reason,'' Assistant
State's Attorney Bruce Hudock said.
   ``We have to give some credibility to the story given by the
defendant that he was just enraged that she would not let go of his
chest area,'' Hudock said. ``I concluded the jury would most likely
find him guilty of manslaughter.''
   Finnegan, who was working as a truck driver for a moving company,
picked up Koppel in Stamford early June 6, 1988, and was having sex
with her in the cab of his truck when he killed her, according to
his attorney, Michael Sherman of Stamford.
   He walked into Stamford police headquarters that morning and told
authorities that her body could be found in his parked truck.
</TEXT>
