<FIRST>r a AM-OfficerKilled     01-24 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Officer Killed,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted In Death of Police Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EASTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury on Tuesday ordered the death penalty
for a man convicted of kidnapping an off-duty police officer from
his apartment and shooting him to death.
   The jury deliberated two hours before delivering the sentence
against Samuel Lee Green, who was convicted late Monday of
first-degree murder, kidnapping and conspiracy.
   The prosecution contended that Green kidnapped and killed Richard
Bowser after the off-duty Harrisburg police officer awoke during a
burglary at his home on Oct. 22, 1987.
   Green and Bonnie Sue Pflugler, who will be tried in February,
were arrested in Florida a week after the murder while sleeping in
the back of a van stolen in North Carolina.
   First Assistant District Attorney Mark Refowich, who argued for
the death penalty, said he was pleased.
   ``It was a statement by the jurors ... that they are sick and
tired of this kind of senseless killing,'' he said.
   Green, 33, of Harrisburg, did not testify during the trial and
would not allow his two lawyers to argue on his behalf during the
sentencing phase, said his attorney, Ronold Karasek.
   Karasek said Green was probably upset and frustrated with the
first-degree verdict. Green will appeal the case, he said.
