<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Chess     01-24 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Chess,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Defeats Canadian In Third Game of Candidates Quarterfinal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Grandmaster Artur Yusupov defeated
Kevin Spraggett of Canada in the third game of their World Chess
Championship Candidates quarterfinal Tuesday to tie the score at 1.5
points each.
   In a endgame characterized by subtle maneuvering, Yusupov,
playing white, boxed in the Canadian player's King.
   Faced with a checkmate, Spraggett resigned while pondering his
42nd move.
   Spraggett seized the lead with a brilliant victory in the second
game on Sunday, fueling Canadian hopes that the 34-year-old from
Montreal, who ranked 35th in the world, might become the first North
American since Bobby Fischer to reach the semifinal stage of the
competition.
   While Yusupov, 28, regained a psychological edge, most experts
say the outcome of the contest is difficult to predict.
   ``In such a short match with only three games left, just about
anything can happen,'' said Leontxo Garcia, a Spanish chess
commentator.
   The winner of the six-game duel will receive five-eighths of the
$32,500 prize fund. The winner of the Candidates series will
challenge Garri Kasparov of the Soviet Union for his world
championship crown in a 1990 title bout.
   The fourth game is scheduled for Wednesday with Spraggett playing
with the advantage of the white pieces. Of the three remaining
games, Spraggett has two games with white, Yusupov only one.
   If the contest ends tied at 3-3, two more games will be played,
followed by sudden-death tiebreakers at increasingly high speeds.
   A win scores one point and a draw a half.
   British Grandmaster Jonathan Speelman, who won quarterfinals in
August, is the only player so far who has made it to the semifinals.
   The third quarterfinal, between former world champion Anatoly
Karpov and Johann Hjartarson of Iceland, begins Saturday in Seattle.
   The fourth quarterfnal, between Dutch Grandmaster Jan Timman and
Lajos Portisch of Hungary, begins Jan. 31 in Antwerp, Belgium.
</TEXT>
