<DOCNO> AP890124-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EmergencyLanding     01-24 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landing,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tapes Show Pilot Didn't Know Engine Had Fallen From Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airline pilot misunderstood an air traffic
controller who told him ``you've lost the engine,'' not realizing it
had actually fallen off the plane until he landed safely, cockpit
conversations revealed Tuesday.
   The pilot of Piedmont Airlines Flight 1480 apparently believed
his engine had only shut down, even after he successfully returned
the plane with 27 passengers aboard to O'Hare International Airport,
just two minutes after takeoff last Friday.
   ``I understand the right engine is shut down,'' the pilot said,
sounding slightly dazed and out of breath shortly after landing,
according to the transcript released by the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   A few minutes later, the pilot told the tower: ``Hey ground
tower, whoever I'm talking to, this is Piedmont out here on the
runway. We've lost the engine. I don't know whatever happened to
it.''
   The control tower responded: ``It fell off the aircraft about a
half-mile past the end of the runway.''
   No one was injured in the incident. The passengers on the Boeing
737-200 were put on other flights to Charlotte N.C., their initial
destination.
   ``The pilot was calm,'' said FAA spokesman Mort Edelstein. ``I
wonder how he would have felt if he'd known. I thought he did a
magnificent job.''
   The control tower knew less than a minute after the plane
departed that it had lost its right engine, according to the
transcript of the conversation with the pilot:
   Tower: ``Piedmont 1480, it looks like you've lost the engine. Can
you make a right turn back for 32 right'' _ a designation for a
runway.
   Pilot: ``We've got to come back to a runway.''
   Tower: ``A left turn. A left turn. You lost the engine. You lost
the engine.
   ``1480 _ any runway, any runway. There is no traffic. (You're)
cleared to land any runway.''
   After it landed, the plane was losing fuel as it sat on the
runway. Fire trucks were called and passengers were taken from the
plane in a bus, Edelstein said.
   ``I need the fire department to come out here to take a look at
this thing. I understand there's some fuel coming out,'' the pilot
said.
   Piedmont spokesman David Shipley said the names of pilot and
co-pilot will not be released.
   The engine, which fell into a field at O'Hare, is being examined
at the airport and some parts have been sent to Washington, the
National Transportation Safety Board has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890124-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EmergencyLanding-Transcript     01-24 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landing-Transcript,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is an edited transcript of the conversation
between the control tower at O'Hare International Airport and the
pilot of Piedmont Airlines Flight 1480, which lost an engine shortly
after takeoff but landed safely Friday. The transcript was provided
by the Federal Aviation Administration.
   `C' stands for control tower and `P' for the Piedmont pilot. The
FAA deleted conversation from other pilots who saw the jet lose its
engine.
   The transcript begins with the tower telling the Piedmont flight
to get ready for takeoff on runway 27L while another jet lands on
runway 32L. After the plane has taken off, the conversation
continues:
   C: Piedmont 1480 it looks like you've lost the engine. Can you
make a right turn back for 32R?
   P: We've got to come back to a runway.
   C: A left turn, a left turn. You lost the engine. You lost the
engine.
   C: 1480 any runway, any runway. The wind is 350 at 20. You're on
a good left base.
   P: A good left base we got it.
   C: You can go 4R if you want; that's a left 90 degree turn.
   P: Roger.
   C: 1480 wind is 350 at 20; there is no traffic for you. Cleared
to land any runway.
   P: Roger, we got you.
   The control tower then asks whether the pilot plans to evacuate
the aircraft.
   P: We're going to park it right here. I need somebody to tow,
we've lost the A pump, too.
   The tower asks again if the pilot plans to evacuate.
   P: Ahh, let's see. I don't need to do that right now. I need the
fire department to come out here to take a look at this thing. I
understand there's some fuel coming out. I've lost the A pump and I
lost the ... There's fuel coming. ... I understand the right engine
is shut down. The right engine is shut down. Well, I tell you what,
how about having somebody come out here and tow us. We don't have
any steering. We can't taxi.
   C: I understand sir, the fire equipment is on the way. We will
have someone come out and tow you. I understand you will not egress
(evacuate) the aircraft. We'll pass that along to the fire
department and I'll keep you advised on this frequency.
   C: Piedmont 1480, some of the folks off the left side said you're
still dumping fuel all over the place down there.
   P: Yeah, I don't doubt it. I've got the fuel pumps off and
everything so the T-handle has been pulled and I don't know if
there's anything that can be done about it.
   P: Hey ground tower, whoever I'm talking to, this is Piedmont out
here on the runway. We've lost the engine. I don't know whatever
happened to it.
   C: It fell off the aircraft about a half a mile past the end of
the runway.
   The control tower then gives the pilot another radio frequency.
   C: ... The city has requested that you egress the aircraft to the
left side of the aircraft because of the fuel. That is the city
request.
   P: Yea, that's what we're going to do. I just wanted to get some
stairs out here. Yea everything's shut down. There should be no fire
danger.
</TEXT>
