<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Opposition     01-24 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Opposition,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Premier Plans To Challenge Iran Hierarchy In Political Comeback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Iranian Prime Minister Mehdi
Bazargan says he plans to build his tiny opposition party into a
national movement to challenge Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
hierarchy, Iran's official news agency reported Tuesday.
   In his first interview in seven years, Bazargan told the Tehran
Times newspaper that his Freedom Movement will field a candidate in
August's presidential election ``if political conditions ... are
favorable,'' the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   Giving a public platform to Bazargan, the first prime minister of
the Islamic republic after the 1979 revolution, underlined moves by
Iranian leaders to ease political restrictions after the August
cease-fire in the eight-year war with Iraq.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said in a separate report that
Khomeini's designated successor, Ayatollah Hussein-Ali Montazeri,
told Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi Tuesday there must be
``no delays'' in implementing a new law permitting opposition
parties.
   ``With ... the new law, the people will really feel that they
have a bigger role in the decision-making process and will see
themselves in the center of the revolution and partners in it,''
Montazeri said.
   IRNA quoted Bazargan as telling the English-language newspaper:
``We will organize the party at all levels throughout the country so
that we can present our plans to the people ... who will give their
verdict.
   ``If that verdict is in our favor, we will naturally have the
right to form a government,'' the 81-year-old political veteran,
said in the interview, which was also reprinted by Farsi-language
dailies.
   His moderate Freedom Movement, which frequently demanded that
Khomeini end the war, is one of 28 groups that have applied to
register as political parties.
   The government announced Dec. 31 it will allow political
organizations provided they do not conspire against the state.
   Since Khomeini abolished the ruling Islamic Republic Party two
years ago as unnecessary, the Freedom Movement has been the only
recognized opposition faction in Iran. The rest were systematically
eliminated in bloody purges in 1981.
   There are no official parties within the hierarchy, but factions
that revolve around leading figures operate like parties.
   Khomeini's regime apparently hopes that giving moderate opponents
a voice will isolate more extremist factions. But the new political
framework will be tightly controlled, and many Iranians are
skeptical about how effective it will be.
   There are indications that any new parties may be approved in
time to take part in planned summer elections for rural, city and
provincial legislative councils totaling 300,000 seats.
   Khomeini named Bazargan, a French-educated engineer who was
jailed by Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, prime minister Feb.23, 1979, a
few days after the revolutionaries took power.
   But Bazargan's moderate policies, seeking gradual social and
economic reforms rather than the radical extremes of the
revolutionaries, ran foul of the fundamentalists.
   Accused by his opponents of being pro-American, he resigned two
days after militants stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran on Nov. 4,
1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
