<DOCNO> AP890124-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ThinBlueLine     01-24 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adams Wins Expedited Parole Review</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state board Tuesday granted an expedited
parole review to the man whose conviction in the 1976 fatal shooting
of a Dallas policeman was questioned in the film ``The Thin Blue
Line.''
   Randall Dale Adams, 40, who is serving a life sentence, has been
denied parole eight times, most recently on Jan. 10, according to
state records.
   His next parole review was scheduled for December, but under
Tuesday's action, the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles will
consider Adams' appeal for parole soon, said Glenn T. Heckmann, the
board's executive director.
   ``I would speculate it would be within the next 30 days. Normally
decisions (about whether to grant parole) are made shortly after
review,'' he said.
   The board expedited Adams' parole request based on information
provided by State District Judge Larry Baraka, said Karen Armstrong,
an information officer with the board.
   In a hearing last month, Baraka ruled Adams did not receive a
fair trial in 1977 and recommended he be granted a new one or set
free.
   During the December hearing, the key witness against Adams
changed his story and testified that Adams didn't commit the murder
and wasn't even in the car police officer Robert Wood stopped just
before he was gunned down. But David Ray Harris, now on Death Row
for another killing, stopped short of saying he pulled the trigger
himself in Wood's slaying.
   Adams has maintained his innocence and contends prosecutors
wanted to convict him rather than Harris, who was only 16 at the
time, because, if convicted as a juvenile, Harris would have been
released at age 18.
   The case was the subject of Errol Morris' documentary movie ``The
Thin Blue Line,'' which questioned Adams' guilt.
   Adams has served more than 12 years in state prison. In 1980, his
death sentence was commuted to life.
   Baraka's recommendation that Adams be given a new trial or set
free is before the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, which could take
as long as two years to act on it, attorneys say.
   Earlier, Baraka had said he would write to the six-member board
asking that Adams be granted parole.
   ``Listening to the evidence, there's reasonable evidence to
believe the man's not guilty or didn't get a fair trial,'' Baraka
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
