<DOCNO> AP890124-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina 4thLd-Writethru a0781 01-24 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0781,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Secure Base; Attackers Reported Killed or Captured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE wounded, Alfonsin quotes, leftist
documents seized at camp. Pickup 7th pvs, `Troopers on...' Edits thereafter
to trim.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed civilians surrendered to the
army Tuesday after a one-day assault on an infantry base in which at
least 36 people were killed and scores wounded, the government said.
   ``Anyone there participated in a shocking spectacle,'' President
Raul Alfonsin said after visiting the camp. ``It was a nightmare.
Death. Once again, death. Brutality. Barbarism.''
   Alfonsin said the commandos were ``ultra-leftists,'' citing
documents seized by soldiers after the camp was recaptured. He said
fighting political subversion is ``the last test of my government.''
   ``This is my fight and I'll fight it to the finish so society is
free of this aggression,'' a somber Alfonsin said at Government
House in a 12-minute address to the Cabinet, military chiefs and a
nationwide broadcast audience.
   ``Society won't tolerate more violence, from whatever side,'' he
said.
   Alfonsin, who also has had to cope with three insurrections by
rightist army officers in the past 21 months, said he would form a
National Security Council to advise him on anti-subversion strategy.
He did not elaborate.
   Alfonsin said 28 commandos were killed and 14 captured alive as
government forces recaptured the 3rd Infantry Regiment base in La
Tablada on the outskirts of Buenos Aires, which the commandos
attacked Monday morning.
   Seven soldiers and one policeman were killed, and 67 soldiers and
policemen were wounded. Four civilians were wounded.
   Troopers on Tuesday tracked down snipers and searched bunkers at
the camp. Captured weapons included sophisticated machine guns from
the Soviet Union and China, military officials said.
   Alfonsin toured the base in the afternoon, looking closely at the
charred bodies and buildings blasted by tanks and mortars. Soldiers
were still exchanging gunfire with snipers in mopping-up operations,
but no fire was aimed at Alfonsin or his helicopter.
   As dusk approached, small fires still smoldered in gutted brick
buildings. Half a dozen buildings were in ruins, their windows blown
out and tile roofs collapsed or burned away.
   Helicopter gunships clattered over the base and a seedy sprawl of
project houses across the highway.
   Military and government officials said the attackers apparently
intended to steal weapons from the camp armory.
   Reporters counted 15 bodies, five blackened or mutilated by
explosions or fire. At least one was a soldier and two were women.
   The identities and motive of the attackers were not known. Army
officers said some were foreigners, the government news agency Telam
reported without elaboration.
   ``Surely, the objective was to take weapons and flee, but the
rapid action of the ... police and the armed forces ... made flight
something they could not achieve,'' said Antonio Berhongaray,
chairman of the Senate Defense Committee and member of Alfonsin's
Radical Civic Union party.
   Cesar Jaroslavsky, Radical Civic Union leader in the House of
Deputies, said at least some in the raiders belonged to the People's
Revolutionary Army, a leftist guerrilla group active in the 1970s.
   Confiscated pamphlets indicated the attackers called themselves
the ``Popular Resistance Front,'' said Jose Ignacio Lopez,
presidential press secretary. He said other pamphlets indicated the
group felt a military coup was imminent and wanted to prevent it.
   Gen. Walter Jurado, the Buenos Aires police chief, said the
captured attackers are believed linked to the leftist People's
Revolutionary Army.
   The assault began about 6:30 a.m. Monday. Shooting continued more
than 27 hours later, when 13 men and a woman with their arms raised
in surrender emerged from the shell of a building that had been
blasted by tanks the day before.
   All reports indicated four of the 14 were soldiers who had been
held captive.
   Graciela Marino, a resident of the working-class neighborhood
around the base, said ``bombs and shooting'' awakened the
neighborhood Monday morning and had continued since.
   The suddenness and ferocity of the attack caught the government
and armed forces off guard, which could cause problems for
Alfonsin's party in elections scheduled for May 14.
   ``This isn't the best moment to start attributing blame, but it
surprises us that an operation of this size was not detected by the
intelligence services, even though we're dealing with commando
groups that are very well organized,'' said Sen. Eduardo Menem of
the opposition Peronist Party.
   Alfonsin's elected civilian government took office in 1983 after
nearly eight years of military rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
