<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpottedOwl     01-24 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists' Lawsuit Reinstated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental groups can sue the government
to try to stop logging of old-growth fir near spotted owl nests in
western Oregon, a federal appeals court ruled Tuesday.
   The environmentalists' lawsuit had been dismissed by a federal
judge in Portland. But the 3-0 ruling on Tuesday by the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals also lifted an appeals court's ban on new
sales of old-growth timber near spotted owl sites.
   Both sides claimed victory.
   ``We feel that that was a significant victory for the timber
associations,'' said industry lawyer Mark Rutzick. He said the most
important part of Tuesday's ruling was ``the decision to lift the
injunction and let the Bureau of Land Management resume full timber
sales, pending some future decision by the District Court in
Portland.''
   But attorney Victor Sher of the Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund
said the court's action does not give the industry what it wanted,
authority ``to allow sales to go forward unchallenged.''
   ``What they (the court) said is, we are entitled to challenge
those sales on a case-by-case basis as they arise now, and that the
District Court in Oregon has to hear our case,'' Sher said. ``We
certainly intend to proceed to protect these critical areas.''
   The environmentalists' suit had been dismissed by a federal judge
in Portland.
   While removing the ban it imposed last June on new sales of
old-growth fir within 2.1 miles of a spotted owl site, the court
said environmental groups could ask U.S. District Judge Helen Frye
in Portland to forbid specific sales as they were proposed. The
groups would have to show a likelihood of proving that a threat to
the owl habitat violated federal law, the court said.
   The timber industry blamed the court's previous order for
shutdowns of five lumber and plywood mills and reductions by nine
others since Sept. 1, leading to the loss of 1,000 jobs.
   Sher said those claims were based on ``false and irresponsible''
statements. He said many of the mills were not authorized to buy
timber from BLM lands, or had not bought any in 10 years.
   The spotted owl, which lives in northern California, Oregon and
Washington, is not listed as an endangered species under federal
law, although Sher said a federal judge has ordered the Fish and
Wildlife Service to reassess the bird's status by May 1.
   Environmental groups regard the spotted owl as an ``indicator''
species, whose reduction foreshadows a threat to other forms of
life. There are 289 spotted owl sites within the timber sale area on
the western slope of the Cascades, Sher said. The suit contends
logging of old-growth timber would kill the birds by destroying
their habitat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
