<DOCNO> AP890124-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1647EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:FanClub Adv29   01-24 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Fan Club, Adv 29,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 29, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Music Died</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holly Fan Club Bigger Than Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first and only time Bill Griggs saw
Buddy Holly perform, he didn't know the bespectacled youth with a
Texas twang was the lead singer for his favorite band, the Crickets
because Holly released songs under his own name as well.
   ``I hate to admit that now,'' said Griggs, who has devoted his
life since that 1958 show to keeping alive the legend of Holly and
other innovators of rock 'n' roll.
   As the president and founder of the Buddy Holly Memorial Society,
he is one of the leading experts on Holly's life and music and owns
an extensive collection of Holly memorabilia. He started a fan club
14 years ago so that the memory of his idol would not fade away.
   ``I was no longer seeing Buddy Holly in the media, no longer
hearing his music on the radio,'' he said. ``I just thought he had
been forgotten after 1959.''
   The organization had more than 400 members after its first year
and now has almost 5,400 members from 31 countries who gather yearly
to share memories and swap memorabilia.
   ``It's not so much a fan club as a research organization,''
Griggs said. ``We're trying to find out as much as we can about the
man and his music. I've interviewed just about everybody that I know
of that knew him or worked with him.''
   The results of Griggs' research efforts almost fill two rooms of
his home. Records, posters, photos and sheet music from Holly and
other 1950s rockers are stacked on tables and pinned to walls.
   A glass case is reserved for Griggs' most cherished memorabilia:
a pair of Holly's famous horn-rimmed glasses; a suit jacket; a pair
of his black oxfords; a broken guitar string and even a guitar pick
used by actor Gary Busey in ``The Buddy Holly Story.''
   One of Griggs' most recent acquisitions is Holly's toilet kit,
carried with him on the night 30 years ago when the plane carrying
Holly, J.P. ``The Big Bopper'' Richardson and Ritchie Valens crashed
near Clear Lake, Iowa.
   Inside the brown leather bag is toothpaste, a comb and brush,
suntan lotion, hair gel and other personal items, covered with the
dust and grime of 1959.
   ``This is very personal,'' he said with awe. ``It's the last
thing he had in his hands.'' Griggs declined to say how he obtained
it.
   ``The reverence with which Griggs handles Holly's belongings was
strong enough to draw him and his family to Lubbock from his home in
Wethersfield, Conn., in 1980 after having visited here for several
years.
   ``It was Buddy Holly that brought us here in the first place and
why we decided to move,'' said Griggs, adding that he since has
grown close to Holly's remaining relatives. The singer's mother, two
brothers and a sister still live here.
   ``I'm like family to them now and that's a very good feeling.''
   So strong is Griggs' attachment to the rock 'n' roll era that the
former K mart manager now makes a living running a mail-order '50s
memorabilia business.
   ``Nostalgia's become big,'' he said. ``People that lived through
the era want to remember it. Those that didn't feel cheated, and
they want to know why their parents are so high on the '50s and why
they're hearing all these '50s songs on TV and radio commercials.''
   Griggs, 47, whose slicked back hair is reminiscent of the era he
loves, says the time between 1955 and the assassination of President
Kennedy in 1963 was a simpler, more wholesome time.
   ``We weren't at war, the kids didn't have a drug problem, we
weren't burning draft cards. We went to college to learn, not to
protest,'' he said. ``A few guys had greased hair and leather
jackets and that's about as bad as it got.''
   Today's world isn't so nice, he says, and contemporary music is
just one symptom of what ails the '80s. ``I'm really down on today's
music; it all sounds the same.''
   Now Buddy Holly _ that was rock 'n' roll.
   ``Buddy never copied himself,'' Griggs said. ``He was never
afraid to experiment, and this is a 22-year-old kid we're talking
about. Buddy was the first white rock 'n' roll performer to use a
full orchestra and strings and was one of the first to overdub his
voice.''
   Appreciation for Holly's contribution to rock has steadily grown
since the release of the movie about his life in 1978 and several
recent biographies.
   As Holly's No. 1 fan, Griggs feels a sense of accomplishment.
   ``He won't be forgotten now,'' he said. ``I still think that what
he did in 18 months is amazing compared to what Elvis Presley did in
27 years and what the Beatles did in nine years.
   ``He left this 18-month legacy of great music that's as fresh
today as it was then.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Jan. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890124-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Holly'sDreams ADV29   01-24 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Holly's Dreams, ADV 29,0890</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Music Died</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holly's Widow Pursues Rocker's Dreams</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I have thought about making a career out of western music if I
am good enough but I will just have to wait to see how that turns
out.'' _ Buddy Holly, (high school autobiography).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>IRVING, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria Elena Holly spends much of her time
hunched over a paper-piled desk in her home, trying to make Buddy
Holly's dreams come true.
   The legendary singer, songwriter and musician, who with his own
blend of rock 'n' roll and country influenced the Beatles, the
Rolling Stones and many others, dreamed that he would inspire young
musicians and pave their way in the industry, his widow said.
   ``If Buddy were still alive, I think that he would be involved in
every facet of the music industry,'' she said.
   Although she has tried to realize that dream through a Buddy
Holly scholarship fund, preferably at Texas Tech University in
Holly's hometown of Lubbock, or through a festival there, each
attempt has failed.
   Three decades after Holly was killed in a plane crash, his widow
pursues his dreams by answering letters from fans who say they will
always remember, and from opportunists who say there is money to be
made making sure the public doesn't forget.
   Maria Elena Holly receives letters from three to 10 people each
day.
   ``Buddy wrote and wanted his music to be received in a positive
way and for people to enjoy it and for people to be inspired by his
music and his determination to make it out there,'' she said.
   ``And that's where I come in with the youngsters. I feel that
through the letters, it has done that. Anything that is a positive
thing received from Buddy Holly's music, it makes me happy. It
pushes me out there to continue putting his name out there and keep
it there.''
   But she's not making Holly available to the public without some
personal benefit.
   In 1987, she successfully lobbied Texas lawmakers to approve
legislation giving her full rights to Holly's name, voice, likeness,
photographs and signature. Under the law, Holly's ``property''
cannot be used for commercial purposes without her approval.
   Bill Griggs, president and founder of the Buddy Holly Memorial
Society, says the law serves a good purpose.
   ``If you go to Memphis, Tenn., to Graceland, across the street is
souvenir store after souvenir store. You can buy Elvis Presley
toilet paper, which to me is the epitome of bad taste,'' he said.
``That's why Maria Elena is so tough. She wants to make sure
everything is done above board and in good taste.''
   Not only does the law keep Holly's name and face off beer cans,
as one entrepreneur proposed, but it also allows her to profit from
the Buddy Holly music boxes, posters and T-shirts that are sold.
   ``That was his legacy he left to us (his family) and the music
was his legacy he left to everybody,'' she said. ``I feel very
strongly that if someone is going to make money, I'm going to make
money and the Hollys are going to make money.''
   Maria Elena Santiago, a native of Puerto Rico, met Buddy Holly
while she was a receptionist at Peer-Southern Music Publishing Co.,
in New York. The morning after they met, Holly confronted Maria
Elena's aunt, who disliked musicians, and asked for permission to
marry her neice.
   They had been married just six months when the small plane
carrying Holly, Ritchie Valens and J.P. ``The Big Bopper''
Richardson crashed near Clear Lake, Iowa, on Feb. 3, 1959, killing
all three and their pilot.
   She was pregnant when Holly left on the tour and she suffered a
miscarriage after the crash. A year after Holly died, she remarried.
She and her second husband had three children before they divorced
three years ago.
   It was her dedication to Holly that helped end her second
marriage.
   ``People ask you, `How did you get over his death?' Well you
don't get over his death. You never do. You cope with it, but you
never get over it,'' she said, turning her head to hide tears.
``Sometimes I do get upset and then I pick myself up and I say this
is not going to bring him back, so why not keep him here.''
   Besides a few posthumously bestowed music awards and a few photos
of Holly, she keeps his Gibson J-200 acoustic guitar and his black,
plastic-frame glasses. The glasses were found long after the crash,
stored in an Iowa sheriff's files.
   Holly's Fender Stratocaster and other belongings are in Lubbock
with his family, who are involved in negotiations with his widow to
divide the items.
   Although she appreciates a statue erected by Holly's friends, she
would have preferred the money to have been spent on a music
scholarship.
   ``That's what Buddy wanted,'' she said of the scholarship.
``Buddy wanted to help young people get established in the music
industry, to be able to help them in whatever career they chose in
music.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Jan. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
