<DOCNO> AP890124-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:BuddyWho? Adv29   01-24 1038</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Buddy Who?, Adv 29,1065</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Music Died</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holly Recognized in Hometown? That'll Be the Day</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The music of the late '50s and early '60s when music was at
that root level, that for me is meaningful music. The singers and
musicians I grew up with transcend nostalgia _ Buddy Holly and
Johnny Ace are just as valid to me today as then.'' _ Bob Dylan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By WENDY E. LANE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buddy Holly influenced generations of
musicians. So does his hometown give him fitting recognition?
   That'll be the day, say fans and friends.
   They complain that 30 years after his death, this city takes
scant notice of its most famous native son.
   Holly was 22 when he died on Feb. 3, 1959, after the small plane
carrying him, Ritchie Valens and J.P. ``The Big Bopper'' Richardson
crashed near Clear Lake, Iowa.
   A life-size bronze statue stands in downtown Lubbock as a tribute
to the famous singer and musician who lived almost all his short
life in this windswept farming town. But it was erected by a few of
Holly's friends, not the city government.
   Lubbock's efforts to capitalize on Holly are pale compared to the
million-dollar industry Memphis built around the legacy of Elvis
Presley.
   ``This is the hometown of Buddy Holly and he should be remembered
here,'' said Bill Griggs, the president and founder of Buddy Holly
Memorial Society. ``I'm not saying every street should be named
after him and every radio station should be playing his music, but
there just isn't that much here for the fans.''
   Those fans have not forgotten the sound of the shy young Texan
with the toothy smile, big black spectacles and hiccup-laced vocal
style that influenced recording artists as diverse as the Rolling
Stones and Linda Ronstadt. Around the anniversaries of his birthday
and death, flowers cover Holly's simple, marble grave marker _
inscribed with a Fender Stratoscaster _ which lies in the city
cemetery.
   Born Charles Hardin Holley, the fourth child of Lawrence and Ella
Holley, the boy known as Buddy took an early interest in music and
was influenced by the country music he heard on the radio. The ``e''
in his family name was dropped on the singer's first recording
contract.
   From his first public exposure _ at age 17 on radio station
KDAV's ``Sunday Party'' show as a country duo with his friend Bob
Montgomery _ Holly's local stature was low-key.
   While most agree Holly deserves more hometown recognition,
there's contention over who is to blame for the lack of local homage.
   Some Holly devotees blame his widow, Maria Elena Holly, for
blocking those seeking permission to use her late husband's name for
memorial concerts.
   Civic Lubbock Inc., a city-appointed, non-profit organization,
sponsors an annual music festival at the time of Holly's birthday,
but the number of musical offerings, as well as attendance, have
declined steadily since the first festival in 1986.
   But the event no longer can use the singer's name since Mrs.
Holly successfully lobbied the 1987 Texas Legislature for a law
forbidding commercial use of Holly's likeness, voice or name without
her permission.
   On the other hand, she says city and festival officials aren't
interested in promoting Holly with a music festival.
   ``For almost 30 years now I have been talking to the officials
and trying to convince them that doing a Buddy Holly week would help
in every way,'' she said. ``But it's one thing or another, and
nothing ever gets done.''
   Jeff Klotzman, a Civic Lubbock board member, says the city hasn't
given up trying to promote Lubbock's famous citizen with a festival.
   ``The commitment is definitely there and the intent is to honor
Holly,'' he said. ``I don't think the city has turned its back on
Buddy Holly by any stretch of the imagination.''
   Mrs. Holly and others say no one in Lubbock cared much about
Holly even when he was alive.
   ``You'd mention Buddy Holly around here and people would say,
`Oh, you mean that kid who used to play down at the fruit and
vegetable?''' said Larry Corbin, former owner of a country radio
station where Holly held informal jam sessions.
   Griggs said the city's disorganized attempt to stage a music
festival was one reason the Buddy Holly Memorial Society moved its
10th annual convention away from Lubbock. For two years, the
gathering of hundreds of fans has been held in Clovis, N.M., where
the singer recorded most of his hits.
   ``I'm not trying to be derogatory, but the people in charge in
this town are from the big band era,'' said Griggs, who is bringing
the meeting back to Lubbock because of its accessibility and
proximity to Holly's grave. ``I think we made our point to the
city.''
   Prior to the 1978 release of the movie ``The Buddy Holly Story,''
there was nothing in Lubbock to commemorate the singer. City
officials rushed to put Holly's name on a park, built on the
outskirts of town over an old landfill. The park sign bearing
Holly's name has been defaced with spray-painted obscenities and a
swastika.
   In 1978, country superstar Waylon Jennings, Holly's bass player
on his final, ill-fated tour, and other Holly friends had the statue
built.
   ``Waylon just wanted to do something for Buddy in Lubbock, since
he gave him his start,'' said Corbin, who also put up money for the
project.
   But the bronze statue stood on a plot of city land for three
years without anything to say who it was. Finally, the statue was
rededicated, this time with a plaque.
   His grave, the park and the statue remain the only reminders of
Holly. The small, white frame house where he was born had been
slated for demolition, ironically on the 18th anniversary of his
death. It was saved after someone unaware of its historical
significance purchased and moved the structure to another location.
Now the lot stands vacant and weed-grown.
   And while the Iowa town where Holly died has a ``Buddy Holly
Place'' among its streets, no road or avenue in Lubbock bears the
singer's name.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Jan. 29</NOTE>
