<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:MusicDied Adv29 1stLd-Writethrub0719 01-24 1137</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Music Died, Adv 29, 1st Ld-Writethru b0719,1166</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Jan. 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to add dropped word, guns.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Musicians and Fans Remember ``The Day the Music Died''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``A long, long time ago I can still remember how that music used
to make me smile. And I knew if I had my chance that I could make
those people dance and maybe they'd be happy for awhile. But
February made me shiver with ev'ry paper I'd deliver. Bad news on
the doorstep. I couldn't take one more step. I can't remember if I
cried when I read about his widowed bride. Something touched me deep
inside the day the music died.'' _ Don McLean, ``American Pie.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By DAVID BAUDER</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   After three decades, the Crickets are looking to complete the
trip their leader Buddy Holly couldn't.
   On Feb. 3, 1989, the band is booked to perform in Fargo, N.D.,
the city Holly, Ritchie Valens and J.P. ``Big Bopper'' Richardson
were scheduled to play on that date 30 years ago. Instead, their
plane crashed in a snowstorm, killing all three musicians and their
pilot.
   Immortalized as ``the day the music died'' in Don McLean's 1972
epic pop song, ``American Pie,'' the plane crash was the first great
rock tragedy.
   ``It's going to feel a little strange, I'll have to admit,'' said
Jerry Allison, one of two original Crickets still playing with the
band, of the Fargo date. ``I still miss Buddy because he and I grew
up together.''
   In less innocent times, musicians would be struck down by drugs,
drink, cars, guns and suicide. Their deaths form a macabre rock 'n'
roll hall of fame. Among them: John Lennon, Marvin Gaye, Sam Cooke,
Andy Gibb, Phil Ochs, Jim Morrison, Janis Joplin, Peter Tosh, Paul
Butterfield, Elvis Presley, Jimi Hendrix, Brian Jones, Keith Moon.
   But when Holly's tour plane went down seven miles north of Clear
Lake, Iowa, kids wore black armbands to school to honor stars not
much older than themselves.
   Holly was only 22 when he died; Valens was 17. Both were at the
beginning of their careers, but left behind enough work to create a
sense of unfulfilled potential that nags today.
   Along with Chuck Berry, rock 'n' roll's first great poet, Holly
was one of the first musicians in the rock era to write much of his
own material. He was the first to experiment with now-common studio
techniques such as overdubbing, and his ``hiccupping'' vocal style
influenced such followers as Paul McCartney, who now owns the rights
to Holly's songs.
   ``Books have been written about the way he structured his
songs,'' Scott Isler, senior editor of Musician magazine, said of
the spare rock that propelled Holly through such hits as ``Peggy
Sue,'' ``Rave On,'' ``Not Fade Away'' and ``It's So Easy.''
   His music lives today on compact disks, a laser-driven technology
of which Holly probably would not have dreamed, and in automobile
commercials, a setting which may have made him cringe.
   Valens' legacy is more modest, although he was put back in the
public eye with the 1987 movie ``La Bamba.'' The band Los Lobos also
re-released Valens' song of the same name that year and made it a
hit. Valens other hits included ``Donna'' and ``Come on, Let's Go.''
The Big Bopper, a former disc jockey, was known for his song,
``Chantilly Lace.''
   Through movies of the lives of Holly and Valens (one hasn't been
made on Richardson), millions of people have learned how Holly
chartered a plane because he wanted to hurry to Fargo to get his
laundry done.
   The Crickets weren't with Holly on his final tour. They stayed
behind in Lubbock, Texas, when Holly left his hometown to get
married in New York City. Crickets guitarist Sonny Curtis shook
Allison awake the morning after with news of the crash.
   ``The whole thing was unbelievable,'' said Allison, who would
rather celebrate the anniversary of Holly's birth (Sept. 7, 1936)
than the day of his death. But the Crickets are a working country
band and they don't shy away from gigs or Holly's memory. Allison
co-wrote some of Holly's best-known songs, including ``That'll Be
the Day.''
   Clear Lake has remembered the three artists with an annual
anniversary concert held for the last 10 years at the Surf Ballroom,
where they gave their final performance. This year's event is
already sold out.
   ``They're proud of Buddy Holly and they like to flaunt the idea
this is where Buddy Holly gave his last concert,'' said disc jockey
Daryl Hensley, organizer of the event.
   This year's concert stars the Diamonds, Bobby Vee and Freddie
``Boom Boom'' Cannon, rock relics from the Holly era.
   Vee took over Holly's scheduled appearance the night after the
crash.
   Meanwhile, the historical society in Beaumont, Texas,
Richardson's hometown, plans to raise two statues on Feb. 3 _ one of
Buddy Holly, Richardson and Valens, and a second of the Big Bopper
alone.
   Musicians have long speculated where Holly's muse would have
taken him had he lived. He was recording with a full orchestra
shortly before he died and confided that he wanted to make gospel
music like Ray Charles, Allison said.
   ``Would he have turned into a supper club crooner or would he
have gone on to write some incredible stuff and break barriers
down?'' Isler said.
   Referring to the crash as ``the day the music died'' is a bit
hyperbolic, ``although it makes a great song lyric,'' Isler said.
   When ``American Pie'' came out, Allison went to a record store
and bought it, pleased that another musician thought so fondly of
Holly. He even backed McLean at a concert in Texas where the
singer-songwriter sang the eight-minute fable littered with obscure
musical metaphors.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Bye-bye, Miss American Pie
   ``Drove my Chevy to the levee but the levee was dry
   ``Them good ole boys were drinkin' whiskey and rye
   ``Singin' this'll be the day that I die.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   But he has one regret. ``I'd like to sit down with him sometime
and say, `what do you mean by all these different things?'''
   William Griggs remembers being rocked by the news of Holly's
death when he was taking a lunch break from school. Griggs,
president of the Buddy Holly Memorial Society, recently moved from
Connecticut to Lubbock. He said he visits Holly's mother every few
months to update her on fan club activities.
   Although devoting much of his life to Holly, Griggs tries not to
inflate the star's reputation, which often happens to artists who
die young.
   ``So many artists who live on to their 40s and 50s had some
failures in their lives,'' Griggs said. ``People like Buddy Holly,
James Dean and Eddie Cochran never had a chance to fail.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Jan. 29</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
