<FIRST>r f PM-FarmBanks Bjt   01-24 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Banks, Bjt,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Fed: Drought Impact On Farm Banks Not As Severe As Once Feared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite fears that drought would wilt
bank earnings in the summer of 1988, farm banks in the Midwest
improved their performance in the third quarter, even outperforming
non-agricultural counterparts, the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago
says.
   ``It appears that the drought's effects on bank performance in
the third quarter were not as severe as once forecasted,'' said the
January edition of the Chicago Fed's ``Banking Barometer.''
   ``Particularly during the real apex of the drought ... analysts
were saying it would be real bad news for farm banks in the third
quarter. We didn't see it,'' George Gregorash, banking analysis
officer for the Chicago Fed, said Monday.
   Not only did earnings rise at 1,747 Midwest farm banks, but the
report said the quality of the banks' credit and assets also
improved in the July-September period.
   The report also said that while earnings for the U.S. banking
industry improved for a third straight quarter, reaching a record
$5.94 billion, problem loans continued to plague banks in the
Southwest.
   Return on assets, a measure of bank earnings, was higher and rose
further at Midwest farm banks in the third quarter than at
non-agricultural banks, it said. Farm banks are lending institutions
with agricultural loans, other than real estate loans secured by
farmland, exceeding 30 percent of their total loans.
   Midwest farm banks had a return on assets of 1.02 percent in the
third quarter, or $1.02 for each $100 in assets. That was up 28
cents from a year earlier. Returns at non-agricultural banks in the
Midwest were 99 cents for each $100 in assets, a rise of 7 cents
from the third quarter of 1987, the report said.
   ``Certainly most analysts had forecast earnings under 1 percent''
of assets for farm banks when the drought first struck, Gregorash
said.
   The Chicago Fed attributed the improved earnings at Midwest farm
banks to a drop in problem loans. Provisions for loan losses fell 30
hundredths of a percentage point to 0.36 percent of assets at
Midwest farm banks, while at non-agricultural banks, provisions for
loan losses dipped 8 hundredths of a percentage point to 0.47
percent of assets, the report said.
   The percentage of nonperforming loans to total loans for Midwest
ag banks fell from 4.41 percent a year earlier and 3.02 percent in
the second quarter to 2.91 percent in third quarter of 1988. At
non-agricultural banks, the percentage of nonperforming loans dipped
just 0.41 point from a year earlier and 0.08 point from the second
quarter to reach 2.11 percent of total loans.
   The figures on Midwest farm banks covered districts supervised by
Federal Reserve Banks in Chicago, Minneapolis, St. Louis and Kansas
City, Mo.
   States either entirely or partially in those districts are
Arkansas, Colorado, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky,
Michigan, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, New
Mexico, North Dakota, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Tennessee, Wisconsin
and Wyoming.
   ``As the Midwest sustained its turnaround, the distress continued
in the Southwest, driven by extremely high provisions'' for bad
loans, the report said. ``As a result of poor credit quality, loan
loss provisions as a percent of average assets were 2.54 percent in
the third quarter (in the Southwest), up from 1.42 percent a year
ago and 2.36 percent in the second quarter of 1988.''
</TEXT>
