<FIRST>r f PM-Boeing Bjt   01-24 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing, Bjt,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Unions: Just Bad Luck For Planemaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at The Boeing Co.'s two major unions say
they haven't heard their members complain about quality slipping at
the planebuilder, and are hard-pressed to attribute a recent spate
of bad news to anything but bad luck.
   ``I don't understand how it could happen,'' said Dan Mahoney,
general counsel for the Seattle Professional Engineering Employees
Association, which represents about 26,000 Boeing engineers and
technical workers. ``Everybody realizes this company survives on
airplanes that stay in the air. There's no effort we're aware of to
skimp on testing and quality assurance.''
   Despite recent news accounts of some quality complaints by Boeing
workers, Mahoney and Jack Daniels, spokesman for International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers Local 751, said the
complaints hadn't reached them.
   ``I haven't heard of anything,'' Daniels said, adding if any of
the 40,000 Boeing production workers had a complaint, they could
report it through their union shop stewards or business
representives.
   ``All our members are concerned about quality,'' said Daniels.
``But we haven't seen any evidence that quality has slipped.''
   In 1988, Boeing smashed industry records for new commercial jets
ordered, 636 planes worth about $29.7 billion.
   It introduced the 737-400, a stretch twinjet, and the 747-400,
the world's largest commercial jetliner. It worked on a new, smaller
version of the 737, the model-500, due out this spring, and
announced it was increasing aircraft production across the board
during the next few years.
   But 1988 also was the year safety of older aircraft became a
worry, sparked by a terrifying accident in which an Aloha Airlines
737-200 lost part of its roof over Hawaii.
   Several airlines also criticized Boeing for poor workmanship.
Boeing executives said the work would be improved, and the four
carriers whose complaints were publicized later placed sizeable
orders for Boeing planes.
   In recent weeks, however, little news has been good for Boeing.
   _The disintegration of a Pan Am 747 over Scotland on Dec. 21,
killing 270, was ultimately blamed on a bomb, but not before
speculation that the 19-year-old plane might have failed.
   _On Dec. 26, an older Eastern 727 made an unscheduled landing
after it lost cabin pressure when a hole opened in the fuselage.
   _On Jan. 8, a 12-week-old British Midlands 737-400 crashed in
Great Britain after one engine failed and the other was shut off.
Cross-wiring in engine warnings systems was being investigated, but
no incidences of cross-wiring in 737s have been reported.
   _Cross-wiring was found in cargo-hold fire extinguishing systems
on seven Boeing 757s, after the Federal Aviation Administration
ordered a check. On Friday, the FAA also ordered the systems checked
on Boeing 767s because of the similarity of design.
   _In the past week, an engine fell off a Piedmont Boeing 737-200,
which still landed safely in Chicago, and a wing panel came off an
Eastern Boeing 757. Neither incident resulted in injuries.
   _Last Friday, Boeing announced it had completed a five-day
``readjustment'' of its 747-400 line to catch up work in some
places, and once again was reviewing its already-delayed schedule
for delivering the new planes. Initial customers Northwest and
Singapore airlines both said they were disappointed and need to get
the new planes as soon as possible.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes President Dean Thornton has
acknowledged rapid growth has meant too many inexperienced workers
and too much overtime. Boeing now employs more than 95,000 in
Washington, 55,000 in Commercial Airplanes alone.
   But Bill Whitlow Jr., analyst with Dain Bosworth Co. in Seattle,
said Boeing's woes are ``short-term blemishes on their reputation.''
   Boeing set a tight schedule for developing the 747-400, getting
it certified and getting production up to what analysts estimate
will be 55 to 60 planes in 1989, Whitlow said. ``They're just trying
to get too much done too quickly,'' he said.
   Some 60 percent of all commercial jets flying were built by
Boeing,said Phil Friedman, an analyst with Drexell Burnham Lambert
in New York.
   ``Boeing's market share is such that whenever a plane goes down,
the chances are good their name is going to be on it,'' he said.
   Friedman also said Boeing's problems are short-term. If not,
``Why did they have the blockbuster year that they did? Customers
putting up money is the best sign they're convinced that quality is
as good as it ever was.''
   ``It's sort of an unfortunate, random confluence of events,''
Mahoney said. ``When you think of how many airplanes there are
taking off and landing every minute of the day, it's one of those
things.''
</TEXT>
