<FIRST>r f PM-CigaretteSuit Bjt   01-24 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cigarette Suit, Bjt,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses Request By Tobacco Lawyers To Interview Landmark Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Lorrilard Inc., one of the
tobacco companies sued in the landmark Cipollone cigarette liability
trial, can't interview jurors from that case, the trial judge ruled.
   U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin rejected Lorillard's request
at a hearing Monday. Sarokin agreed with attorneys for Antonio
Cipollone, who said not enough reason existed to depart from federal
rules in New Jersey which only allow such interviews for ``good
cause.''
   Most of the exceptions involve cases in which there was evidence
of jury tampering or interference. Lorillard made no such
allegation, saying it only wanted to speak to the jurors ``to
discuss their impressions of the case'' for purposes of
``self-education,'' according to court papers.
   The company said it would make sure no juror would be harassed,
and that they would be told they could stop the interview at any
time. Lorillard noted that some jurors had spoken freely to
reporters, and included copies of news articles in their court
documents.
   ``Certainly in a case of this importance, the court can
understand the self-education motivation of counsel,'' Sarokin said,
adding that the reason was not enough to depart from the rules.
   In June, a six-member jury awarded Cipollone $400,000 in damages,
finding that Liggett Group Inc. violated advertising promises that
its products were safe. Liggett made the cigarettes smoked by
Cipollone's wife, Rose, before warning labels were put on packs in
1966.
   The Cipollone verdict was the first to award money damages,
though it awarded them to Cipollone only and not on behalf of his
wife. Liggett has appealed.
   Damages were assessed only against Liggett. Liggett, Philip
Morris Inc. and Lorillard were cleared of conspiring to misrepresent
the dangers of smoking and other claims.
   Mrs. Cipollone smoked for 40 years before dying in 1984 at age 58.
   The cigarette industry spends millions of dollars defending
itself against hundreds of smoker-liability cases and waged a
large-scale public relations campaign during the trial.
   ``Lorillard states categorically that no information it obtains
from the Cipollone trial jurors will be used in any way in
connection with the pending appeal of the Cipollone judgment,''
their court papers said.
   Lorillard also said no information from juror interviews ``will
be used for any sort of public relations campaign or purpose.''
   Three jurors told The Philadelphia Inquirer that they compromised
into agreeing to award the damages to Cipollone because two jurors
insisted on finding the tobacco companies at fault.
   ``As I look back on it today, I don't think I did the right
thing,'' said jury forewoman Marie Mickens in the newspaper's Sept.
4 edition. ``I hope they (Liggett) win on appeal.''
   Cipollone's attorney, Alan M. Darnell, argued that if wanting to
learn about how a jury worked was enough to allow juror interviews,
``then applications to interview jurors would be routinely granted,
because lawyers and parties are always curious about what `really'
happened in the jury room.''
</TEXT>
