<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     01-24 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading today and
foreign currency dealers said they expected it to trade within a
narrow range for the remainder of the session.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Traders said the dollar fell sharply overnight following another
round of central bank intervention Monday afternoon and a statement
by Bundesbank Director Leonhard Gleske that West Germany would
prefer to see the dollar below 1.80 marks.
   ``The market is trying to see whether the dollar has reached its
minimum levels for now or whether it should fall further to 1.80
marks,'' said one trader in Rome.
   ``People's confidence in the dollar has been shaken,'' said a
dealer at a major West German bank in Frankfurt. ``They're nervous
and uncertain.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.25 yen to a closing 126.95. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 126.55 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8234 West German marks, down from 1.8385; 1.5438
Swiss francs, down from 1.5577; 6.2050 French francs, down from
6.2545; 2.0571 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0780; 1,336.75 Italian
lire, down from 1,353.00; 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1888.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7813, more expensive for
buyers than $1.7733 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $407.30 a troy ounce,
down from $407.75 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $407.80.
   The bid price was also $407.80 an ounce in Zurich, up from
$407.40 bid late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 16 cents to close at a bid
$408.99.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.19 a troy ounce,
down marginally from Monday's $6.20.
</TEXT>
