<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     01-24 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Japanese Stocks Set New Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged from its recent relatively high
levels against the Japanese yen today, while the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's leading index climbed to another record.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 162.50-point gainer Monday,
rose another 224.80 points, or 0.72 percent, closing at 31,557.68, a
new high.
   Foreign exchange rate stability and a downtrend in oil prices and
short-term interest rates boosted Japanese investors' buying
interest, said an analyst with Nomura Securities, Japan's largest
brokerage.
   ``The yen's strength contributed most in the Nikkei's sharp rise
today,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In active trading, with first section volume estimated at 1.3
billion shares, steel, real estate and financial issues attracted
buyers.
   On the currency exchange market, the dollar finished at 126.95
yen, down 1.25 yen from Monday's 128.20 yen close. The currency
opened at 127.37 yen and ranged between 126.70 and 127.55 yen.
   The dollar had climbed to a closing of 129.20 yen last Thursday,
up more than six yen from its mid-December level.
   A Bank of Tokyo dealer said concerted dollar-selling intervention
by U.S. and European central banks for the last four days
effectively brought the dollar down. Dealers said its low opening in
Tokyo today followed a decline on overseas markets overnight.
   In quiet trading, Japanese market players made only some
technical adjustments after the dollar's rally last week, said a
dealer with Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo.
   ``Investors were intermittently selling and buying the currency
for speculative purposes as the dollar-yen rate moved,'' said the
dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
