<FIRST>u f PM-SuddenAcceleration Bjt   01-24 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudden Acceleration, Bjt,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sudden Acceleration Alleged in Cadillacs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group's allegation that 1.1 million
Cadillacs may be prone to sudden acceleration runs counter to the
findings of earlier government investigations, General Motors Corp.
says.
   The Center for Auto Safety, in a petition filed Monday with the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, asked the agency to
order the recall of Cadillacs with HT-4100 4.1-liter V8 engines and
made from 1982 through 1988.
   GM responded that a 1986 NHTSA investigation of GM vehicles,
including Cadillacs, failed to find ``a common design flaw or
manufacturing defect that could be a root cause for these unwanted
acceleration incidents.''
   ``If the center has any technical information that would shed
light on these incidents, we would certainly like to see it,'' said
Vince Muniga, a spokesman for GM's Cadillac Division in Detroit.
   The center based its petition on public complaints of 120
instances of unintended acceleration that allegedly resulted in 63
accidents, 70 injuries and five deaths.
   Two of the fatalities occurred in November when a 1985 Cadillac
Eldorado crashed through the front of a department store in
Belleville, N.J., killing two shoppers and injuring 13.
   ``Victims in many of these cases are pedestrians or bystanders
unable to dodge an out-of-control Cadillac,'' the center said in its
petition.
   NHTSA said it would respond to the center's request within 120
days and declined to comment further on the petition.
   GM said it would cooperate with any NHTSA investigation of the
allegations.
   NHTSA, in response to an earlier petition by the center, has been
investigating allegations of sudden acceleration in
front-wheel-drive Cadillac DeVilles and Fleetwoods made from 1985
through 1988.
   The models included in the center's latest petition are the
1982-1984 DeVilles and Fleetwoods; 1982-1987 Eldorados, Sevilles,
Broughams and Fleetwood Broughams; and 1987-1988 Allantes.
   Federal engineers in recent years have investigated allegations
of sudden acceleration in about 80 million vehicles produced by 10
manufacturers, according to figures compiled by the center.
   About 440,000 cars were recalled as a result of the
investigations, the center said.
</TEXT>
