<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Minorities     01-24 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Minorities,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Contractors Worry About Going Broke After Supreme Court Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civic leaders lamented a U.S. Supreme Court
decision to strike down Richmond's minority set-aside ordinance, and
at least one minority contractor said his business won't survive the
ruling.
   Merlin Hargrove said the city law, which required at least 30
percent of any city contract to be subcontracted to minority-owned
businesses, meant $400,000 in business over four years for his
United Unlimited Construction Co.
   He said Monday's ruling will mean the end of his company, which
employs nine people.
   ``I was expecting it to go the other way,'' he said of the
ruling. ``I guess the only thing you can do is pray.''
   Dwight Snead, another minority contractor, said his landscaping
and paving business will survive, but only because the ordinance got
it started. The law was enacted in 1983 and suspended in 1987
pending the outcome of the Supreme Court's ruling.
   Snead said he never got city work before the set-aside law was
enacted. Since then, he said, he's received several million dollars
in subcontracts on city projects and his company has grown from 10
employees to 60.
   The ordinance ``enabled us to become a general contractor,'' said
Snead.
   Many city leaders were critical of the court's ruling, which said
the ordinance amounted to ``reverse discrimination.''
   The decision marks ``a dark day for the city, a dark day for the
country and a dark day for human relations,'' Councilman Roy A. West
said.
   ``I'm keenly disappointed in the decision,'' Councilman Henry L.
Marsh III said. ``But I think we have to regroup in Richmond and
make an attempt to comply with the Supreme Court requirements.''
   One voice of praise for the court came from Councilwoman Carolyn
C. Wake, who voted against the ordinance in 1983.
   ``I feel that justice has prevailed,'' she said, ``because I
believe very much in the marketplace and the free enterprise
system.''
   Councilman Chuck Richardson called the court's decision ``weak,
superficial, superfluous and an excuse. ... For the court to hide
behind the feeble excuse that there was no evidence (of
discrimination) was almost unconscionable.''
   Richardson said blacks received less than 1 percent of all
contracts before the ordinance. Forty percent of all contracts went
to minority-owned companies during the life of the ordinance,
according to City Manager Robert Bobb.
   The ordinance was challenged in 1987 by J.A. Croson Co., an Ohio
company that was the only bidder on a city project but failed to get
the job because it lacked a minority subcontractor.
</TEXT>
