<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 0955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-TreasuryBills     01-24 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Fall on Short-Term Treasuries In Monday's Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in the government's latest auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 8.26 percent on Monday, down from 8.30
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 8.31 percent, down from 8.35 percent
last week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 8.24
percent on Jan. 3, and six-month bills averaged 8.29 percent on Dec.
19.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.55 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,791.20 and 8.79 percent for six-month bills selling for $9,579.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for 1-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for
making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, fell to 8.96
percent last week after averaging 9.11 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
