<FIRST>u f PM-TexacoBoard     01-24 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texaco Board,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Agrees to Accept Fund Nominee To Board Of Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. has bowed to the wishes of
some of its biggest institutional stockholders by agreeing to
appoint the president of New York University to its board of
directors.
   John Brademas, 61, who has been NYU's president since 1981, was
one of 14 people that a group of big pension funds had asked Texaco
to consider as a nominee to the board.
   Texaco on Monday announced the appointment of Brademas, who will
join the board later this month, and Charles H. Price, 58, who will
join in March after completing a 6-year tenure as ambassador to
Britain.
   Texaco's agreement to accept the funds' nominee was described as
a landmark in the struggle over who runs corporations.
   The selection of a fund-backed director ``is a watershed
development,'' W. Gordon Binns Jr., head of General Motors Corp.'s
pension fund, the nation's largest private fund, told the Wall
Street Journal.
   ``It means (some public) institutional investors ... want to go
beyond just voting proxies and take a direct hand in corporate
governance.''
   The appointments come during the final stages of a massive
restructuring since the oil giant emerged from bankruptcy protection
last year and during a battle with disgruntled shareholders led by
financier Carl C. Icahn.
   Price previously was ambassador to Belgium for two years, and
chairman of American Bancorp, president of American Bank and Trust
Co., and chairman of Price Candy Co., all of Kansas City, Mo.
   Before joining NYU, Brademas served 11 terms as an Indiana
congressman.
   The moves expand the board size to 15 from 14. Texaco said Lorene
L. Rogers, the retired president of the University of Texas at
Austin, was retiring from the board after 13 years.
   Texaco has made major changes over the last year, selling off
major assets, reorganizing internally and shifting its focus to
exploration and production from refining and marketing.
   But Texaco has been fored to fight Icahn, its largest
shareholder, who has been pushing Texaco to boost the value of the
company's stock by selling off assets.
   Icahn last week indicated he might try for a second time to wrest
control of Texaco's board from management at the May shareholders
meeting. Icahn also has indicated in the past he might mount a
buyout bid for the oil giant.
   Texaco is the nation's third-largest oil company behind Exxon
Corp. and Mobil Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
