<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EmployerBounty     01-24 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Employer Bounty,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ky. Bank Puts Up Bounty for New Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FALMOUTH, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Falmouth bank is offering a $5,000 reward
to anyone who can provide a tip that helps bring a factory with more
than 50 employees to job-starved Pendleton County in rural northern
Kentucky.
   The First National Bank is offering the bounty in hopes of luring
an employer to the county, where the annual unemployment rate was
9.6 percent in 1987, the latest year for which that figure is
available. The county is home to an estimated 11,300 people.
   Tracy Farmer, a former Kentucky Democratic Party chairman and
aide to former Kentucky Gov. John Y. Brown Jr., owns the bank and
initiated the reward.
   ``This is an ideal place for a factory. We have good labor, it's
a good area, improvements on U.S. 27 are beneficial and the
industrial foundation has been doing a good job,'' Farmer said. The
foundation is a group of the county's business leaders.
   Warren Shonert, the bank's vice president for public and
community relations, said the reward offer expires April 1.
   ``Mr. Farmer is always interested in economic development and
thought maybe this would help bring a new industry to Pendleton
County,'' Shonert said. ``He doesn't care where it locates, just so
it is in the county.''
   David Butcher, past president of the Pendleton County Chamber of
Commerce, said the county hopes to attract an employer that would
hire women. He said this could help increase the standard of living
for families, by providing jobs for wives.
   ``That would increase the family's standard of living
considerably,'' Butcher said.
   Pendleton County's per capita income for 1986, the latest
available, was $9,443, compared with the state per capita of
$11,268, said Ron Decker, economic development representative with
the Kentucky Cabinet for Economic Development.
   Pendleton County's largest manufacturer is the Fuller
Manufacturing and Supply Co. in Falmouth, which employs about 150
people.
</TEXT>
