<FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler-NAACP     01-24 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler-NAACP,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Joins NAACP in Minority Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said it has begun
talks with the NAACP to advance job opportunities for minorities.
   In a joint announcement with the civil rights group released
Monday, Chrysler said it would work toward a ``fair share''
agreement.
   ``We believe we have a good record with our minority programs,''
Chairman Lee Iacocca said in a written statement. ``But as the
saying goes, almost everything can stand improvement.''
   Benjamin Hooks, executive director of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People, said, ``We are pleased that
the Chrysler Corporation, as a good corporate citizen, has responded
positively to our request for discussion of a fair share agreement.''
   The Fair Share Program, in effect since 1982, is aimed at
expanding opportunities for minorities.
   General Motors Corp. earlier signed a fair share agreement with
the NAACP, and Ford Motor Co. signed a similar agreement in Chicago.
</TEXT>
