<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-24 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Futures Higher; Wheat Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of soybeans and corn were higher
while wheat futures were lower in early trading today on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Talk of Soviet purchases of U.S. soymeal and higher prices on the
European soymeal spot market drove soybean prices much higher, said
Steve Freed, grain analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Traders said corn futures followed the advance in soybeans, but
the rally was restrained by reports of a new Agriculture Department
catalog of corn next week that would provide an avenue for more spot
sales, Freed said.
   Wheat prices were depressed by a forecast for showers in growing
areas of the U.S. winter wheat crop, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2} cents to 3} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in Martch at $4.41 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 2\ cents higher with March at $2.72{ a bushel; oats were \ cent
lower to 3 cents higher with March at $2.39 a bushel; and soybeans
were 3 cents to 9{ cents higher with March at $7.65 a bushel.
   Futures prices for livestock and meat were mostly higher on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .05 cent lower to .28 cent
higher with the contract for delivery in February at 72.80 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .30 cent higher with
January at 83.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to .05
cent higher with February at 43.35 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .47 cent lower to .30 cent higher with February at
39.70 cents a pound.
   On Monday, livestock and meat prices traded mostly lower.
</TEXT>
