<FIRST>r f BC-EECStudy     01-24 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC Study,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Firm: 1992 Too Soon For Unified European Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading U.S. accounting firm said it
was doubtful the European Economic Community could achieve a single
capital market by 1992.
   Arthur Andersen &amp; Co. of Chicago said Tuesday that serious
problems in harmonizing regulations, taxes and technology among the
countries would prevent integration of the 12-nation trading bloc on
schedule.
   ``An integrated European capital market, with a common
infrastructure, will not be achieved by 1992,'' a report by the Big
Eight accounting firm said. ``A longer timetable is needed.''
   The EEC wants to create a single, European-wide market by the end
of 1992. To meet that goal, the Common Market nations are in the
process of dismantling barriers to the movement of capital, goods
and people among the member states.
   About 80 percent of the 1,000 experts from 13 countries who took
part in the study predicted that international equity trading will
remain concentrated in London, Tokyo and New York, but the European
exchange may lose some importance.
   ``London will play a significant role in the international
market, but even its ability to compete with Tokyo and New York is
far from certain,'' it said.
   The report predicted that assets managed by European
institutional investors would double in the next five years but said
savers would demand more sophisticated investment instruments.
   The study said European exchanges will have to cooperate rather
than compete in order to handle the increased and more demanding
business. It also predicted gaps among Common Market countries as
some remove regulations from their markets faster than others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
