<FIRST>u f PM-CommoditiesProbe 2ndLd-Writethru f0042 01-24 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0042,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Futures Exchange Urges Calm; Attorney Says FBI Bullied Traders</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new 3rd graf to UPDATE with attorney confirming grand
jury appearances; picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, The New ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid reports that a government investigation of
Chicago commodity markets was expanding, the head of the agency that
oversees the markets said the probe should not shake investor
confidence.
   ``I think this is a very good example of how we're doing in our
job,'' said Wendy Gramm, chairwoman of the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission.
   John Troelstrup, a Chicago attorney representing at least one of
the traders subpoenaed, told The Associated Press he understood the
grand jury would meet today and Wednesday.
   The New York Times reported today that at least a dozen more
subpoenas were delivered to Chicago traders Monday and some people
could appear today before a grand jury.
   The Chicago Sun-Times reported that unidentified sources said the
FBI has asked the Internal Revenue Service to conduct ``net worth''
investigations of some brokers and traders suspected of evading
large amounts of taxes.
   The Sun-Times also said the suspects are believed to be
frantically trying to shift assets to relatives and business
associates to hide unreported profits.
   U.S. law enforcement officials are investigating allegations that
as many as 100 brokers and traders systematically cheated customers
out of millions of dollars on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange and
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Since last week's revelations, FBI agents and U.S. prosecutors in
Chicago have said nothing for the record, but on Monday in
Washington, Ms. Gramm acknowledged her agency has been involved in
the investigation from the outset.
   Ms. Gramm declined to say whether the CFTC simply had been
informed of the probe or had assigned personnel to it from the
start. Nor would she say whether the agency knew that undercover FBI
agents were operating on the floors of the exchanges and whether
CFTC records have been subpoenaed.
   Asked if the revelations should shake investor confidence in the
futures markets, Ms. Gramm said: ``The fact that we bring cases ...
to root out fraud and abuse is an example of why people should be
confident in our ability to police the markets.''
   FBI agents posing as traders recorded conversations about the
alleged fraud at the exchanges, and the government has subpoenaed
traders and trading records dating back to Jan. 1, 1983.
   The investigation has raised jitters among many traders and
sparked a rash of seat sales on the major exchanges. Six more seats
were sold on both exchanges by the close of business Monday,
bringing to 32 the total number sold since the probe went public
Thursday.
   The Merc's board of governors issued a letter urging traders
``not to be driven to irrational or self-destructive behavior by the
adverse publicity.''
   ``Our own internal compliance department had already focused on
many of the same practices that appear to be central to the federal
investigation,'' the letter read.
   ``We will deal harshly with violators. We stand ready to revise
rules and enforce procedures where necessary.''
   The Chicago Tribune reported today that the FBI paid between $1
million and $2 million to secretly buy three seats on the exchanges,
lease a fourth seat, deposit $200,000 with firms that processed the
agents' trades and stake the agents to trading capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
