<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     01-24 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Post Decline in Mid-January Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales among the nation's Big
Three automakers fell 12.3 percent in mid-January from last year,
when sales and consumer confidence bounced back following the stock
market crash, the companies reported Tuesday.
   Cars and light trucks sold by General Motors Corp., Ford Motor
Co. and Chrysler Corp. dealerships sold at an average daily rate of
27,072 during the Jan. 11-20 period this year, compared with a rate
of 30,867 during the same period last year.
   There were nine selling days in both periods.
   Car sales among the Big Three dropped 17.4 percent, going to a
daily rate of 16,164 during the period this year from a rate of
19,565 in mid-January last year. Trucks made by GM, Ford and
Chrysler sold at 10,908 this year, compared with an 11,302 daily
rate last year, a decline of 3.5 percent.
   During the period last year, consumer confidence was on the
upswing after the Oct. 19, 1987, stock market crash. This year, the
Big Three, with Ford in the lead, began a round of cut-rate
financing with interest rates as low as 4.9 percent on some loans on
a limited number of cars and light trucks.
   The financing or cash-back programs, which cut the total cost of
a car by about the same amount, expire in March.
   So far this year, the Big Three have sold cars at a daily rate of
15,380, down 12.9 percent from the 17,659 daily rate for the first
20 days of January last year. Light truck sales have risen 5.2
percent to a daily rate of 10,520, compared with a rate of 9,999
during the same time last year.
   There were 16 sales days in the Jan. 1-20 periods both years.
   GM suffered the biggest year-to-year hit during the 10-day
period, as its car sales tumbled 21.9 percent to a 7,861 daily rate
this year from the daily rate of 10,066 during mid-January of last
year. GM's light trucks sold at a 4,306 daily rate, compared with a
rate of 4,488 rate during the same time last year, down 4 percent.
   Ford reported its cars sold at a daily rate of 5,842 during the
period this year, compared with a rate of 6,766 last year, a
decrease of 13.6 percent. Trucks made by Ford sold at a rate of
3,968 during mid-January this year, down 5.5 percent from a rate of
4,202 last year.
   Cars sales by Chrysler dropped 10 percent during mid-January this
year, going to a daily rate of 2,462 this year from a rate of 2,736
last year. Light trucks sold at a daily rate of 2,634 this year, up
0.8 percent from the 2,613 rate during the period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890124-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1404EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Brokers     01-24 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokers,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shearson Posts Lower Earnings; Morgan Stanley Reports Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc. said Tuesday
it narrowed its fourth-quarter loss over a year earlier, while
Morgan Stanley Group Inc. reported a sharp jump in earnings.
   Both brokerage firms made a profit for all of 1988, although
Shearson said annual earnings fell slightly due partly to continued
expenses from the acquisition of E.F. Hutton Inc. in January 1988.
   Shearson said that for the three months ended Dec. 31 it lost
$13.5 million, compared with a loss of $95 million in the 1987
period. Revenue, though, shot up 63 percent to $2.9 billion from
$1.8 billion, reflecting the Hutton merger.
   Earnings in 1988 were restated to correct an overstatement in
income from Shearson's wholly-owned subsidiary, Boston Co.
   For the year, earnings totaled $96 million, or 81 cents a share,
down 5 percent from $101 million, or $1 a share, in 1987.Annual
revenue totaled $10.5 billion, up 56 percent from $6.7 billionin the
previous year.
   Morgan Stanley said its fourth-quarter net income rose to $108.3
million, or $4.25 a share, from $31.4 million, or $1.16 a share, in
1987. Revenue also rose, to $594.9 million from $339.5 million.
   For the year, earnings totaled $394.6 million, or $15.39 a share,
on revenue of $2.2 billion. That compared with net income of $230.9
million, or $8.99 a share, in 1987 and $1.8 billion in revenue.
   The October 1987 stock market crash had affected the results of
both Shearson and Mortan Stanley, as it had with other brokerage
firms that year.
   But Shearson noted that it also took a $77 million pre-tax charge
in 1987 related to the underwriting of part of British Petroleum Co.
PLC's disappointing $2.5 billion public stock offering, which had
taken place in the wake of the market collapse.
   Shearson blamed the decline in 1988 earnings on lower investor
participation in the financial markets, $165 million in expenses
associated with the Hutton merger and a $100 million pre-tax
write-down of MCorp securities held by the firm.
   Chairman Peter A. Cohen said, ``While we forsee a continuation of
a difficult enviornment in the financial markets, we are optimistic
for the year ahead. We will continue to be diligent in cutting costs
and reducing staffing levels ...''
   Morgan Stanley Chairman S. Parker Gilbert and President Richard
B. Fisher attributed their company's improved results to favorable
performances in equity and fixed-income divisions despite ``often
sluggish markets in the United States and Europe.''
   ``Important contributions were also made by our asset management,
foreign exchange and commodities businesses,'' they said in a joint
statement.
</TEXT>
