<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1423EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AutoDealers-Mood Bjt   01-24 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Dealers-Mood, Bjt,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dealers: Digging In On The Front-Line of the Car Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automobile dealers are on the front lines of the
car wars, and there's restlessness in the ranks.
   Many dealers say manufacturers are not doing enough to help them
shoulder the burdens posed in selling cars to increasingly
sophisticated consumers and in the face of growing competition.
   If the incoming president of the National Automobile Dealers
Association has his way, the dealers will be heard.
   ``The dealers have been a whipping boy for the manufacturers long
enough,'' Ron Tonkin said recent in a telephone interview from his
office in Portland, Ore.
   ``We feel very testy about the fact that in 1987, when automakers
were making big profits, dealers' profits were down 12 percent,''
Tonkin said. ``There has got to be some equity in this equation.
   Tonkin said one way of helping dealers might be to someday
require automakers to pay for space on dealership floors, much like
food and beverage makers pay for shelf space at the supermarket.
   Tonkin takes office Jan. 31 at the end of the NADA convention in
New Orleans.
   Scott LeFever, general manager of Northtowne Lincoln-Mercury in
Kansas City, Mo., also thinks manufacturers need to do more to aid
dealers, such as improving sales training.
   ``I don't think the training they're offering is targeted to the
real-life situation,'' LeFever said. ``It's what they would like to
believe what happens in the sale. They think the sale can go down by
being (only) honest and truthful.
   ``The people can adore you but they buy from you only because of
the price,'' he said.
   Dealers contacted in a spot check around the nation indicated
they believe customers are more knowledgeable than they were five
years ago about what they plan to buy and more sophisticated about
ways of financing the purchase.
   ``We've found some of them that come in that know more about a
product than some of our salespeople,'' said Doug Moreland, owner of
Cherry Creek Dodge in Aurora, Colo. ``They seem more sure in their
mind of what they're looking for. They want a lot more.''
   Additionally, the flurry of information available about car
features, options and available financing deals puts a bigger burden
on a salesperson to cut through the mass of information, said
Tonkin, a ``megadealer'' who owns 10 dealerships selling 14 makes of
cars and light trucks.
   ``If the (sales) person doesn't sell the customer the first time,
the chances of selling a subsequent time is very, very poor,'' he
said. ``There is so much product out there.''
   Competition poses another challenge, as the growing number of
foreign car dealers become increasingly willing to strike deals and
bargain with customers, a practice rarely seen in years past.
   Import sellers have been more willing to play the car-selling
game by traditional American rules as design and engineering of
domestic and imported cars become closer and as the number of
imported car dealers grows.
   ``Some of our import competitors are finding out that they've got
to get down and work to make a deal,'' Moreland said. ``They're not
used to doing what we have to do.''
   Bob Smith, owner of Bob Smith Audi-Volkswagen-Porsche of
Hollywood, Calif., has been in the car business for 52 years.
Recently, there have been bad times for Audi business, and he points
to what he calls disappointing dealership-manufacturer relationships
as a cause.
   ``They've got a lot of financially poor dealers...'' Smith said.
``They should buy them, but they are just going to sit there and let
us go down the drain.''
   Audi sales slumped sharply last year, falling to a daily sales
rate of 22,943 cars from 41,322 in 1987.
   Company spokesman Joe Bennett said Audi dealers already have
access to dealer, salesperson and sales manager incentives, which
can be passed along to customers to help boost sales. He said there
are no plans for the company to buy any of the 390 Audi dealerships,
down from 402 a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
