<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Phone     01-24 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Phone,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Telesis Group Reports Jump In Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pacific Telesis Group on Tuesday said its fourth-quarter earnings
rose 66 percent, completing a year that was the best since the phone
company was formed in the 1984 breakup of the Bell System.
   The San Francisco-based regional Bell holding company said
quarterly earnings were $249 million, or 59 cents per share,
compared with $150 million, or 35 cents per share, a year earlier.
Revenue for the final quarter was $768 million, down from $771
million the previous year.
   Excluding special items from both 1988 and 1987, fourth-quarter
earnings were essentially flat, Pacific Telesis said.
   For all of 1988, Pacific Telesis said its earnings rose 25
percent to $1.19 billion, or $2.81 a share, from $950 million, or
$2.21 a share, a year earlier. Revenue fell to $3.04 billion from
$3.06 billion.
   The company cited cellular operations as a major source of growth
in the future.
   ``This has been a banner year for us, the best since
divestiture,'' Sam Ginn, Pacific Telesis chairman and chief exective
officer, said in a statement.
   Both annual and fourth-quarter results for 1987 included one-time
charges for an early retirement program and the restructuring of
PacTel Communications Cos., the company said.
   The 1987 year-end results also included the retroactive impact of
a California Public Utilities Commission decision on Pacific Bell's
1986 rates, the company said.
   Ginn also said the corporation took a charge of about $16 million
to fourth-quarter net income for restructuring and costs associated
with disposing of discontinued operations.
   Pacific Telesis's cellular and paging operations reported net
income of $16.6 million on revenues of $381.1 million during 1988.
In 1987, those operations posted earnings of $5.7 million on
revenues of $270.1 million.
   ``Cellular has experienced explosive growth since we began
acquiring properties in 1985 and 1986,'' Ginn said. ``This is a
critical source of growth for us in the future.''
</TEXT>
