   Stocks staged a strong advance on Wall Street
today as investors saw a brighter outlook for interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials surged 35.18 points
higher to 2,253.57 as of 2 p.m. EST.
   Advancing issues held a better than 2-to-1 margin over decliners,
with 938 stocks rising, 449 declining and 525 unchanged on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 133.88 million shares at
midafternoon.
   The market resumed an upward course following Monday's 17-point
drop in the Dow Jones industrial average as the dollar and bond
prices also rose.
   Jack Barbanel, an analyst with Gruntal &amp; Co., said the markets
were reassured by comments by Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan that indicated he was satisfied with Fed policy on
interest rates.
   The markets believed that meant there would not be further
tightening of credit, Barbanel said.
   There also was a feeling in the markets that President Bush was
taking ``the right steps to develop a dialogue with congressional
leaders in terms of the budget deficit,'' Barbanel said.
   The analyst warned, however, that it remained to be seen if Wall
Street's sharp gains could hold up over the next few days. He called
the market ``slightly overbought.''
   The most actively-traded issue on the NYSE was AT&amp;T, up ~ to 30].
   GAF rose 1{ to 50}. The company scheduled a Feb. 22 annual
meeting at which shareholders will vote on the proposed $53-a-share
cash and securities buyout led by Samuel J. Heyman, the firm's
chairman and chief executive.
   Merck rose 1{ to 62[ as investors reacted favorably to the
company's fourth-quarter earnings.
   Among other gainers, IBM was up 1| to 124. Morgan Stanley rose 1\
to 89} after announcing a stock split and dividend increase.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
1.75 to 161.88. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index rose 0.50 to 318.53.
