<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-PersonalFile-Antoci Adv27   01-24 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Antoci, Adv 27,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Friday Jan. 27 and thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>New CEO Antoci Burnishes New Image of Thrift in Federal Rescue</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few days after Mario Antoci took the helm at
American Savings, he was asked to approve advertisements for a new
6-month certificate of deposit paying an attractive interest rate.
   The new chief executive balked at the thought of what the offer
would cost the savings and loan, which had just been rescued from
insolvency by the federal government.
   But in the end he let the ads go _ after first cutting the rate a
bit to a still-competitive 8.25 percent and inserting the words
``limited offer'' in the ad copy.
   Antoci uses the story to describe the tightrope walk he must
execute as head of what used to be the single biggest insolvent
savings and loan in the nation.
   He must bring interest rates down from inflated levels that the
struggling thrift used to attract desperately needed deposits, but
not so low as to chase away the loyal customers who have stuck with
American through years of travail.
   At the same time, he must convey the idea the new American
Savings, bought by corporate takeover strategist Robert M. Bass and
backed by $1.7 billion in federal promissory notes, really is a new,
solid and conservative institution.
   ``American Savings is a new company _ with a 104-year-old
tradition _ but a new company with a new direction,'' Antoci, 54,
said in a get-acquainted session with reporters earlier this month.
   American, based in Stockton, Calif., was formerly the nation's
second-biggest S&amp;L. It was seized by the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board last year and turned over to the Bass Group of Fort Worth at
year's end in exchange for a $350 million cash infusion.
   The government assumed responsibility for the bad assets _ a huge
portfolio of foreclosed real estate loans and mortgage-backed
securities earning below-market interest rates _ and promised
financial backing.
   The good assets, which at $15 billion are less that half of what
American used to be worth on paper, are the property of the
recapitalized American Savings, a subsidiary of a new,
Bass-controlled private holding company called New American Holdings
Inc.
   American's performance under its new management will be watched
as a key test of the government's controversial handling of the
nation's S&amp;L crisis.
   The sales of some badly managed bankrupt institutions to
financial sharpies such as Bass for what some lawmakers considered
fire-sale prices have incited widespread criticism in Congress.
   Antoci, hired away from the No. 2 job at Los Angeles-based H. F.
Ahmanson &amp; Co, the parent of Home Savings of America, the nation's
biggest thrift, is chairman and chief executive officer of both the
Bass-owned holding company and the S&amp;L.
   He told reporters that the Bass organization's move to hire him
reflected its commitment to the thrift's long-term health.
   Asked about speculation that Bass would sell American in a couple
of years, Antoci quoted him as saying, ``This is a keeper.''
   Rival thrift executives say Antoci was a good choice for Bass if
he's interested in re-establishing American as a conservative,
traditionally run thrift. Though he isn't widely known on a personal
basis, Antoci's reputation is as a solid numbers man who embraces
Home Savings' conservative strategy of emphasizing single-family
home lending.
   Antoci frequently invokes the Home Savings name and philosophy,
and the vision of the new American Savings he painted for reporters
is a near mirror image of Home: He'll concentrate on investing in
single-family mortgages, the meat and potatoes of the traditional
thrift.
   Ninety percent of those mortgages, he said, will be six-month
adjustable-rate loans, which protect the thrift from interest rate
swings.
   Antoci's appointment ``sends a signal that the institution is
going to be run in a conservative and traditional fashion,'' says
Bob Adelizzi, president of San Diego-based Home Federal Savings &amp;
Loan.
   He's described as a hard worker but an informal boss _ most of
his former co-workers call him Mario.
   A scuba diver and avid boater, he keeps his 58-foot motor yacht
moored off the back yard of his house on Huntington Harbor, an
Orange County suburb south of Los Angeles.
   Though outgoing in social settings, he says he doesn't intend to
become a high-profile public spokesman in American advertising.
   Rather, Antoci says he's content to let a 1950s-themed ad
campaign dress up his message, that American will offer competitive
rates and attentive service.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Friday Jan. 27.</NOTE>
