<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FrenchScandal-US     01-24 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-French Scandal-US,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Requests Swiss Help In French Insider Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States formally asked
Switzerland Tuesday to freeze accounts at four banks cited by U.S.
officials in an insider trading probe that has caused a political
scandal in France.
   The accounts are believed linked to alleged stock market
manipulation in the takeover of U.S.-based Triangle Industries Inc.
by the French state-owned industrial company Pechiney SA.
   The accounts were provisionally blocked Dec. 19. At that time,
Swiss authorities acted on a request for judicial assistance from
the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The formal demand lists detailed allegations, including
U.S.-compiled evidence of criminal acts, a Swiss justice ministry
spokeswoman said.
   Under a U.S.-Swiss treaty, judicial assistance can be granted
only if the alleged offenses fall under the criminal code in both
countries.
   The banks cited by the U.S. investigators are Union Bank of
Switzerland, Banque Cantonale Vaudoise, Schweizerische Volksbank and
Banca Della Svizzera Italiana. Accounts in the banks allegedly were
used to steer part of the takeover transactions on the New York
stock market.
   Top aides of French President Francois Mitterrand have been
implicated in the affair. Alain Boublil, chief of staff of the
French Finance Ministry, resigned last week, though he denied buying
shares on inside information.
   The SEC alerted French authorities after noting abnormally heavy
purchases of Triangle shares in the week before Pechiney publicly
launched its successful takeover bid Nov. 21.
   Pechiney bought Triangle, the former parent of American National
Can Corp., for $56 a share, nearly six times the value a week
earlier.
   French authorities have not yet asked Switzerland for judicial
assistance.
   Under the decentralized Swiss judicial system, implementation of
the formal U.S. request and subsequent possible moves like the
lifting of bank secrecey and handover of records are up to
authorities in each canton, or state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
