<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-MartinMarietta     01-24 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Martin Marietta,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quarterly Net Cut By Reserve For Commercial Titan Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Corp. Tuesday said its
income fell about 60 percent in the fourth quarter reflecting
establishment of a reserve to compensate for increasing competition
in commercial satellite launching.
   But, for all of last year the company reported a 55.6 percent
increase in profit, record sales and an all-time high of backlogged
orders.
   ``The year's results attest to the vitality and strong earning
power of our core busineses and give us renewed confidence of solid
future earnings progress,'' said Norman R. Augustine, chairman and
chief executive.
   The company said after-tax earnings came to $23.7 million, or 45
cents a share, in the three months ended Dec. 31, down from $59.4
million, or $1.12 a share, in the corresponding 1987 quarter. Fourth
quarter sales totaled $1.5 billion, compared to $1.3 billion for
1987's fourth quarter.
   In 1988, Martin Marietta's profit totaled $358.9 million, or
$6.75 per share, compared with $230.7 million, or $4.25, per share
in 1987. The record sales amount was $5.7 billion, up from 1987's
$5.1 billion and the backlog of undelivered orders amounted to $11.2
billion vs. $10.8 billion in 1987.
   Earnings for 1988 included a fourth quarter reserve of $90
million, or $1.05 per share, to put the Commercial Titan launch
program ``on a more conservative footing,'' the company said. The
reserve was more than offset for the year's results by a $2.25 per
share from the third quarter sale of Hoskyns Group plc, a British
data systems subsidiary.
   The reserve for the Titan program reflects prospective revenues,
costs, and demand for commercial launch vehicles. Titan equipment is
used in the launch of commercial and military communications
satellites.
   ``It was considered a prudent action in view of current industry
pricing following the recent entry into the world market of the
Chinese Long March launch vehicle,'' the company statement said.
</TEXT>
