<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Higher After Late-Day Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rallied Tuesday in late trading on the
London Stock Exchange to close at the day's best level and to set
yet another post-crash record high.
   At the close of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 16.4 points, or 0.9 percent, at 1,941.1.
   Trading was still brisk, but much reduced from its recent active
pace, as many institutional investors stepped back from the market
ahead of Friday's scheduled release of British trade figures for
December.
   Volume slackened to 562.8 million shares from 649.9 million on
Monday and more than 900 million last Friday.
   ``People are wary the market has gone up so quickly. They have
backed off a little bit, but there's still no sign people are
wanting to pull out. It's just a question of whether they'll put
more money in,'' one equity salesman said.
   After a rise of nearly 150 points, or 8.3 percent, in the
100-share index since the start of the year, market-makers initially
marked prices lower Tuesday in expectation of a decline. This was
quickly reversed, however, as fresh buying ensued from several large
institutional programs.
   Shares took off again in late afternoon, rallying in sympathy
with an early surge on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 11.2 points at 1,580.7
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 8.96 points
to close at 1,092.99.
</TEXT>
