<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Higher; Wheat Futures Sink</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of soybeans and corn climbed higher
while wheat futures sank at the close of trading Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybeans advanced more than 11 cents for the March spot contract.
   ``A rumor that the Russians bought 600,000 tons of meal from
Brazil or the United States supported the beans, and corn went along
for the ride,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Weighing on wheat prices were a forecast of rain in the Great
Plains growing area and talk that Secretary of Agriculture-designate
Clayton Yeutter ``isn't too keen on export bonuses,'' Lespinasse
said.
   Corn's rally was shortened by reports of a new USDA catalog of
corn due out next week that would provide an avenue for more spot
sales, analsysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 6 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.38} a bushel; corn was 2} cents
to 3} cents higher with March at $2.73 a bushel; oats were unchanged
to 1 cent lower with March at $2.36 a bushel; and soybeans were 4{
cents to 11{ cents higher with March at $7.65 a bushel.
