<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     01-24 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0222</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices rose sharply on Wall Street today, as
investor optimism about interest rates carried the stock market past
the level where it stood before the October 1987 crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 38.04 to 2,256.43.
It was the first time the widely-followed index had closed above
2,246.74, where it finished on Oct. 16, 1987, the last trading day
before the market collapse.
   Wall Street was carried higher today by optimism about interest
rates and by its own recent strength.
   Jack Barbanel, an analyst with Gruntal &amp; Co., said the markets
were reassured by comments by Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan that indicated he was satisfied with Fed policy on
interest rates.
   The markets believed that meant there would not be further
tightening of credit, Barbanel said.
   There also was a feeling among traders that President Bush was
taking ``the right steps to develop a dialogue with congressional
leaders in terms of the budget deficit,'' Barbanel said.
   Alfred E. Goldman, an analyst with A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc. in
St. Louis, said today's price surge fed on itself, as investors on
the sideline jumped into the market for fear they would miss the
latest rally.
</TEXT>
