<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1942EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-UnionPacific     01-24 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Union Pacific,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Pacific Reports 34 Percent Quarterly Earnings Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Pacific Corp. Tuesday reported a 34
percent fourth-quarter profit gain and a 32 percent gain in income
from continuing operations in the final quarter of 1988, a year in
which the parent of Union Pacific Railroad completed a major portion
of its restructuring.
   In the three months ended Dec. 31, the corporation had after-tax
earnings of $187.4 million, or $1.65 a share, up from $139.8
million, or $1.23 a share, during Oct.-Dec. 1987.
   Earnings from continuing operations totaled $156 million, which
came to $1.38 a share. The comparable 1987 figures were $118.4
million and $1.03.
   Revenue in the quarter came to $1.58 billion, up from $1.38
billion in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   For all of last year, Union Pacific reported net income of $643.9
million, or $5.65 a share, and revenue of $6.07 billion, up from
$582.9 million, or $5.10 a share, and $5.35 billion in 1987.
   Last year's earnings from continuing operations were $558.7
million, or $4.90 per share, vs. $494.8 million, or $4.32 a share in
1987.
   Drew Lewis, chief executive officer of the corporate parent of
Omaha, Neb.-based Union Pacific Railroad, said ``Strong performances
were achieved in every phase of our business.
   ``We are pleased with the financial results and the strategic
steps we took in 1988 to enhance shareholder value,'' Lewis said.
``If the economy does not weaken and there is not a major energy
price deterioration, we believe 1989 will be another year of strong
earnings.''
   Among the steps taken in 1988 was the withdrawal of Union Pacific
Resources from the refining business.
   A good showing by Union Pacific Railroad contributed to the
corporation's overall earnings growth. Increased traffic,
improvements in productivity and higher prices helped the railroad's
profitability.
   Mike Walsh, chairman of the Omaha-based railroad, said he
expected earnings to continue to improve in 1989.
   ``We've succeeded in getting the railroad growing again after
four years of flat revenues,'' Walsh said in a news release, noting
that 1988 was the third consecutive year in which the railroad
improved profits by at least 15 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
