<DOCNO> AP890124-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DigitalComputers     01-24 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Digital Computers,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Digital Announces New Computers; Admits Miscalculation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. announced new midsize
computers Tuesday, and President Kenneth Olsen admitted the company
had miscalculated how popular the middle of its Vax line would be
compared with its own top-of-the-line models.
   Olsen said its midsize Vax 6200 computers had ``cannibalized''
sales of its 8800 models, which have more powerful processors but
cost more.
   ``It hurt our pride in planning _ embarrassed us,'' Olsen said of
the unexpectedly slow sales of its 8800 models. On the other hand,
he said, the company was pleased with the strong sales of the 6200s.
   Introduced Tuesday was a 6300 series, which Digital said offers
up to 35 percent better performance than the 6200 computers at only
5 percent higher price. The company also announced new data-storage
devices.
   Steve Noyes, engineering manager for Digital's Vax line, said the
8800 series of computers, with its more powerful processors, is
still best for customers who have big jobs that can't be decomposed
into several jobs and distributed among several weaker processors.
   Digital, based in Maynard, Mass., said its new machines, the Vax
6310 up through the Vax 6360, offer from 3.8 times to 22 times the
performance of the Vax 11-780, Digital's first Vax system.
</TEXT>
