<DOCNO> AP890124-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1707EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     01-24 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound From Selloff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rebounded from the selloff at
the start of the week as traders Tuesday turned their attention to
an upcoming meeting between OPEC and non-OPEC nations.
   Still, the price of crude oil, which broke the $19-a-barrel level
this month, remained well below $18 a barrel during the trading
session, and some analysts said it appeared doubtful that prices
would return to those higher levels any time soon.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate _ the benchmark grade of U.S. crude _ rose 21
cents to finish at $17.54 a barrel.
   The contract had fallen $1.06 on Monday in what some analysts
called an expected ``correction'' following a recent strong rally
fueled by confidence in OPEC's production-cutting pact.
   Among refined petroleum contracts traded on the exchange,
February home heating oil settled 0.64 cent higher at 50.87 cents a
gallon, after losing 2.10 cents on Monday.
   The February contract for unleaded gasoline, which declined 2.08
cents in Monday's session, settled at 50.45 cents a gallon, up 1.03
cents.
   ``Right now the market is a little confused as to whether
yesterday's decline was the beginning of a sharp movement downward
or just a correction,'' said Andrew Lebow, senior analyst with
E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   ``I think it was overdone, and I think (Tuesday) we just had a
rebound off yesterday,'' he said.
   Chris McCormack, an energy analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., agreed, but wasn't too bullish about the direction of prices
in the near future.
   ``I think the market pretty much has discounted all the bullish
news,'' McCormack said. ``I don't think crude is sustainable at
$19.''
   Analysts note that since early October, West Texas Intermediate
had risen more than $7 on optimism that the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries would significantly cut its output to
help shore up sagging worldwide prices.
   A daily quota of 18.5 million barrels went into effect Jan. 1,
and traders said there were indications that OPEC was sticking to
that level.
   Analysts said traders were now turning their attention to
Thursday's scheduled meeting in London between OPEC and non-OPEC
nations.
   ``I think the market feels that something positive could come out
of that meeting,'' said McCormack.
</TEXT>
