<FIRST>u f AM-ComputerContract     01-24 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Contract,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Board Refuses to Disturb Contract Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government appeals board Tuesday refused to
disturb a contract that has been called the computer deal of the
century, denying a challenge by Honeywell Federal Systems Inc. to
last fall's award to the American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
   The contract at issue is expected to total more than $1 billion.
   The Board of Contract Appeals of the General Services
Administration ``has issued an opinion today denying the protest of
Honeywell,'' said Judge Vincent LaBella, who chaired the three-judge
panel that considered the matter.
   ``The board proposes to release its opinion to the public
Wednesday after providing the parties an opportunity to request any
appropriate (removal) of (proprietary) material that should be
protected from disclosure. But the protest has been denied.''
   Honeywell Federal Systems was one of six competitors that fought
long and hard for the Air Force contract, which was finally awarded
last October to AT&amp;T Technologies Inc., a subsidiary of AT&amp;T.
   The Air Force is acting as the executive agent for the other
armed services, which together are trying to standardize and update
their computer systems. The contract calls for AT&amp;T Technologies to
deliver about 20,000 mini-computers over the next five years.
   ``We're very pleased by this decision,'' Herb Linnen, an AT&amp;T
spokesman in Washington, said Tuesday.
   ``From the start, we believed the Air Force conducted a thorough
and proper evaluation, which clearly supported its decision to award
the contract to AT&amp;T.''
   The Air Force contract to AT&amp;T so far totals $929.1 million, but
company and service officials agree its value could easily exceed $1
billion depending upon what options are exercised.
   The Air Force is buying the computers for its own use as well as
that of the Army, Navy, Coast Guard, Defense Communications Agency
and Defense Logistics Agency. From the moment bids were requested,
the contract had been recognized as being so large it could ensure
the winner a strong position in the highly competitive industry for
years to come.
   Judge LaBella did not offer any explanation of the GSA board's
ruling, noting the opinion would not be released until Wednesday.
One of the main issues, however, involved the Air Force's internal
ranking procedures for bids.
   In its appeal, Honeywell charged it provided the Air Force a
``best and final offer'' that substantially undercut that of AT&amp;T _
$744 million, or $185 million below that of the winner _ while still
passing technical muster.
   The company alleged the Air Force recalculated its bid upward
using internal criteria without informing the company, but even with
that change its bid still was more than $140 million below that of
AT&amp;T.
   Ron Cuneo, vice president and general manager of Honeywell
Federal Systems, said Tuesday he had been informed of the decision
but ``I have not seen the opinion, obviously.''
   ``I'm disappointed, of course, that we lost,'' he continued.
``Somehow, you would think in this budget environment that $140
million would mean something, but apparently not. Generally, I think
the system works. But I'm not sure it did here.''
   Cuneo said it was premature to discuss the possibility of
appealing the board's decision to the courts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
