<FIRST>u f AM-Occidental-NorthSea     01-24 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Occidental-North Sea,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owner of Destroyed Oil Rig Offers $187 Million to Victims' Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of the 167 victims of July's oil rig
explosion in the North Sea have been offered a total of $187 million
in compensation payments, the rig's owner, Occidental Petroleum
Corp., disclosed Tuesday.
   Armand Hammer, chairman and chief executive officer of the Los
Angeles-based oil company, revealed the offers in a meeting with
financial analysts in New York. A summary of Hammer's remarks to the
New York Society of Security Analysts was released by the company's
headquarters.
   Occidental's oil platform Piper Alpha off Aberdeen, Scotland,
exploded and burned July 6. The platform was destroyed and 167 men
were killed.
   Hammer said he believed most of the victims' families would
accept the compensation Occidental has offered them.
   Most of the company's cost will be covered by insurance, he said.
   Oil and gas production from Occidental's Claymore and Scarpa
platforms, which fed through Piper Alpha, will resume by the end of
the first quarter, Hammer said. The company previously had said
production at the fields would resume by the end of 1988.
   Occidental officials previously have estimated lost production
from the disaster would cut year-end profit by between five and 10
cents a share, or $13.2 million to $26.5 million.
</TEXT>
