<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Prime-MAIBasic     01-24 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime-MAI Basic,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Four Asks Court to Drop Injunction to Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc. asked a federal judge Tuesday
to lift a court order blocking a $20-a-share bid for Prime Computer
Inc. and tried to answer questions about the financing of the deal.
   In court documents responding to a judge's concerns, MAI Basic
said Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is confident ofraising $875 million
to finance the takeover despite its guilty plea in a massive
securities fraud settlement in New York.
   U.S. District Court Judge A. David Mazzone last month said MAI
Basic needed to make disclosures about the relationship between
Drexel and New York investor Bennett S. LeBow, who controls MAI
Basic.
   Mazzone also said MAI Basic concealed information concerning past
securities law violations or alleged violations by LeBow and William
Weksel, another principal in the takeover bid.
   MAI Basic, based in Tustin, Calif., said that Drexel since 1986
has been the primary financier for LeBow and certain of his
companies, and owns 7 percent of MAI Basic's common stock.
   If the takeover goes through, the disclosures say, Drexel Burnham
will earn $33 million in financing or advisory fees, may perform
future work worth $22 million in fees and will be allowed to buy
more MAI Basic stock at a discount.
   MAI Basic also said Weksel agreed to turn over $208,000 in
profits made from a separate stock sale as part of a consent decree
with the Securities and Exchange Commission in 1986. LeBow has been
sued in connection with that case but no action has been taken
against him by the SEC, the disclosures said.
   Drexel last month agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay
a record $650 million in fines and restitution to settle the
securities fraud case in U.S. history.
   Natick-based Prime said the financial disclosures do not provide
enough information on the deal and that the company will fight to
keep the court order in place.
   Prime said in a statement that the documents do not adequately
explain how MAI Basic plans to meet federal requirments concerning
using the takeover target's own stock as collateral for loans needed
to finance the deal.
   As of Jan. 19, 70.9 percent of Prime's undiluted outstanding
common stock had been tendered, MAI Basic spokeswoman Toni Lee said.
The company has extended its tender offer until Jan. 30.
   But Prime spokesman Richard Eckel said because of the firm's
convertible debentures _ bonds that the bearers can convert to
common stock _ the tenders represent only about 53 percent of the
total diluted stock.
   One of the conditions of MAI Basic's original tender offer was
that the company control 67 percent of the fully diluted stock,
Eckel said.
   In a related offensive, MAI Basic released a letter to Prime
blasting the company for an ``unnecessary, exorbitantly expensive
and clearly unsuccessful program'' to convince shareholders not to
accept MAI Basic's offer.
   The letter from LeBow points out that a majority of shareholders
have accepted the tender offer and calls on Prime officials to
negotiate.
</TEXT>
