<DOCNO> AP890124-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock 1stLd-Writethru   01-24 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0170,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Rejects Shamrock's $45-a-Share Offer; Proxy Fight Expected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, Polaroid stock ... to UPDATE with closing
stock price. INSERTS two grafs of comments from Shamrock President Stanley
Gold after 8th graf pvs, Shamrock's candidates ... Picks up 8th graf pvs,
Polaroid spokeswoman ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. on Tuesday rejected as
inadequate a $3.2 billion hostile buyout offer from Shamrock
Holdings Inc., setting the stage for a threatened proxy fight for
control of Polaroid.
   Shamrock, a television and radio concern owned by the Roy E.
Disney family, last week increased its offer to $45 per share for
all Polaroid stock, including 9.7 million shares issued under
Polaroid's controversial employee stock ownership plan.
   The previous offer of $2.6 billion, or $42 per share, did not
include the employee shares.
   In a statement, Polaroid called the latest sweetened offer
``inadequate from a financial point of view and not in the best
interest of Polaroid and its stockholders, except Shamrock and its
affiliate.''
   ``Polaroid's board strongly recommends that stockholders reject
the Shamrock offer and not tender any of their shares of common
stock,'' Polaroid stated.
   On Tuesday, Polaroid stock rose 12{ cents a share to $40 on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Tom Reed, a spokesman for Shamrock, said the Burbank,
Calif.-based company would proceed with its plan to nominate a slate
of candidates for election to Polaroid's board at the company's
annual meeting May 9.
   Shamrock's candidates would be committed, if elected, to selling
the company either under Shamrock's offer or to any third party that
made a higher bid.
   Shamrock President Stanley P. Gold said he was disappointed by
Polaroid's rejection of Shamrock's $45 per share offer.
   In a prepared statement issued from Burbank, Gold said: ``We
intend to vigorously pursue our tender offer and our previously
announced plans to wage a proxy contest for control of Polaroid if
our tender offier is not consummated prior to Polaroid's May annual
meeting.''
   Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips declined comment on
Shamrock's proposed proxy challenge.
   Shamrock said when it extended its offer Jan. 19 that about 13.1
million Polaroid shares, or 18.3 percent of the outstanding stock,
had been tendered and not withdrawn.
   Shamrock's tender offer expires March 15, and is contingent on
obtaining at least 90 percent of Polaroid's 71.6 million outstanding
shares.
   Alex Henderson, an analyst with Prudential Bache Inc., said
Polaroid's management could be forced into a leveraged buyout to
thwart Shamrock's takeover attempt.
   ``My guess is that the next time Shamrock is forced to extend its
offer, that the number of tendered shares will probably move up to
close to 25 million,'' he said.
   Henderson said 25 million tendered shares _ amounting to nearly
35 percent of the outstanding shares _ combined with the 6.9 million
he said Shamrock already holds could frighten Polaroid executives
into financing a leveraged buyout to avoid having to sell the
company to Shamrock.
   Polaroid has been resisting Shamrock since last July, when
Shamrock offered $40 per share in a friendly but unsolicited bid.
   Shamrock is appealing a Delaware Chancery Court ruling upholding
the employee stock ownership plan. The Delaware Supreme Court has
scheduled a hearing on the appeal March 16.
   Shamrock contends the employee stock was issued to block a
takeover. If it is invalidated, Shamrock has promised to raise its
offer to $3.36 billion, or $47 per share.
   The stock plan owns about 14 percent of Polaroid's stock. It
makes a takeover extremely difficult because under Delaware law a
hostile suitor must gain at least 85 percent of its target for a
takeover to be allowed. Polaroid is incorporated in Delaware.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
