<FIRST>u f AM-Ashland-Iran     01-24 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ashland-Iran,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ashland Talking With Iran About Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. says its chief executive,
John Hall, has talked with Iranian officials about a possible
out-of-court settlement of the multimillion-dollar lawsuits between
them.
   Hall has met from time to time with Iranian officials for months,
according to Ashland spokesman Roger Schrum. But he said the
negotiations were mostly about Ashland's countersuit.
   Schrum also denied an oil industry trade publication report,
which quoted an Iranian oil official as saying Ashland already had
agreed to pay $283 million to the National Iranian Oil Co.
   Ashland has not agreed to pay principle or interest involving the
Iranian state oil company's claim, Schrum told the Lexington
Herald-Leader on Monday.
   The case is scheduled to go to trial May 15 in U.S. District
Court in Jackson, Miss. A similar but separate lawsuit is winding
its way through Bermuda courts.
   National Iranian Oil has contended that Ashland failed to pay for
$283 million worth of oil the Iranians sent the company in 1979,
after revolutionaries seized power in Iran and took U.S. Embassy
workers hostage in Tehran.
   Jimmy Carter, who was president at the time, imposed a trade
embargo against Iran, apparently during the time between the order
of the oil and its delivery.
   The Iranian oil company has asked for $283 million plus interest,
bringing the amount of its lawsuit to more than $500 million.
   Ashland has countersued the Iranian company for breach of
contract, contending that the Iranians failed to deliver all the oil
Ashland had ordered.
   Ashland's countersuit could amount to more than $500 million.
   Iranian deputy oil minister Kazempur Ardebili, however, said
Ashland had offered to pay the Iranian company the original price of
the oil shipments, according to Platt's Oilgram News.
   Steve Truitt, an attorney for National Iranian Oil in Washington,
D.C., said he was prohibited by law from commenting on the case to
the news media.
   An oil industry analyst said he expected Ashland to negotiate a
settlement with the Iranians.
   ``I've always been convinced that they (Ashland) were going to
settle _ the only question was how,'' said Jack Shaughnessy of
Advest Inc.
   Ashland previously set aside the money to settle with the Iranian
company, Shaughnessy said, and ending the case would clear the decks
of the uncertainty of a trial.
   But Shaughnessy said he would be surprised if Ashland paid the
Iranians as much as $283 million.
   A U.S. District Court judge has ruled that Iranian Oil Minister
Gholamreza Agazadeh must come to the United States to give a
deposition before the trial.
   National Iranian Oil has appealed the ruling requiring Agazadeh's
appearance, said Alex Alston Jr., a Mississippi attorney for the
company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
