<DOCNO> AP890124-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Venezuela-Economy     01-24 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Economy,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuelan President-elect Plans Economic Reform Package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuelan President-elect Carlos
Andres Perez said he plans a series of economic reforms, including
elimination of the two-tiered foreign exchange system.
   Perez, addressing a group of business leaders late Monday, said
the two-tiered exchange system, in operation to allow subsidized
imports of strategic goods, would be eliminated once he takes office
Feb. 2.
   The official exchange rate is 14.50 bolivars to the dollar, while
the free market rate fluctutates between 30 and 40 bolivars to the
dollar.
   Perez did not say whether the bolivar would be allowed to float
according to the market, or whether one single official rate would
be established.
   In the last two days, the bolivar has gained on the dollar on
rumors that the incoming government would establish a single rate of
about 25 bolivars to the dollar, below the current market rate.
   Along with reform of the exchange system, Perez promised to do
away with price controls, reduce government spending and free
interest rates.
   Advisers to Perez earlier this week said the economic reforms
could even include turning over state-run companies to the private
sector, although Perez did not mention this possibility in his
speech to the business leaders.
   Venezuela is currently in the initial phases of talks with the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank in order to receive
fresh funds to back up dollar reserves depleted by a stagnating
economy.
   Critics of the reform package say Perez is giving in to pressures
from the international banking system that will lead to hardships
for the general population, including soaring inflation with the end
of subsidized imports and price controls.
   Perez said his government would not decree an across the board
wage increase, but would mandate a rise in the minimum wage and
implement a ``food basket'' at reduced prices for the poorest
Venezuelans.
</TEXT>
