<DOCNO> AP890124-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-24-89 2134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Oil 2ndLd-Writethru f0236 01-24 1036</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Oil, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0236,1065</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Decline for Exxon, Mobil, Chevron, Sun; Amerada Rebounds
From Loss</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Exxon Corp. ... to include Sun Co. results.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, For the ... INSERTS 3 new grafs after 19th graf
pvs, Chevron Chairman ... to include Sun details. Picks up 20th graf pvs,
Amerada Hess ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Several of the nation's largest petroleum companies said Tuesday
their fourth-quarter profit fell as the erosion of crude prices hurt
oil and gas production, dragging down gains in refining and
marketing.
   Exxon Corp., the nation's largest oil concern, said its profit
plunged 11 percent, while Chevron's earnings were down 25 percent,
Mobil's declined slightly and Sun Co.'s profit fell 8 percent.
Separately, Amerada Hess Corp. said its earnings rebounded after a
loss in the 1987 quarter.
   For the three-month period ended Dec. 31, Exxon's net income fell
to $1.4 billion, or $1.06 a share, from $1.6 billion, or $1.12 a
share in the comparable 1987 period.
   No. 2-ranked Mobil said earnings declined 1 percent in the latest
quarter to $469 million, or $1.14 a share, from $474 million, or
$1.15 a share in the year-earlier period.
   Chevron's net income totaled $175 million, or 51 cents a share,
from $234 million, or 68 cents a share in the year-earlier quarter,
while Amerada Hess reported net income of $66 million, or 80 cents a
share.
   Analysts said that after several quarters of rising earnings, oil
companies failed to withstand the steady drop in petroleum prices
that occured throughout most of 1988.
   ``With the decline in crude prices last year versus a year ago,
(the companies) just weren't able to offset it from stronger
refining and marketing,'' said Thomas C. Lewis, an analyst with Duff
&amp; Phelps Corp., a Chicago investment concern.
   However, industry experts said Tuesday that steadily rising oil
prices in 1989 could improve exploration and production performance
in the first quarter, but won't necessarily lower margins in
refining because of recent improvements in that segment of the
business.
   New York-based Exxon said fourth-quarter revenue remained nearly
unchanged at $22 billion vs. a year earlier.
   Exxon said earnings for all of 1988 rose 9 percent to $5.3
billion, or $3.95 a share, from $4.8 billion, or $3.43 a share, in
1987. Sales for 1988 rose 5 percent to $87.5 billion from $83.3
billion in 1987.
   The company said earnings from refining, marketing and chemicals
operations continued strong in the fourth quarter due to ``lower
crude oil acquisition costs and relatively firm product prices.''
   But weak crude prices resulted in sharply lower earnings from
exploration and production despite an increase in output, Exxon
Chairman L.G. Rawl said. In the fourth quarter alone, Exxon's U.S.
production earnings plunged 57 percent to $144 million from $335
million in the 1987 period, and for all of 1988, they fell 37
percent to $829 million from $1.2 billion, the company said.
   Mobil, also based in New York, said fourth-quarter revenue
declined 2 percent to $13.9 billion from $14.2 billion in the
year-earlier period.
   For all of 1988, Mobil earnings rose 55 percent to $2.1 billion,
or $5.09 a share, from $1.3 billion, or $3.28 a share, in 1987.
Revenue rose 7 percent to $54.9 billion, from $51.4 billion in 1987.
   Mobil Chairman Allen E. Murray attributed the company's yearly
gain to improved profit margins in refining and marketing due to
strong worldwide demand and improved margins in Europe, Japan and
other areas. A record performance by Mobil's chemicals unit _ helped
by tight supply and strong demand _ also contributed.
   But Mobil's exploration and production results also were
adversely affected by a 19 percent drop in crude oil prices during
the year and higher exploration expenses, Murray said. For the
fourth quarter, exploration and production results declined $210
million and for the year they fell $389 million, he said.
   San Francisco-based Chevron said its revenue declined 7 percent
to $6.9 billion from $7.4 billion in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   For the year, Chevron's earnings rose 41 percent to $1.8 billion,
or $5.17 a share, from $1.3 billion, or $3.65 a share in 1987. Its
revenue declined slightly to $28.9 billion from $29.1 billion the
year before.
   Chevron Chairman Ken Derr said the company's 1988 earnings
rebounded with the help of a strong refining and marketing segment
and low crude prices. But those same weak oil prices contributed to
Chevron's fourth-quarter loss of $64 million in its oil and gas
production unit.
   Sun, based in Radnor, Pa., said its profit for the fourth quarter
fell to $76 million, or 72 cents a share, compared with $83 million,
or 77 cents a share, a year earlier. Fourth-quarter revenue rose 4.2
percent to $2.72 billion from $2.61 billion a year earlier.
   For the year, Sun's profit plunged to $7 million, or 6 cents a
share, from $348 million, or $3.21 a share, in 1987. The latest
results reflected an afte-tax charge of $297 million in the second
quarter for a writedown in assets intended for sale and related
costs.
   Revenue for the year edged up to $10 billion from $9.82 billion
in 1987.
   Amerada Hess said its net income totaled $66 million in the
fourth quarter, or 80 cents a share, compared with a net loss of
$79.6 million, or a minus 93 cents a share, for the same period in
1987. Revenue totaled $1.2 billion, compared with $1.8 billion for
the year-year period.
   The New York-based company said its fourth quarter results
include a charge of $30 million for capitalized exploration expenses
related to certain of its undeveloped properties. Its 1987 results
reflected non-recurring income of $73 million, resulting from
reductions or refunds of foreign taxes.
   Amerada said its refining and marketing earnings were $90.1
million compared with a loss of $195 million in the 1987 quarter,
reflecting writedowns of crude oil and refined product inventory
values.
   However, the company's exploration and production operations lost
$300,000 in the latest quarter, including similar crude oil
writedowns.
   For all of 1988, net income totaled $124 million, or $1.51 a
share, down more than 40 percent from 1987. Revenue amounted to $4.3
billion compared with $4.8 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
